window.EXAM_DATA = (window.EXAM_DATA || []).concat([{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2010","year":"2010","title":"2010 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2010 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2010 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nThe longest bull run in a century of art-market history <font color=\"#ffff00\">ended on a</font> dramatic <font color=\"#ffff00\">note</font> with a sale of 56 works by Damien Hirst, Beautiful Inside My Head Forever, at Sotheby’s in London on September 15th 2008.\n翻译: <u>艺术市场一个世纪历史中最长的牛市，以一种戏剧性的方式结束：2008年9月15日，达米恩·赫斯特的一场名为“Beautiful Inside My Head Forever”的56件作品拍卖会在伦敦苏富比举行。</u>\n\n-**end on a … note**：<u>以……方式/氛围结束。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">All but two</font> pieces sold, <font color=\"#ffff00\">fetching</font> more than £70m, a record for a sale by a single artist.\n翻译: <u>除两件作品外，其余全部售出，成交额超过7000万英镑，创下单个艺术家作品拍卖的纪录。</u>\n\n-**All but two**：<u>除了两个之外全部。</u>\n-**but**：<u>这里 but 不是“但是”，而是“除了”</u>\n-**fetch**：<u>售得、卖得；在拍卖语境里，fetch 常表示“卖出某价格”</u>\n\n---\n\nIt was a last victory.\n翻译: <u>这是最后一次胜利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs the auctioneer called out bids, in New York one of the oldest banks on Wall Street, Lehman Brothers, filed for bankruptcy.\n翻译: <u>就在拍卖师喊出竞价时，在纽约，华尔街最古老的银行之一雷曼兄弟申请破产。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe world art market had already been losing momentum for a while after rising <font color=\"#ffff00\">bewilderingly</font> since 2003.\n翻译: <u>自2003年以来令人眼花缭乱地上涨之后，全球艺术市场此前已经有一段时间在失去势头。</u>\n\n-**bewilderingly**：<u>令人困惑地、令人眼花缭乱地。</u>\n\n---\n\nAt its peak in 2007 it was worth <font color=\"#ffff00\">some</font> $65 billion, reckons Clare McAndrew, founder of Arts Economics, a research firm – double the figure five years earlier.\n翻译: <u>研究公司Arts Economics的创始人克莱尔·麦克安德鲁估算，艺术市场在2007年达到顶峰时价值约650亿美元，是五年前数字的两倍。</u>\n\n-**some**：<u>在数字前表示“大约”。</u>\n\n---\n\nSince then it may have come down to $50 billion.\n翻译: <u>从那以后，它可能已经降至500亿美元。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the market generates interest far beyond its size because it <font color=\"#ffff00\">brings together</font> great wealth, <font color=\"#ffff00\">enormous egos</font>, greed, passion and controversy <font color=\"#ffff00\">in a way</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">matched by few other industries</font>.\n翻译: <u>但这个市场引发的关注远远超出其规模，因为它以少有其他行业能比的方式，将巨额财富、极度膨胀的自我、贪婪、激情和争议汇集在一起。</u>\n\n-**bring together**：<u>汇集。</u>\n-**enormous egos**：<u>极强的自我意识 / 巨大的自负。</u>\n-**in a way**：<u>以一种方式。</u>\n-**matched by few other industries**：<u>很少有其他行业能匹敌。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the weeks and months that followed Mr. Hirst’s sale, <font color=\"#ffff00\">spending of any sort</font> became deeply unfashionable.\n翻译: <u>在赫斯特先生那场拍卖之后的几周和几个月里，任何形式的消费都变得极不合时宜。</u>\n\n-**spending of any sort**：<u>任何种类的花钱。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the art world that meant collectors stayed away from galleries and salerooms.\n翻译: <u>在艺术界，这意味着收藏家远离画廊和拍卖场。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSales of contemporary art fell by two-thirds, and in the most <font color=\"#ffff00\">overheated sector</font>, they were down by nearly 90% in the year to November 2008.\n翻译: <u>当代艺术销售额下降了三分之二；而在最过热的领域，截至2008年11月的一年里，销售额下降了近90%。</u>\n\n-**overheated sector**：<u>过热板块。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Within weeks</font> the world’s two biggest auction houses, Sotheby’s and Christie’s, had to pay out nearly $200m in guarantees to clients who <font color=\"#ffff00\">had placed works for sale with them</font>.\n翻译: <u>几周之内，全球两大拍卖行苏富比和佳士得不得不向那些委托它们出售作品的客户支付近2亿美元的担保款。</u>\n\n-**within weeks**：<u>在几周内。</u>\n-**had placed works for sale with them**：<u>此前把作品委托给它们出售。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe current downturn in the art market is the worst since the Japanese stopped buying Impressionists at the end of 1989.\n翻译: <u>当前艺术市场的低迷，是自1989年底日本人停止购买印象派作品以来最严重的一次。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis time experts reckon that prices are about 40% down on their peak on average, though some have been far more <font color=\"#ffff00\">fluctuant</font>.\n翻译: <u>专家估计，这一次价格平均比峰值下跌了约40%，尽管有些价格波动要大得多。</u>\n\n-**fluctuant**：<u>波动的、不稳定的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">But</font> Edward Dolman, Christie’s chief executive, says: “I’m pretty confident we’re at the bottom.”\n翻译: <u>但佳士得首席执行官爱德华·多尔曼说：“我相当有信心，我们已经处在底部。”</u>\n\n-**But**：<u>但是；前文说市场下跌严重；这里引入一个相对乐观的声音</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat makes this slump different from <font color=\"#ffff00\">the last</font>, he says, is that there are still buyers in the market.\n翻译: <u>他说，使这次低迷不同于上一次的是，市场上仍然有买家。</u>\n\n-**the last**：<u>上一次低迷，指 1989 年日本退出后的那轮艺术市场下跌。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlmost everyone who was interviewed for this special report said that the biggest problem at the moment is not a lack of demand but a lack of good work to sell.\n翻译: <u>几乎所有接受这份特别报道采访的人都说，目前最大的问题不是缺乏需求，而是缺乏可出售的优秀作品。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The three Ds</font> – death, debt and divorce – still deliver works of art to the market.\n翻译: <u>三大D，即死亡、债务和离婚，仍然会把艺术品带入市场。</u>\n\n-**The three Ds**：<u>三个以 D 开头的词。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut anyone who does not have to sell is <font color=\"#ffff00\">keeping away</font>, waiting for confidence to return.\n翻译: <u>但任何并非不得不出售的人都在回避市场，等待信心恢复。</u>\n\n-**keep away**：<u>远离、不参与。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nI was addressing a small gathering in a suburban Virginia living room – a women’s group that had invited men to join them.\n翻译: <u>我当时正在弗吉尼亚郊区一间客厅里对一个小型聚会讲话，那是一个女性团体，她们也邀请了男性参加。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThroughout the evening, one man had been particularly talkative, frequently offering ideas and anecdotes, while his wife sat silently beside him on the couch.\n翻译: <u>整个晚上，有一名男子尤其健谈，频繁提出想法和讲述轶事，而他的妻子则静静地坐在他身旁的沙发上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nToward the end of the evening, I commented that women frequently complain that their husbands don’t talk to them.\n翻译: <u>临近晚上结束时，我评论说，女性经常抱怨她们的丈夫不和她们说话。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis man quickly nodded in agreement.\n翻译: <u>这名男子立刻点头表示同意。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHe gestured toward his wife and said, “She’s the talker in our family.”\n翻译: <u>他朝妻子做了个手势，说：“在我们家，她才是爱说话的人。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe room burst into laughter; the man looked puzzled and hurt.\n翻译: <u>房间里爆发出笑声；那名男子显得困惑而受伤。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It’s true,” he explained.\n翻译: <u>“这是真的，”他解释说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“When I come home from work I have nothing to say.\n翻译: <u>“我下班回家时没什么可说的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIf she didn’t keep the conversation going, we’d spend the whole evening in silence.”\n翻译: <u>如果不是她维持谈话，我们整个晚上都会在沉默中度过。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis episode crystallizes the irony that although American men tend to talk more than women in public situations, they often talk less at home.\n翻译: <u>这一插曲清楚地体现出一种讽刺：尽管美国男性在公共场合往往比女性说得更多，但他们在家里却常常说得更少。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd this pattern is wreaking havoc with marriage.\n翻译: <u>而这种模式正在对婚姻造成严重破坏。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe pattern was observed by political scientist Andrew Hacker in the late 1970s.\n翻译: <u>政治学家安德鲁·哈克在20世纪70年代末观察到了这种模式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSociologist Catherine Kohler Riessman reports in her new book Divorce Talk that most of the women she interviewed – but only a few of the men – gave lack of communication as the reason for their divorces.\n翻译: <u>社会学家凯瑟琳·科勒·里斯曼在她的新书《Divorce Talk》中报告说，她采访的大多数女性，而只有少数男性，把缺乏沟通作为她们离婚的原因。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nGiven the current divorce rate of nearly 50 percent, that amounts to millions of cases in the United States every year – a virtual epidemic of failed conversation.\n翻译: <u>考虑到目前接近50%的离婚率，这在美国每年就相当于数百万个案例，几乎是一场失败谈话的流行病。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn my own research, complaints from women about their husbands most often focused not on tangible inequities such as having given up the chance for a career to accompany a husband to his, or doing far more than their share of daily life-support work like cleaning, cooking and social arrangements.\n翻译: <u>在我自己的研究中，女性对丈夫的抱怨最常集中在并非有形的不平等上，比如为了陪丈夫去追求他的事业而放弃自己的职业机会，或者承担远超自己份额的日常生活维持工作，如清洁、做饭和社交安排。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nInstead, they focused on communication: “He doesn’t listen to me.”\n翻译: <u>相反，她们关注的是沟通：“他不听我说话。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“He doesn’t talk to me.”\n翻译: <u>“他不和我说话。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nI found, as Hacker observed years before, that most wives want their husbands to be, first and foremost, conversational partners, but few husbands share this expectation of their wives.\n翻译: <u>我发现，正如哈克多年前所观察到的那样，大多数妻子首先并且最重要的是希望她们的丈夫成为谈话伙伴，但很少有丈夫对妻子抱有这种期待。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn short, the image that best represents the current crisis is the stereotypical cartoon scene of a man sitting at the breakfast table with a newspaper held up in front of his face, while a woman glares at the back of it, wanting to talk.\n翻译: <u>简言之，最能代表当前危机的形象，是那种刻板的漫画场景：一个男人坐在早餐桌旁，把报纸举在脸前，而一个女人瞪着报纸背面，想要说话。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nOver the past decade, many companies had <font color=\"#ffff00\">perfected</font> the art of creating automatic behaviors – habits – among consumers.\n翻译: <u>在过去十年里，许多公司已经完善了在消费者中创造自动行为，即习惯的技艺。</u>\n\n-**perfected**：<u>使完美、精通（作动词用）。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese habits have helped companies earn billions of dollars when customers eat snacks or wipe counters almost without thinking, often in response to a carefully designed <font color=\"#ffff00\">set of daily cues</font>.\n翻译: <u>当顾客几乎不假思索地吃零食或擦拭台面时，这些习惯帮助公司赚取了数十亿美元，而这些行为往往是对一套精心设计的日常提示的反应。</u>\n\n-**set of daily cues**：<u>一系列的日常暗示/线索。</u>\n\n---\n\n“There are fundamental public health problems, like dirty hands instead of a soap habit, that remain killers only because we can’t figure out how to change people’s habits,” said Dr. Curtis, the director of the Hygiene Center at the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine.\n翻译: <u>伦敦卫生与热带医学院卫生中心主任柯蒂斯博士说：“有一些根本性的公共卫生问题，比如手脏而不是养成用肥皂洗手的习惯，它们之所以仍然致命，只是因为我们弄不清如何改变人们的习惯。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We wanted to learn from <font color=\"#ffff00\">private industry</font> how to create new behaviors that happen automatically.”\n翻译: <u>“我们想向私营企业学习，如何创造会自动发生的新行为。”</u>\n\n-**private industry**：<u>私营企业、私有产业（这里代指商业界）。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe companies that Dr. Curtis turned to – Procter & Gamble, Colgate- Palmolive and Unilever – had invested hundreds of millions of dollars finding the subtle cues in consumers’ lives that corporations could use to introduce new routines.\n翻译: <u>柯蒂斯博士求助的那些公司，即宝洁、高露洁-棕榄和联合利华，已经投入数亿美元，寻找消费者生活中那些企业可以用来引入新惯例的微妙提示。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIf you <font color=\"#ffff00\">look hard enough</font>, you’ll find that many of the products we use every day – chewing gums, skin moisturizers, disinfecting wipes, air fresheners, water purifiers, health snacks, teeth whiteners, fabric softeners, vitamins – are results of <font color=\"#ffff00\">manufactured habits</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果你足够仔细地观察，就会发现我们每天使用的许多产品——如口香糖、皮肤保湿霜、消毒湿巾、空气清新剂、净水器、健康零食、牙齿美白剂、织物柔顺剂、维生素——都是人为制造的习惯的结果。</u>\n\n-**look hard enough**：<u>看得很仔细、深入观察。</u>\n-**manufactured habits**：<u>被制造出来的习惯（人为培养的习惯）。</u>\n\n---\n\nA century ago, few people regularly brushed their teeth multiple times a day.\n翻译: <u>一个世纪以前，很少有人每天定期多次刷牙。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nToday, because of shrewd advertising and public health campaigns, many Americans habitually give their <font color=\"#ffff00\">pearly whites</font> a cavity-preventing scrub twice a day, often with Colgate, Crest or one of the other brands.\n翻译: <u>如今，由于精明的广告和公共卫生运动，许多美国人习惯性地每天两次给自己洁白的牙齿做防蛀清洁，常常使用高露洁、佳洁士或其他品牌之一。</u>\n\n-**pearly whites**：<u>珍珠般白的东西（俚语中指代“牙齿”）。</u>\n\n---\n\nA few decades ago, many people didn’t drink water outside of a meal.\n翻译: <u>几十年前，许多人在用餐之外并不喝水。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThen beverage companies started bottling the <font color=\"#ffff00\">production of far-off springs</font>, and now office workers unthinkingly sip bottled water all day long.\n翻译: <u>后来饮料公司开始把遥远泉水的产出装瓶销售，而现在办公室职员整天不假思索地啜饮瓶装水。</u>\n\n-**production of far-off springs**：<u>遥远泉水的产出（指偏远地方的泉水资源）。</u>\n\n---\n\nChewing gum, once bought primarily by adolescent boys, is now featured in commercials as a breath freshener and teeth cleanser for use after a meal.\n翻译: <u>口香糖曾经主要由青春期男孩购买，如今在广告中被塑造成饭后使用的清新口气剂和牙齿清洁剂。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSkin moisturizers are advertised as part of morning beauty rituals, <font color=\"#ffff00\">slipped in between</font> hair brushing and putting on makeup.\n翻译: <u>皮肤保湿霜被宣传为早晨美容仪式的一部分，被安插在梳头和化妆之间。</u>\n\n-**slipped in between...**：<u>被悄悄塞入/安插在……之间。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Our products succeed when they become part of daily or weekly patterns,” said Carol Berning, a consumer psychologist who recently retired from Procter & Gamble, the company that sold $76 billion of Tide, Crest and other products last year.\n翻译: <u>消费者心理学家卡罗尔·伯宁说：“当我们的产品成为每日或每周模式的一部分时，它们就成功了。”她不久前从宝洁退休；这家公司去年销售了价值760亿美元的汰渍、佳洁士和其他产品。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Creating positive habits is a huge part of improving our consumers’ lives, and it’s essential to making new products <font color=\"#ffff00\">commercially viable</font>.”\n翻译: <u>“创造积极的习惯，是改善我们消费者生活的一个重要部分，也是使新产品在商业上可行的关键。”</u>\n\n-**commercially viable**：<u>在商业上可行的/能赚钱的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThrough experiments and observation, social scientists like Dr. Berning have learned that there is power in tying certain behaviors to habitual cues through <font color=\"#ffff00\">ruthless advertising</font>.\n翻译: <u>通过实验和观察，像伯宁博士这样的社会科学家已经了解到，通过强力广告把某些行为与习惯性提示联系起来具有力量。</u>\n\n-**tying A to B**：<u>把 A 和 B 绑定/联系起来。</u>\n-**ruthless advertising**：<u>无情的、狂轰滥炸式的广告。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs this new science of habit has emerged, controversies have erupted when the tactics have been used to sell <font color=\"#ffff00\">questionable</font> beauty creams or unhealthy foods.\n翻译: <u>随着这门新的习惯科学兴起，当这些策略被用来销售有问题的美容霜或不健康食品时，争议也随之爆发。</u>\n\n-**questionable**：<u>可疑的、有问题的。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nMany Americans regard <font color=\"#ffff00\">the jury system</font> as a concrete expression of crucial democratic values, including <font color=\"#ffff00\">the principles that</font> all citizens <font color=\"#ffff00\">who meet minimal qualifications of age and literacy</font> are equally competent to serve on juries; that jurors should be selected randomly from a <font color=\"#ffff00\">representative cross section</font> of the community; that <font color=\"#ffff00\">no citizen should be denied the right</font> to serve on a jury <font color=\"#ffff00\">on account of</font> race, religion, sex, or national origin; that defendants are entitled to <font color=\"#ffff00\">trial by their peers</font>; and that verdicts should represent <font color=\"#ffff00\">the conscience of the community</font> and not just the letter of the law.\n翻译: <u>许多美国人把陪审团制度看作关键民主价值的具体体现，其中包括这些原则：所有符合最低年龄和读写能力资格的公民都同样有能力担任陪审员；陪审员应从社区中具有代表性的横截面中随机选出；任何公民都不应因种族、宗教、性别或民族出身而被剥夺担任陪审员的权利；被告有权接受由其同辈组成的陪审团审判；裁决应代表社区的良知，而不仅仅是法律的字面规定。</u>\n\n-**the jury system**：<u>陪审团制度。</u>\n-**the principles that…**：<u>这些原则，即后面一连串 that 从句。</u>\n-**who meet minimal qualifications of age and literacy**：<u>达到最低年龄和读写能力条件的人。</u>\n-**representative cross section**：<u>具有代表性的横截面 / 代表性样本。</u>\n-**no citizen should be denied the right**：<u>任何公民都不应被剥夺权利。</u>\n-**on account of…**：<u>由于、因为。</u>\n-**trial by their peers**：<u>由其同辈进行审判。</u>\n-**peers**：<u>这里的 peers 不是“朋友”，而是社会地位相当、普通公民群体中的成员。</u>\n-**the conscience of the community**：<u>社区良知、社会共同道德判断。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe jury is also said to be the best surviving example of direct rather than representative democracy.\n翻译: <u>陪审团也被说成是直接民主而非代议民主的最佳现存例证。</u>\n\n-**direct democracy**：<u>直接民主，公民亲自参与决策。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a direct democracy, citizens take turns governing themselves, rather than electing representatives to govern for them.\n翻译: <u>在直接民主中，公民轮流治理自己，而不是选举代表来替他们治理。</u>\n\n-**take turns doing**：<u>轮流做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">as recently as</font> in 1968, <font color=\"#ffff00\">jury selection procedures</font> conflicted with these democratic ideals.\n翻译: <u>但就在近至1968年，陪审团遴选程序仍与这些民主理想相冲突。</u>\n\n-**as recently as**：<u>就在……这样近的时间、直到……还；作者强调：1968 年并不遥远，但当时陪审团遴选仍与民主原则冲突</u>\n-**jury selection procedures**：<u>陪审团遴选程序。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn some states, for example, jury duty was limited to persons of supposedly superior intelligence, education, and moral character.\n翻译: <u>例如，在一些州，陪审义务仅限于那些被认为智力、教育水平和道德品质较高的人。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAlthough the Supreme Court of the United States had prohibited intentional racial discrimination in jury selection as early as the 1880 case of Strauder v. West Virginia, the practice of selecting so-called elite or blue-ribbon juries <font color=\"#ffff00\">provided a convenient way around</font> this and other antidiscrimination laws.\n翻译: <u>尽管美国最高法院早在1880年的 Strauder v. West Virginia 案中就已经禁止在陪审团遴选中蓄意进行种族歧视，但选择所谓精英陪审团或蓝带陪审团的做法，为规避这一法律和其他反歧视法律提供了一种便利途径。</u>\n\n-**provide a way around…**：<u>提供绕过……的方法。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe system also failed to regularly include women on juries until the mid-20th century.\n翻译: <u>直到20世纪中叶，该制度也未能经常把女性纳入陪审团。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAlthough women first served on state juries in Utah in 1898, it was not until the 1940s that a majority of states made women eligible for jury duty.\n翻译: <u>尽管女性早在1898年就首次在犹他州担任州陪审团成员，但直到20世纪40年代，多数州才使女性有资格承担陪审义务。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Even then</font> several states automatically exempted women from jury duty unless they personally asked to have their names included on the jury list.\n翻译: <u>即便如此，仍有几个州自动免除女性的陪审义务，除非她们亲自要求把自己的名字列入陪审员名单。</u>\n\n-**Even then**：<u>即使那时，指 1940 年代大多数州已让女性有资格担任陪审员之后。</u>\n-**exempt A from B**：<u>免除 A 的 B 义务。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis practice was justified by the claim that women were needed at home, and it kept juries <font color=\"#ffff00\">unrepresentative of women</font> through the 1960s.\n翻译: <u>这种做法以女性需要待在家里为理由而被正当化，并且直到20世纪60年代都使陪审团不能代表女性。</u>\n\n-**be justified by…**：<u>被用……证明合理。</u>\n-**unrepresentative of women**：<u>不能代表女性、女性代表性不足。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn 1968, the Congress of the United States passed the Jury Selection and Service Act, <font color=\"#ffff00\">ushering in</font> a new era of democratic reforms for the jury.\n翻译: <u>1968年，美国国会通过了《陪审团遴选与服务法》，开启了陪审团民主改革的新时代。</u>\n\n-**usher in**：<u>开启、引入。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis law abolished special educational requirements for federal jurors and required them to be selected at random from a cross section of the entire community.\n翻译: <u>这项法律废除了对联邦陪审员的特殊教育要求，并要求从整个社区的横截面中随机遴选他们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn the landmark 1975 decision <font color=\"#ffff00\">Taylor v. Louisiana</font>, the Supreme Court extended the requirement that juries be representative of all parts of the community to the state level.\n翻译: <u>在1975年具有里程碑意义的 Taylor v. Louisiana 案判决中，最高法院把陪审团应代表社区所有组成部分这一要求扩展到了州一级。</u>\n\n-**Taylor v. Louisiana**：<u>案件名。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Taylor <font color=\"#ffff00\">decision</font> also declared sex discrimination in jury selection to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">unconstitutional</font> and ordered states to use the same procedures for selecting male and female jurors.\n翻译: <u>泰勒案的判决还宣布，在陪审员遴选中的性别歧视是违宪的，并命令各州采用相同程序来遴选男性和女性陪审员。</u>\n\n-**decision**：<u>判决。</u>\n-**declare A to be B**：<u>宣布 A 是 B。</u>\n-**unconstitutional**：<u>违宪的。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2011","year":"2011","title":"2011 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2011 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2011 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nRuth Simmons joined Goldman Sachs’s board <font color=\"#ffff00\">as an outside director</font> in January 2000; a year later she became president of Brown University.\n翻译: <u>露丝·西蒙斯于2000年1月作为外部董事加入高盛董事会；一年后，她成为布朗大学校长。</u>\n\n-**as an outside director**：<u>作为外部董事。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor <font color=\"#ffff00\">the rest of the decade</font> she apparently <font color=\"#ffff00\">managed both roles</font> without attracting much criticism.\n翻译: <u>在那十年剩下的时间里，她显然同时处理好了这两个角色，而没有招致多少批评。</u>\n\n-**the rest of the decade**：<u>这个十年中剩余的时间。</u>\n-**managed both roles**：<u>兼顾两个角色。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut by the end of 2009 Ms. Simmons was under fire for having sat on <font color=\"#ffff00\">Goldman’s compensation committee</font>; how could she have let those enormous bonus payouts pass unremarked?\n翻译: <u>但到2009年底，西蒙斯女士因曾在高盛薪酬委员会任职而受到抨击；她怎么能让那些数额巨大的奖金发放在无人置评的情况下通过呢？</u>\n\n-**Goldman’s compensation committee**：<u>高盛薪酬委员会。</u>\n-**let something pass unremarked**：<u>让某事未被评论/未被质疑地过去。</u>\n\n---\n\nBy February the next year Ms. Simmons had left the board.\n翻译: <u>到次年2月，西蒙斯女士已经离开了董事会。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe position was just taking up too much time, she said.\n翻译: <u>她说，这个职位只是占用了太多时间。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOutside directors are supposed to serve as helpful, <font color=\"#ffff00\">yet</font> less biased, advisers on a <font color=\"#ffff00\">firm’s board</font>.\n翻译: <u>外部董事本应在公司董事会中充当有帮助、但偏见较少的顾问。</u>\n\n-**yet**：<u>不是“然而”那种强转折，而是表示一种轻微转折/补充对比，“同时又……” / “但又……” / “不过还……”。</u>\n-**firm’s board**：<u>公司的董事会。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Having made</font> their wealth and their reputations elsewhere, they <font color=\"#ffff00\">presumably</font> have enough independence to disagree with the chief executive’s proposals.\n翻译: <u>由于他们是在别处积累财富和声望的，他们大概拥有足够的独立性，能够不同意首席执行官的提议。</u>\n\n-**Having made…**：<u>= Because they have made…</u>\n-**presumably**：<u>大概、按理说。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf the sky, and the share price is falling, outside directors should be able to give advice based on having weathered their own crises.\n翻译: <u>如果形势不妙，股价也在下跌，外部董事应当能够基于自己曾经渡过危机的经验提出建议。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe researchers from Ohio University used a database that covered more than 10,000 firms and more than 64,000 different directors between 1989 and 2004.\n翻译: <u>俄亥俄大学的研究人员使用了一个数据库，该数据库涵盖了1989年至2004年间1万多家公司和6.4万多名不同董事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThen they <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply</font> checked which directors stayed <font color=\"#ffff00\">from one</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">proxy statement</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">to the next</font>.\n翻译: <u>然后他们只是核查哪些董事从一份委托书到下一份委托书仍然留任。</u>\n\n-**simply**：<u>只是、简单地。</u>\n-**proxy statement**：<u>委托书/股东代理声明，公司提交给股东的文件，通常列出董事名单、高管薪酬等信息。</u>\n-**from one…to the next**：<u>从一份到下一份。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe most likely reason for departing a board was age, so the researchers concentrated on those “surprise” disappearances by directors under the age of 70.\n翻译: <u>离开董事会最可能的原因是年龄，因此研究人员把注意力集中在70岁以下董事的那些“意外”离任上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey found that after a surprise departure, the probability that the company will subsequently have to <font color=\"#ffff00\">restate earnings</font> increases by nearly 20%.\n翻译: <u>他们发现，在一次意外离任之后，公司随后不得不重报收益的概率会增加近20%。</u>\n\n-**restate earnings**：<u>重述收益，指公司发现之前财务报表有误，需要重新公布利润数据。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">likelihood</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">being named in</font> a <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal class-action lawsuit</font> also increases, and the stock is likely to perform worse.\n翻译: <u>在联邦集体诉讼中被点名的可能性也会增加，而且股票表现很可能更差。</u>\n\n-**likelihood**：<u>可能性。</u>\n-**being named in…**：<u>被列名于……中，即成为诉讼对象。</u>\n-**federal class-action lawsuit**：<u>联邦集体诉讼。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The effect</font> tended to be larger for larger firms.\n翻译: <u>这种影响在较大的公司中往往更大。</u>\n\n-**the effect**：<u>这种效应，指董事意外离任与后续负面结果之间的关联。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlthough a correlation between them leaving and subsequent bad performance at the firm is <font color=\"#ffff00\">suggestive</font>, it does not mean that such directors are always jumping off a sinking ship.\n翻译: <u>尽管他们离任与公司随后表现不佳之间的相关性颇具暗示性，但这并不意味着这类董事总是在跳下一艘正在下沉的船。</u>\n\n-**correlation between A and B**：<u>A 和 B 之间的相关性。</u>\n-**suggestive**：<u>有暗示意义的、发人深思的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Often</font> they “trade up,” leaving riskier, smaller firms for larger and more stable firms.\n翻译: <u>他们常常是“向上流动”，离开风险更高、规模更小的公司，转投规模更大、更稳定的公司。</u>\n\n-**Often**：<u>经常。</u>\n-**leave A for B**：<u>离开 A 去 B。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the researchers believe that outside directors have an easier time of avoiding <font color=\"#ffff00\">a blow to</font> their reputations if they leave a firm before bad news breaks, even if <font color=\"#ffff00\">a review of history</font> shows they were on the board at the time <font color=\"#ffff00\">any</font> wrongdoing occurred.\n翻译: <u>但研究人员认为，如果外部董事在坏消息爆出之前离开一家公司，他们就更容易避免声誉受损，即便对历史的回顾显示，在任何不当行为发生时他们就在董事会中。</u>\n\n-**have an easier time of doing**：<u>做某事更容易。</u>\n-**a blow to…**：<u>对……的打击。</u>\n-**a review of history**：<u>回顾历史、事后追查。</u>\n-**any**：<u>任何。</u>\n\n---\n\nFirms who want to keep their outside directors through tough times <font color=\"#ffff00\">may have to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">create incentives</font>.\n翻译: <u>想让外部董事在艰难时期继续留任的公司，可能不得不创造激励措施。</u>\n\n-**may have to**：<u>可能不得不。</u>\n-**create incentives**：<u>创造激励、提供激励措施。</u>\n\n---\n\nOtherwise outside directors will follow the example of Ms. Simmons, <font color=\"#ffff00\">once again</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">very popular on campus</font>.\n翻译: <u>否则，外部董事将效仿西蒙斯女士的做法，而她如今在校园里又一次非常受欢迎。</u>\n\n-**once again**：<u>再次。</u>\n-**very popular on campus**：<u>在校园里很受欢迎；这句话带有讽刺意味：离开充满争议的公司董事会后，她回到大学校园中的正面形象，名声恢复</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nWhatever happened to the death of newspapers?\n翻译: <u>报纸之死到底发生了什么？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA year ago the end <font color=\"#ffff00\">seemed near</font>.\n翻译: <u>一年前，末日似乎近在眼前。</u>\n\n-**seemed near**：<u>似乎很近、似乎马上就要到来。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">recession</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">threatened to</font> remove the advertising and readers that had not already fled to the internet.\n翻译: <u>经济衰退威胁着要夺走那些尚未转向互联网的广告和读者。</u>\n\n-**recession**：<u>经济衰退。</u>\n-**threatened to…**：<u>有可能……、威胁要……。</u>\n\n---\n\nNewspapers like the <font color=\"#ffff00\">San Francisco Chronicle</font> were chronicling <font color=\"#ffff00\">their own doom</font>.\n翻译: <u>像《旧金山纪事报》这样的报纸正在记录自己的末日。</u>\n\n-**San Francisco Chronicle**：<u>《旧金山纪事报》。</u>\n-**chronicle**：<u>记录、报道。</u>\n-**their own doom**：<u>自己的毁灭、末日。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmerica’s Federal Trade Commission launched <font color=\"#ffff00\">a round of talks</font> about how to save newspapers.\n翻译: <u>美国联邦贸易委员会发起了一轮关于如何拯救报纸的会谈。</u>\n\n-**a round of talks**：<u>一轮讨论、会谈。</u>\n\n---\n\nShould they become <font color=\"#ffff00\">charitable corporations</font>?\n翻译: <u>它们应该变成慈善性公司吗？</u>\n\n-**charitable corporations**：<u>慈善性公司 / 非营利性质机构。</u>\n\n---\n\nShould the state subsidize them?\n翻译: <u>政府应该补贴它们吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt will <font color=\"#ffff00\">hold another meeting</font> soon.\n翻译: <u>它很快还将举行另一场会议。</u>\n\n-**hold another meeting**：<u>再举行一次会议。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the discussions now seem out of date.\n翻译: <u>但这些讨论现在看来已经过时了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn <font color=\"#ffff00\">much of the world</font> there is <font color=\"#ffff00\">little sign</font> of crisis.\n翻译: <u>在世界许多地方，几乎没有危机的迹象。</u>\n\n-**much of the world**：<u>世界很多地方、大部分地区。</u>\n-**little sign**：<u>几乎没有迹象。</u>\n\n---\n\nGerman and Brazilian papers have <font color=\"#ffff00\">shrugged off</font> the recession.\n翻译: <u>德国和巴西的报纸已经轻松挺过了经济衰退。</u>\n\n-**shrug off**：<u>轻松摆脱、不把……当回事。</u>\n\n---\n\nEven American newspapers, which inhabit the most troubled corner of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">global industry</font>, have not only survived but often returned to profit.\n翻译: <u>即使是处在全球报业最困扰角落的美国报纸，也不仅存活了下来，而且往往重新实现了盈利。</u>\n\n-**global industry**：<u>全球行业，指全球报业。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Not</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">20% profit margins</font> that were routine a few years ago, <font color=\"#ffff00\">but</font> profit all the same.\n翻译: <u>不是几年前司空见惯的20%利润率，但终究还是盈利。</u>\n\n-**20% profit margins**：<u>20% 的利润率</u>\n-**Not…but…**：<u>不是……而是……。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt has not been much fun.\n翻译: <u>这并不是什么愉快的经历。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMany papers <font color=\"#ffff00\">stayed afloat</font> by pushing journalists overboard.\n翻译: <u>许多报纸是通过把记者推下船才维持了生存。</u>\n\n-**stay afloat**：<u>保持漂浮，比喻维持生存、不破产。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The American Society of News Editors</font> reckons that 13,500 newsroom jobs have gone since 2007.\n翻译: <u>美国新闻编辑协会估计，自2007年以来，已有13,500个编辑部岗位消失。</u>\n\n-**The American Society of News Editors**：<u>美国新闻编辑协会。</u>\n\n---\n\nReaders are paying more for <font color=\"#ffff00\">slimmer products</font>.\n翻译: <u>读者正在为内容更薄的产品支付更多费用。</u>\n\n-**slimmer products**：<u>更薄的产品，指内容减少、版面变薄的报纸。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome papers even had the nerve to refuse delivery to distant suburbs.\n翻译: <u>有些报纸甚至有胆量拒绝向偏远郊区投递。</u>\n\n-**have the nerve to do**：<u>竟敢做某事、有胆量做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet these <font color=\"#ffff00\">desperate measures</font> have proved the right ones and, sadly for many journalists, they can be pushed further.\n翻译: <u>然而，这些绝望的措施已被证明是正确的，而且令许多记者伤心的是，它们还可以进一步推进。</u>\n\n-**desperate measures**：<u>绝望措施、迫不得已的手段。</u>\n\n---\n\nNewspapers are becoming <font color=\"#ffff00\">more balanced businesses</font>, with a <font color=\"#ffff00\">healthier mix</font> of revenues from readers and advertisers.\n翻译: <u>报纸正在成为更加均衡的企业，来自读者和广告商的收入组合也更加健康。</u>\n\n-**more balanced businesses**：<u>更平衡的商业体。</u>\n-**healthier mix**：<u>更健康的组合。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmerican papers have long been highly unusual in their reliance on ads.\n翻译: <u>长期以来，美国报纸在依赖广告方面一直非常不同寻常。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFully 87% of their revenues came from advertising in 2008, according to the Organization for Economic Cooperation & Development (OECD).\n翻译: <u>据经济合作与发展组织（OECD）称，2008年它们足足87%的收入来自广告。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn Japan the proportion is 35%.\n翻译: <u>在日本，这一比例为35%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNot surprisingly, Japanese newspapers are much more stable.\n翻译: <u>毫不奇怪，日本报纸要稳定得多。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">whirlwind</font> that swept through newsrooms harmed everybody, but much of the damage has been concentrated in <font color=\"#ffff00\">areas</font> where newspapers are <font color=\"#ffff00\">least distinctive</font>.\n翻译: <u>席卷编辑部的旋风伤害了所有人，但大部分损害集中在报纸最不具特色的领域。</u>\n\n-**whirlwind**：<u>旋风，比喻剧烈变化、行业冲击。</u>\n-**areas**：<u>领域、板块。</u>\n-**least distinctive**：<u>最不独特、最没有差异化优势。</u>\n\n---\n\nCar and film reviewers have gone.\n翻译: <u>汽车和电影评论员已经离开。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">So have</font> science and general business reporters.\n翻译: <u>科学记者和普通商业记者也是如此。</u>\n\n-**So have…**：<u>是承接上一句</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Foreign bureaus</font> have been <font color=\"#ffff00\">savagely</font> cut off.\n翻译: <u>驻外新闻分社已被猛烈削减。</u>\n\n-**foreign bureaus**：<u>海外新闻分社、驻外记者站。</u>\n-**have been cut off**：<u>已经被砍掉、被切断。</u>\n-**savagely**：<u>残酷地、猛烈地。</u>\n\n---\n\nNewspapers are less complete as a result.\n翻译: <u>结果，报纸变得不那么完整了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut completeness is no longer a virtue in the newspaper business.\n翻译: <u>但在报业中，完整性不再是一种优点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nWe tend to <font color=\"#ffff00\">think of</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">decades immediately following World War II</font> as a time of prosperity and growth, with soldiers returning home <font color=\"#ffff00\">by the millions</font>, going off to college on the G. I. Bill and lining up at the marriage bureaus.\n翻译: <u>我们往往把二战后最初几十年看作一个繁荣和增长的时期：数以百万计的士兵返乡，凭借《退伍军人权利法案》上大学，并在婚姻登记处排队。</u>\n\n-**think of A as B**：<u>把 A 看作 B。</u>\n-**the decades immediately following World War II**：<u>二战后紧接着的几十年。</u>\n-**by the millions**：<u>数以百万计。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut when it came to their houses, it was a time of common sense and a belief that less <font color=\"#ffff00\">could truly be</font> more.\n翻译: <u>但说到他们的住房，那是一个崇尚常识、相信更少确实可以成为更多的时代。</u>\n\n-**could truly be**：<u>这里用 could truly be 表示“确实可能是”。</u>\n\n---\n\nDuring <font color=\"#ffff00\">the Depression</font> and the war, Americans had learned to live with less, and that restraint, in combination with the postwar confidence in the future, made small, efficient housing positively stylish.\n翻译: <u>在大萧条和战争期间，美国人已经学会了以更少的东西生活，而这种克制，加上战后对未来的信心，使小巧、高效的住房变得格外时髦。</u>\n\n-**the Depression**：<u>大萧条。</u>\n\n---\n\nEconomic condition was only a stimulus for the <font color=\"#ffff00\">trend toward</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">efficient living</font>.\n翻译: <u>经济状况只是推动高效生活趋势的一个刺激因素。</u>\n\n-**trend toward…**：<u>朝向……的趋势。</u>\n-**efficient living**：<u>高效生活。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe phrase “less is more” was actually <font color=\"#ffff00\">first popularized by</font> a German, <font color=\"#ffff00\">the architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe</font>, who <font color=\"#ffff00\">like other people associated with the Bauhaus</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">a school of design</font>, emigrated to the United States before World War II and <font color=\"#ffff00\">took up posts</font> at American architecture schools.\n翻译: <u>“少即是多”这个短语实际上最早是由一位德国人推广开来的，他就是建筑师路德维希·密斯·凡·德罗；和其他与包豪斯这一设计学院有关的人一样，他在二战前移民到美国，并在美国建筑学院任职。</u>\n\n-**first popularized by…**：<u>最早由……推广。</u>\n-**the architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe**：<u>一位德国人，即建筑师密斯·凡·德·罗。</u>\n-**like other people associated with the Bauhaus**：<u>像其他与包豪斯相关的人一样。</u>\n-**a school of design**：<u>一所设计学校，同位语解释 Bauhaus。</u>\n-**took up posts**：<u>担任职位。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese designers <font color=\"#ffff00\">came to exert</font> enormous influence on the course of American architecture, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">none</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">more so</font> than Mies.\n翻译: <u>这些设计师后来对美国建筑的发展进程产生了巨大影响，但没有人比密斯影响更大。</u>\n\n-**came to exert**：<u>逐渐开始产生。</u>\n-**exert influence on…**：<u>对……施加影响。</u>\n-**none**：<u>没有一个人。</u>\n-**more so**：<u>在这方面更多/更强。</u>\n\n---\n\nMies’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">signature phrase</font> means that less decoration, properly organized, has more impact than a lot.\n翻译: <u>密斯的标志性短语意思是，较少的装饰，只要组织得当，比大量装饰更有影响力。</u>\n\n-**signature phrase**：<u>标志性短语、代表性名言。</u>\n\n---\n\nElegance, he believed, did not derive from abundance.\n翻译: <u>他认为，优雅并非源自丰裕。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nLike other modern architects, he <font color=\"#ffff00\">employed</font> metal, glass and laminated wood – materials that we take for granted today but that in the 1940s symbolized the future.\n翻译: <u>像其他现代建筑师一样，他使用金属、玻璃和层压木材，这些材料如今我们视为理所当然，但在20世纪40年代象征着未来。</u>\n\n-**employed**：<u>使用。</u>\n\n---\n\nMies’s sophisticated presentation <font color=\"#ffff00\">masked</font> the fact that the spaces he designed were small and efficient, rather than big and often empty.\n翻译: <u>密斯精致的呈现方式掩盖了这样一个事实：他设计的空间是小巧而高效的，而不是巨大且常常空荡的。</u>\n\n-**masked**：<u>掩盖。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe apartments in the elegant towers Mies built on Chicago’s Lake Shore Drive, for example, were smaller – two-bedroom units <font color=\"#ffff00\">under 1,000 square feet</font> – than those in their older neighbors along the city’s Gold Coast.\n翻译: <u>例如，密斯在芝加哥湖滨大道建造的优雅高楼中的公寓，比这座城市黄金海岸沿线较老的邻近建筑中的公寓更小，其中两居室单元不到1,000平方英尺。</u>\n\n-**under 1,000 square feet**：<u>不到 1000 平方英尺。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut they were popular because of their airy glass walls, <font color=\"#ffff00\">the views they afforded</font> and the elegance of the buildings’ details and proportions, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">architectural equivalent</font> of the abstract art so popular at the time.\n翻译: <u>但它们很受欢迎，因为有通透的玻璃墙、所提供的景观，以及建筑细部和比例的优雅，这在建筑上相当于当时非常流行的抽象艺术。</u>\n\n-**the views they afforded**：<u>它们提供的景观；这是当时流行抽象艺术在建筑上的对应物</u>\n-**architectural equivalent**：<u>建筑上的对应物。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe trend toward “less” was <font color=\"#ffff00\">not entirely foreign</font>.\n翻译: <u>这种走向“更少”的趋势并非完全来自国外。</u>\n\n-**not entirely foreign**：<u>并非完全外来的 / 并不完全陌生。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the 1930s Frank Lloyd Wright started building more modest and efficient houses – usually around 1,200 square feet – than the spreading two-story ones he had designed in the 1890s and the early 20th century.\n翻译: <u>20世纪30年代，弗兰克·劳埃德·赖特开始建造更朴素、更高效的房子，通常约1,200平方英尺，而不是他在19世纪90年代和20世纪初设计的那些铺展开来的两层住宅。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe “Case Study Houses” <font color=\"#ffff00\">commissioned from</font> talented modern architects <font color=\"#ffff00\">by</font> California Arts & Architecture magazine between 1945 and 1962 were <font color=\"#ffff00\">yet another</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">homegrown</font> influence on the “less is more” trend.\n翻译: <u>1945年至1962年间，加利福尼亚《艺术与建筑》杂志委托才华横溢的现代建筑师设计的“案例研究住宅”，是对“少即是多”趋势的又一种本土影响。</u>\n\n-**commissioned from…by…**：<u>由……委托……设计/创作。</u>\n-**yet another**：<u>又一个、再一个。</u>\n-**homegrown**：<u>本土产生的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Aesthetic effect</font> came from the landscape, new materials and <font color=\"#ffff00\">forthright detailing</font>.\n翻译: <u>美学效果来自景观、新材料和直截了当的细部处理。</u>\n\n-**Aesthetic effect**：<u>美学效果。</u>\n-**forthright detailing**：<u>直率、清楚、不掩饰结构的细部设计。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn his Case Study House, Ralph Rapson <font color=\"#ffff00\">may have mispredicted</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">just how</font> the mechanical revolution would impact everyday life – few American families acquired helicopters, <font color=\"#ffff00\">though</font> most eventually got clothes dryers – but his belief that self-sufficiency was both desirable and inevitable was widely shared.\n翻译: <u>在他的案例研究住宅中，拉尔夫·拉普森或许误判了机械革命将如何影响日常生活——几乎没有美国家庭拥有直升机，尽管大多数家庭最终都有了干衣机——但他关于自给自足既可取又不可避免的信念得到了广泛认同。</u>\n\n-**may have mispredicted**：<u>可能误判了。</u>\n-**just how…**：<u>究竟如何。</u>\n-**though**：<u>虽然、不过。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nWill the European Union make it?\n翻译: <u>欧盟能挺过去吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe question <font color=\"#ffff00\">would have sounded</font> strange not long ago.\n翻译: <u>不久以前，这个问题听起来还会很奇怪。</u>\n\n-**would have sounded**：<u>本来会听起来。</u>\n\n---\n\nNow even the project’s greatest <font color=\"#ffff00\">cheerleaders</font> talk of a continent facing a “<font color=\"#ffff00\">Bermuda triangle</font>” of debt, population decline and lower growth.\n翻译: <u>如今，甚至连这一项目最热情的支持者也在谈论一个正面临由债务、人口下降和较低增长构成的“百慕大三角”的大陆。</u>\n\n-**cheerleaders**：<u>原义是“啦啦队员”，这里比喻“热情支持者、鼓吹者”</u>\n-**Bermuda triangle**：<u>百慕大三角，原指传说中船只飞机神秘失踪的海域；这里比喻危险组合。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">As well as</font> those chronic problems, the EU faces an acute crisis in its economic core, the 16 countries that use <font color=\"#ffff00\">the single currency</font>.\n翻译: <u>除了这些长期问题之外，欧盟还在其经济核心，即使用单一货币的16个国家，面临一场急性危机。</u>\n\n-**as well as**：<u>除……之外，也。</u>\n-**the single currency**：<u>单一货币，指欧元。</u>\n\n---\n\nMarkets have lost faith that the euro zone’s economies, <font color=\"#ffff00\">weaker or stronger</font>, will one day converge <font color=\"#ffff00\">thanks to</font> the discipline of sharing a single currency, which denies uncompetitive members the <font color=\"#ffff00\">quick fix</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">devaluation</font>.\n翻译: <u>市场已经失去信心，不再相信欧元区经济体无论强弱，终有一天会因共享单一货币所带来的纪律而趋同；这种纪律剥夺了缺乏竞争力的成员国通过货币贬值迅速解决问题的办法。</u>\n\n-**weaker or stronger**：<u>较弱的或较强的，插入语。</u>\n-**thanks to**：<u>由于、因为。</u>\n-**deny A B**：<u>不给 A B，使 A 得不到 B。</u>\n-**quick fix**：<u>快速补救办法、权宜之计。</u>\n-**devaluation**：<u>货币贬值。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet the debate about how to save Europe’s single currency from disintegration is <font color=\"#ffff00\">stuck</font>.\n翻译: <u>然而，关于如何拯救欧洲单一货币免于瓦解的辩论却陷入了僵局。</u>\n\n-**stuck**：<u>卡住的、陷入僵局的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is stuck because the euro zone’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">dominant powers</font>, France and Germany, <font color=\"#ffff00\">agree on</font> the need for <font color=\"#ffff00\">greater harmonisation</font> within the euro zone, but disagree about <font color=\"#ffff00\">what to harmonise</font>.\n翻译: <u>僵局之所以存在，是因为欧元区的主导力量法国和德国都同意欧元区内部需要更大程度的协调一致，但对于应当协调什么存在分歧。</u>\n\n-**dominant powers**：<u>主导力量、主要大国。</u>\n-**agree on**：<u>在……上达成一致。</u>\n-**greater harmonisation**：<u>更大程度的协调、统一。</u>\n-**what to harmonise**：<u>要统一/协调什么。</u>\n\n---\n\nGermany thinks the euro must be saved by stricter rules on <font color=\"#ffff00\">borrowing</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">spending</font> and competitiveness, backed by <font color=\"#ffff00\">quasi-automatic</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">sanctions</font> for governments that do not obey.\n翻译: <u>德国认为，必须通过对借贷、支出和竞争力制定更严格的规则来拯救欧元，并以准自动的制裁措施来约束不遵守规则的政府。</u>\n\n-**borrowing**：<u>借贷。</u>\n-**spending**：<u>支出。</u>\n-**quasi-automatic**：<u>准自动的、几乎自动触发的。</u>\n-**sanctions**：<u>制裁、惩罚措施。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese might include threats to freeze EU funds for poorer regions and <font color=\"#ffff00\">EU mega-projects</font>, and even the suspension of a country’s voting rights in <font color=\"#ffff00\">EU ministerial councils</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些制裁可能包括威胁冻结用于较贫困地区和欧盟大型项目的欧盟资金，甚至暂停一国在欧盟部长理事会中的投票权。</u>\n\n-**freeze funds**：<u>冻结资金。</u>\n-**EU mega-projects**：<u>欧盟大型项目。</u>\n-**EU ministerial councils**：<u>欧盟部长理事会，各成员国部长参与决策的机构。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt insists that <font color=\"#ffff00\">economic co-ordination</font> should involve all 27 members of the EU club, among whom there is <font color=\"#ffff00\">a small majority</font> for free-market liberalism and <font color=\"#ffff00\">economic rigour</font>; in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">inner core alone</font>, Germany fears, a small majority favour <font color=\"#ffff00\">French interference</font>.\n翻译: <u>德国坚持认为，经济协调应当涉及欧盟俱乐部的全部27个成员国；在这些成员国中，自由市场自由主义和经济严谨性略占多数，而德国担心，如果只在内部核心中，则略占多数的人会支持法国式干预。</u>\n\n-**economic co-ordination**：<u>经济协调。</u>\n-**a small majority**：<u>微弱多数。</u>\n-**economic rigour**：<u>经济严谨/财政纪律。</u>\n-**inner core alone**：<u>仅仅内部核心，指欧元区国家。</u>\n-**French interference**：<u>法国式干预，带有德国视角的贬义，指法国主张更强政治干预、财政转移和统一经济治理。</u>\n\n---\n\nA “southern” <font color=\"#ffff00\">camp</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">headed by France</font> wants something different: “European economic government” <font color=\"#ffff00\">within an inner core</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">euro-zone members</font>.\n翻译: <u>一个由法国领导的“南方”阵营想要的是另一种东西：在欧元区成员国的内部核心中建立“欧洲经济政府”。</u>\n\n-**camp**：<u>阵营。</u>\n-**headed by France**：<u>由法国领导。</u>\n-**within an inner core**：<u>在内部核心之内。</u>\n-**euro-zone members**：<u>欧元区成员国。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Translated</font>, that means politicians intervening in monetary policy and <font color=\"#ffff00\">a system of redistribution</font> from richer to poorer members, via cheaper borrowing for governments through <font color=\"#ffff00\">common Eurobonds</font> or <font color=\"#ffff00\">complete fiscal transfers</font>.\n翻译: <u>翻译过来，这意味着政治人物干预货币政策，并通过共同的欧元债券为各国政府提供更便宜的借贷，或通过完全的财政转移，建立一种从较富成员国向较穷成员国再分配的体系。</u>\n\n-**Translated**：<u>不是字面说语言翻译，而是“换句话说、说穿了”。</u>\n-**a system of redistribution**：<u>再分配制度。</u>\n-**common Eurobonds**：<u>共同欧元债券，即欧元区共同发行债券，信用较弱国家借款成本会下降。</u>\n-**complete fiscal transfers**：<u>完全财政转移，即富国向穷国转移财政资源。</u>\n\n---\n\nFinally, <font color=\"#ffff00\">figures</font> close to the Franch government <font color=\"#ffff00\">have murmured</font>, euro-zone members should agree to some fiscal and <font color=\"#ffff00\">social harmonisation</font>: e.g., curbing <font color=\"#ffff00\">competition in corporate-tax rates</font> or <font color=\"#ffff00\">labour costs</font>.\n翻译: <u>最后，接近法国政府的人士曾低声表示，欧元区成员国应当同意某种财政和社会层面的协调一致，例如限制企业税率或劳动力成本方面的竞争。</u>\n\n-**figures**：<u>人物、人士。</u>\n-**close to the French government**：<u>接近法国政府的。</u>\n-**have murmured**：<u>低声说、私下暗示。</u>\n-**social harmonisation**：<u>社会政策协调/统一。</u>\n-**competition in corporate-tax rates**：<u>公司税率竞争。</u>\n-**labour costs**：<u>劳动力成本。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is too soon to <font color=\"#ffff00\">write off</font> the EU.\n翻译: <u>现在就断言欧盟无望还为时过早。</u>\n\n-**write off**：<u>认定……失败、放弃对……的希望。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt remains <font color=\"#ffff00\">the world’s largest trading block</font>.\n翻译: <u>它仍然是世界上最大的贸易集团。</u>\n\n-**the world’s largest trading block**：<u>世界最大贸易集团。</u>\n\n---\n\nAt its best, the European project is <font color=\"#ffff00\">remarkably</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">liberal</font>: <font color=\"#ffff00\">built around</font> a single market of 27 rich and poor countries, its internal borders are <font color=\"#ffff00\">far more open to</font> goods, capital and labour <font color=\"#ffff00\">than</font> any comparable trading area.\n翻译: <u>在最佳状态下，欧洲项目是相当自由主义的：它围绕一个由27个富国和穷国组成的单一市场建立，其内部边界对商品、资本和劳动力的开放程度远高于任何类似的贸易区。</u>\n\n-**remarkably**：<u>非常、显著地。</u>\n-**liberal**：<u>自由主义的、开放的。</u>\n-**built around…**：<u>围绕……建立。</u>\n-**far more open to…than…**：<u>远比……更开放。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is an ambitious attempt to <font color=\"#ffff00\">blunt</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the sharpest edges of globalisation</font>, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">make capitalism benign</font>.\n翻译: <u>这是一次雄心勃勃的尝试，旨在削弱全球化最锋利的棱角，并使资本主义变得温和。</u>\n\n-**blunt**：<u>使变钝、减弱。</u>\n-**the sharpest edges of globalisation**：<u>全球化最锋利的边缘，比喻全球化带来的最残酷冲击，如产业转移、失业、贫富差距。</u>\n-**make capitalism benign**：<u>让资本主义变得温和、良性。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2012","year":"2012","title":"2012 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2012 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2012 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nHomework has never been <font color=\"#ffff00\">terribly popular</font> with students and even many parents, but in recent years it has been particularly <font color=\"#ffff00\">scorned</font>.\n翻译: <u>家庭作业从来都不太受学生、甚至许多家长欢迎，但近年来它尤其受到轻视。</u>\n\n-**terribly popular**：<u>特别受欢迎；这里 terribly 是程度副词，相当于 very。</u>\n-**scorned**：<u>被轻视、被鄙视、被强烈批评。</u>\n\n---\n\nSchool districts across the country, <font color=\"#ffff00\">most recently</font> Los Angeles Unified, are revising their thinking on this educational ritual.\n翻译: <u>全国各地的学区，最近的是洛杉矶联合学区，正在重新审视他们对这一教育惯例的看法。</u>\n\n-**most recently**：<u>最近的是、最新例子是。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, L.A.\n翻译: <u>不幸的是，洛杉矶</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nUnified has produced an inflexible policy which <font color=\"#ffff00\">mandates</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">with the exception of</font> some advanced courses, homework may no longer <font color=\"#ffff00\">count for</font> more than 10% of a student’s academic grade.\n翻译: <u>联合学区制定了一项僵化的政策，该政策规定，除某些高级课程外，家庭作业在学生学业成绩中所占比例不得再超过10%。</u>\n\n-**mandate**：<u>强制规定、命令。</u>\n-**with the exception of…**：<u>除了……之外。</u>\n-**count for**：<u>占……比例、计入……。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis rule is meant to address the difficulty that students from impoverished or chaotic homes might have in completing their homework.\n翻译: <u>这项规定旨在解决来自贫困或混乱家庭的学生在完成家庭作业时可能遇到的困难。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the policy is unclear and <font color=\"#ffff00\">contradictory</font>.\n翻译: <u>但这项政策含糊不清且自相矛盾。</u>\n\n-**contradictory**：<u>矛盾的、自相矛盾的。</u>\n\n---\n\nCertainly, no homework should be assigned that students cannot complete on their own or that they cannot do without expensive equipment.\n翻译: <u>当然，不应布置学生无法独立完成的家庭作业，也不应布置他们没有昂贵设备就无法完成的作业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut if <font color=\"#ffff00\">the district</font> is essentially giving a pass to students who do not do their homework because of complicated family lives, it is going riskily close to the implication that standards need to be lowered for poor children.\n翻译: <u>但是，如果学区实际上是在让那些因家庭生活复杂而不做家庭作业的学生过关，那么它就危险地接近于暗示需要为贫困儿童降低标准。</u>\n\n-**the district**：<u>该学区，指 L.A. Unified。</u>\n-**give a pass to someone**：<u>放过某人、不追究某人、给某人通融。</u>\n\n---\n\nDistrict administrators say that homework will still be a part of schooling; teachers are allowed to assign as much of it as they want.\n翻译: <u>学区管理者说，家庭作业仍将是学校教育的一部分；教师可以布置任意多的家庭作业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut with homework counting for no more than 10% of their grades, students can easily skip half their homework and see very little difference on their report cards.\n翻译: <u>但是，由于家庭作业在成绩中所占比例不超过10%，学生很容易不做一半家庭作业，而在成绩单上几乎看不出什么差别。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome students might do well on state tests without completing their homework, but what about the students who performed well on the tests and did their homework?\n翻译: <u>有些学生也许不完成家庭作业也能在州考试中表现良好，但那些考试表现良好并且完成了家庭作业的学生又该如何看待呢？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is <font color=\"#ffff00\">quite possible</font> that the homework helped.\n翻译: <u>家庭作业很可能起了帮助作用。</u>\n\n-**quite possible**：<u>相当可能、完全可能。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet rather than <font color=\"#ffff00\">empowering</font> teachers to find what works best for their students, the policy imposes a flat, <font color=\"#ffff00\">across-the-board</font> rule.\n翻译: <u>然而，这项政策并没有赋权教师去寻找最适合其学生的方法，而是强加了一条一刀切的统一规则。</u>\n\n-**empower**：<u>赋权、授权。</u>\n-**flat rule**：<u>一刀切的规则。</u>\n-**across-the-board**：<u>全面适用的、统一的。</u>\n\n---\n\nAt the same time, the policy <font color=\"#ffff00\">addresses</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">none of</font> the truly thorny questions about homework.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，这项政策没有解决任何关于家庭作业的真正棘手问题。</u>\n\n-**address**：<u>处理、解决。</u>\n-**none of…**：<u>没有任何……。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf the district finds homework to be unimportant to its students’ academic achievement, it should move to reduce or eliminate the assignments, not make them count for almost nothing.\n翻译: <u>如果学区认为家庭作业对学生的学业成就并不重要，它就应当着手减少或取消这些作业，而不是让它们几乎不计入成绩。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Conversely</font>, if homework matters, it should account for a significant portion of the grade.\n翻译: <u>反过来说，如果家庭作业重要，它就应当占成绩的相当大一部分。</u>\n\n-**Conversely**：<u>相反地、反过来；实际上是补充说明</u>\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, this policy does nothing to ensure that the homework students receive is meaningful or appropriate to their age and the subject, or that teachers are not assigning more than they are willing to review and correct.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，这项政策并没有采取任何措施来确保学生收到的家庭作业是有意义的，或适合他们的年龄和所学科目，也没有确保教师布置的作业不超过他们愿意审阅和批改的数量。</u>\n\n-**be willing to review and correct**：<u>愿意检查和批改；这一整句很好 可以研读一下</u>\n\n---\n\nThe homework rules <font color=\"#ffff00\">should be put on hold</font> while the school board, which is responsible for setting educational policy, <font color=\"#ffff00\">looks into the matter</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">conducts public hearings</font>.\n翻译: <u>家庭作业规定应当暂缓执行，同时由负责制定教育政策的学校董事会调查此事并举行公开听证会。</u>\n\n-**should be put on hold**：<u>应该被暂停、暂缓。</u>\n-**look into the matter**：<u>调查此事。</u>\n-**conduct public hearings**：<u>举行公开听证会。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is not too late for L.A. Unified to <font color=\"#ffff00\">do homework right</font>.\n翻译: <u>对于洛杉矶联合学区来说，现在把家庭作业问题处理好还不算太晚。</u>\n\n-**do homework right**：<u>把作业问题做好 / 正确处理作业。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Pretty in pink</font>: adult women do not remember being so obsessed with the colour, yet it is <font color=\"#ffff00\">pervasive</font> in our young girls’ lives.\n翻译: <u>粉红真漂亮：成年女性并不记得自己曾如此痴迷于这种颜色，然而它却在我们年幼女孩的生活中无处不在。</u>\n\n-**pretty in pink**：<u>是常见表达，意思是“穿粉色很好看”。</u>\n-**it**：<u>指 pink。</u>\n-**pervasive**：<u>it 指 pink。pervasive：无处不在的、弥漫性的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is not that pink is intrinsically bad, but it is such a tiny slice of the rainbow and, though it may <font color=\"#ffff00\">celebrate girlhood</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">in one way</font>, it also <font color=\"#ffff00\">repeatedly</font> and firmly fuses girls’ identity to appearance.\n翻译: <u>并不是说粉红色本质上不好，而是它只是彩虹中极小的一部分；而且，尽管它可能以某种方式赞美女孩时代，它也一再而坚定地把女孩的身份与外貌联系在一起。</u>\n\n-**celebrate girlhood**：<u>赞美女孩时期 / 女孩身份。</u>\n-**in one way**：<u>在某种意义上。</u>\n-**repeatedly**：<u>反复地。</u>\n-**fuse A to B**：<u>把 A 和 B 融合/绑定在一起。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Then</font> it presents that connection, even among <font color=\"#ffff00\">two-year-olds</font>, between girls as not only innocent but as evidence of innocence.\n翻译: <u>随后，它把这种联系，即便是在两岁儿童之间、在女孩之间的联系，呈现为不仅是天真的，而且是天真的证据。</u>\n\n-**Then**：<u>然后、接着。</u>\n-**two-year-olds**：<u>两岁的孩子。</u>\n\n---\n\nLooking around, I <font color=\"#ffff00\">despaired at</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">singular</font> lack of imagination about girls’ lives and interests.\n翻译: <u>环顾四周，我对人们关于女孩生活和兴趣的想象力如此单一匮乏感到绝望。</u>\n\n-**despair at…**：<u>对……感到绝望。</u>\n-**singular**：<u>特别的、异常的。</u>\n\n---\n\nGirls’ attraction to pink may seem unavoidable, somehow encoded in their DNA, but according to Jo Paoletti, an associate professor of American Studies, it is not.\n翻译: <u>女孩对粉红色的喜爱似乎不可避免，仿佛以某种方式写在她们的DNA里，但根据美国研究副教授Jo Paoletti的说法，并非如此。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nChildren were not colour-coded at all until the early 20th century: in the era before domestic washing machines all babies wore white <font color=\"#ffff00\">as a practical matter</font>, since the only way of getting clothes clean was to boil them.\n翻译: <u>直到20世纪初，儿童根本没有按颜色来区分性别：在家用洗衣机出现以前的时代，所有婴儿出于实际考虑都穿白色，因为让衣服洗干净的唯一办法就是煮沸。</u>\n\n-**as a practical matter**：<u>出于实际考虑。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat’s more, both boys and girls wore what were thought of as gender-neutral dresses.\n翻译: <u>此外，男孩和女孩都穿当时被认为是性别中性的连衣裙。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen <font color=\"#ffff00\">nursery colours</font> were introduced, pink was actually considered the more masculine colour, a <font color=\"#ffff00\">pastel</font> version of red, which was associated with strength.\n翻译: <u>当婴儿房颜色被引入时，粉红色实际上被认为是更具男性气质的颜色，是红色的浅淡版本，而红色与力量相关。</u>\n\n-**nursery colours**：<u>婴儿房颜色 / 儿童房配色。</u>\n-**pastel**：<u>柔和淡色的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBlue, <font color=\"#ffff00\">with its intimations of</font> the Virgin Mary, <font color=\"#ffff00\">constancy</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">faithfulness</font>, symbolised femininity.\n翻译: <u>蓝色因其让人联想到圣母玛利亚、恒常和忠诚，象征着女性气质。</u>\n\n-**with its intimations of…**：<u>带有对……的暗示/联想。</u>\n-**constancy**：<u>坚定、恒久。</u>\n-**faithfulness**：<u>忠诚。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt was <font color=\"#ffff00\">not until</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the mid-1980s</font>, when amplifying age and sex differences became a dominant children’s marketing strategy, that pink fully came into its own, when it began to seem inherently attractive to girls, part of what defined them as female, at least for the first few <font color=\"#ffff00\">critical years</font>.\n翻译: <u>直到20世纪80年代中期，当放大年龄和性别差异成为儿童营销的主导策略时，粉红色才充分确立了自己的地位；那时它开始显得天生对女孩有吸引力，成为定义她们为女性的一部分，至少在最初几个关键年份如此。</u>\n\n-**not until**：<u>强调“时间很晚”。</u>\n-**the mid-1980s**：<u>not until 强调“时间很晚”。the mid-1980s：20 世纪 80 年代中期。</u>\n-**come into one’s own**：<u>充分发挥作用、得到应有地位、真正成熟起来。</u>\n-**critical years**：<u>关键年份。</u>\n\n---\n\nI had not realised <font color=\"#ffff00\">how profoundly</font> marketing trends dictated our perception of what is natural to kids, including our core beliefs about their psychological development.\n翻译: <u>我此前没有意识到，营销趋势在多么深刻地支配着我们对于什么对孩子来说是自然的这一认知，包括我们关于他们心理发展的核心信念。</u>\n\n-**how profoundly**：<u>多么深刻地。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Take</font> the toddler.\n翻译: <u>以“学步儿童”这个概念为例。</u>\n\n-**Take…**：<u>在文章中常用来引出例子；不是“拿走幼儿”，而是</u>\n\n---\n\nI assumed that phase was something experts developed after years of research into children’s behaviour: <font color=\"#ffff00\">wrong</font>.\n翻译: <u>我原以为这个阶段是专家们经过多年研究儿童行为后提出的：错了。</u>\n\n-**wrong**：<u>是作者对自己假设的否定；完整可理解为</u>\n\n---\n\nTurns out, according to Daniel Cook, a historian of <font color=\"#ffff00\">childhood consumerism</font>, it was popularised as a marketing trick by clothing manufacturers in the 1930s.\n翻译: <u>结果证明，根据童年消费主义历史学家Daniel Cook的说法，它是在20世纪30年代由服装制造商作为一种营销手段推广开来的。</u>\n\n-**childhood consumerism**：<u>儿童消费主义，即围绕儿童展开的消费文化。</u>\n\n---\n\nTrade publications <font color=\"#ffff00\">counselled</font> department stores that, in order to increase sales, they should create a “<font color=\"#ffff00\">third stepping stone</font>” between infant wear and older kids’ clothes.\n翻译: <u>行业出版物建议百货商店，为了增加销售，应当在婴儿服装和较大儿童服装之间创造一个“第三块垫脚石”。</u>\n\n-**counselled**：<u>建议、劝告。</u>\n-**third stepping stone**：<u>第三块踏脚石 / 第三个过渡阶段；这是比喻，指在婴儿服装和大童服装之间创造一个新商品类别</u>\n\n---\n\nIt was only after “toddler” became a common shoppers’ term that it evolved into a broadly accepted developmental stage.\n翻译: <u>只有在“学步儿童”成为购物者常用术语之后，它才演变为一个被广泛接受的发展阶段。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSplitting kids, or adults, into ever-tinier categories has proved a <font color=\"#ffff00\">sure-fire</font> way to boost profits.\n翻译: <u>事实证明，把儿童或成年人划分成越来越细小的类别，是提高利润的可靠办法。</u>\n\n-**sure-fire**：<u>一定成功的、万无一失的。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd one of the easiest ways to segment a market is to magnify gender differences – or invent them where they did not previously exist.\n翻译: <u>而细分市场最容易的方法之一，就是放大性别差异，或者在原本不存在性别差异的地方发明出这些差异。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nIn 2010, a federal judge shook America’s biotech industry to its core.\n翻译: <u>2010年，一名联邦法官动摇了美国生物技术行业的根基。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCompanies had won patents for <font color=\"#ffff00\">isolated DNA</font> for decades – by 2005 some 20% of human genes were patented.\n翻译: <u>数十年来，公司一直获得分离DNA的专利；到2005年，约20%的人类基因已经被授予专利。</u>\n\n-**isolated DNA**：<u>分离出来的 DNA，即从人体/自然环境中分离并纯化出来的 DNA 分子。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut in March 2010 a judge ruled that genes were unpatentable.\n翻译: <u>但在2010年3月，一名法官裁定基因不可申请专利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Executives</font> were <font color=\"#ffff00\">violently</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">agitated</font>.\n翻译: <u>企业高管们极为不安。</u>\n\n-**Executives**：<u>企业高管。</u>\n-**violently**：<u>强烈地、剧烈地。</u>\n-**agitated**：<u>激动的、不安的、焦躁的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Biotechnology Industry Organisation (BIO), a trade group, assured members that this was just a “preliminary step” in a longer battle.\n翻译: <u>行业组织生物技术产业组织（BIO）向会员保证，这只是更长斗争中的一个“初步步骤”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOn July 29th they were relieved, at least temporarily.\n翻译: <u>7月29日，他们松了一口气，至少暂时如此。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal appeals court</font> overturned the prior decision, ruling that Myriad Genetics could indeed hold patents to two genes that help forecast a woman’s risk of breast cancer.\n翻译: <u>一家联邦上诉法院推翻了此前的裁决，裁定Myriad Genetics确实可以持有两种基因的专利，而这两种基因有助于预测女性患乳腺癌的风险。</u>\n\n-**federal appeals court**：<u>联邦上诉法院。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe chief executive of Myriad, a company in Utah, said the ruling was a blessing to <font color=\"#ffff00\">firms and patients alike</font>.\n翻译: <u>位于犹他州的Myriad公司首席执行官表示，这一裁决对公司和患者都是福音。</u>\n\n-**firms and patients alike**：<u>公司和患者都一样。</u>\n-**alike**：<u>放在名词后，表示“两者都”。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut as companies continue their attempts at <font color=\"#ffff00\">personalised medicine</font>, the courts will remain <font color=\"#ffff00\">rather busy</font>.\n翻译: <u>但是，随着公司继续尝试个性化医疗，法院仍将相当忙碌。</u>\n\n-**personalised medicine**：<u>个性化医疗，即根据个人基因、体质、疾病风险来定制治疗或检测。</u>\n-**rather busy**：<u>相当忙。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The Myriad case</font> itself is probably not over.\n翻译: <u>Myriad案本身很可能还没有结束。</u>\n\n-**The Myriad case**：<u>Myriad 案。</u>\n\n---\n\nCritics make three main arguments against gene patents: a gene is a product of nature, so it may not be patented; gene patents suppress innovation rather than reward it; and <font color=\"#ffff00\">patents’ monopolies</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">restrict access to</font> genetic tests such as Myriad’s.\n翻译: <u>批评者提出了反对基因专利的三个主要论点：基因是自然产物，因此不得申请专利；基因专利压制创新，而不是奖励创新；以及专利所带来的垄断限制了人们获得基因检测的机会，例如Myriad的检测。</u>\n\n-**patents’ monopolies**：<u>专利带来的垄断。</u>\n-**restrict access to…**：<u>限制获得……的机会。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">A growing number</font> seem to agree.\n翻译: <u>似乎有越来越多的人同意这一观点。</u>\n\n-**a growing number**：<u>越来越多的人 / 越来越多的机构。</u>\n\n---\n\nLast year a <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal task-force</font> urged reform for patents related to genetic tests.\n翻译: <u>去年，一个联邦特别工作组敦促对与基因检测相关的专利进行改革。</u>\n\n-**federal task-force**：<u>联邦特别工作组 / 专门小组。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn October the Department of Justice <font color=\"#ffff00\">filed a brief</font> in the Myriad case, arguing that an <font color=\"#ffff00\">isolated DNA molecule</font> “is <font color=\"#ffff00\">no less a product of nature…than</font> are cotton fibres that have been separated from cotton seeds.”\n翻译: <u>10月，司法部在Myriad案中提交了一份意见书，主张一段分离出来的DNA分子“并不比从棉籽中分离出来的棉纤维更少是自然产物”。</u>\n\n-**file a brief**：<u>提交法律意见书/诉讼书状。</u>\n-**isolated DNA molecule**：<u>分离 DNA 分子。</u>\n-**no less a product of nature than…**：<u>并不比……更少是自然产物；也就是“同样是自然产物”。</u>\n\n---\n\nDespite the appeals court’s decision, big questions remain unanswered.\n翻译: <u>尽管上诉法院作出了裁决，重大问题仍未得到回答。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFor example, it is unclear whether the <font color=\"#ffff00\">sequencing</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">a whole genome</font> violates the patents of individual genes <font color=\"#ffff00\">within it</font>.\n翻译: <u>例如，尚不清楚对整个基因组进行测序是否侵犯其中单个基因的专利。</u>\n\n-**sequencing**：<u>测序。</u>\n-**a whole genome**：<u>整个基因组。</u>\n-**within it**：<u>在其中，it 指 whole genome。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe case <font color=\"#ffff00\">may yet</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">reach the Supreme Court</font>.\n翻译: <u>此案或许还会提交至最高法院。</u>\n\n-**may yet**：<u>仍有可能、到头来可能。</u>\n-**reach the Supreme Court**：<u>进入最高法院审理。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs the industry advances, however, other suits may have an even greater impact.\n翻译: <u>然而，随着该行业的发展，其他诉讼可能会产生甚至更大的影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCompanies are unlikely to file <font color=\"#ffff00\">many more patents</font> for human DNA molecules – most are already patented or in the public domain.\n翻译: <u>公司不太可能再为人类 DNA 分子申请更多专利，因为大多数已经获得专利，或者处于公共领域。</u>\n\n-**many more patents**：<u>更多大量专利。</u>\n\n---\n\nFirms are now studying how genes interact, looking for correlations that might be used to determine the causes of disease or <font color=\"#ffff00\">predict a drug’s efficacy</font>.\n翻译: <u>公司如今正在研究基因如何相互作用，寻找可能被用来确定疾病成因或预测药物疗效的相关性。</u>\n\n-**predict a drug’s efficacy**：<u>预测一种药物的疗效。</u>\n\n---\n\nCompanies are eager to win patents for “<font color=\"#ffff00\">connecting the dots</font>,” explains Hans Sauer, a lawyer for the BIO.\n翻译: <u>BIO 的律师汉斯·绍尔解释说，公司急于为“把各个点连接起来”赢得专利。</u>\n\n-**connecting the dots**：<u>把点连起来，指发现不同基因、疾病、药物反应之间的联系。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir success <font color=\"#ffff00\">may be determined by</font> a suit related to this issue, <font color=\"#ffff00\">brought by</font> the Mayo Clinic, which the Supreme Court will hear <font color=\"#ffff00\">in its next term</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们能否成功，可能取决于梅奥诊所提起的一起与这一问题有关的诉讼，最高法院将在下一个任期审理此案。</u>\n\n-**may be determined by…**：<u>可能由……决定。</u>\n-**brought by…**：<u>由……提出/提起。</u>\n-**in its next term**：<u>在其下一审期/任期。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe BIO recently held a convention which included <font color=\"#ffff00\">sessions</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">coach lawyers on</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">shifting landscape</font> for patents.\n翻译: <u>BIO 最近举办了一次大会，其中包括一些会议，用来指导律师了解专利领域不断变化的格局。</u>\n\n-**sessions**：<u>会议环节、专题场次。</u>\n-**coach lawyers on…**：<u>培训律师关于……。</u>\n-**shifting landscape**：<u>不断变化的格局。</u>\n\n---\n\nEach meeting was <font color=\"#ffff00\">packed</font>.\n翻译: <u>每场会议都座无虚席。</u>\n\n-**packed**：<u>挤满人的、爆满的。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nThe great recession may be over, but this era of <font color=\"#ffff00\">high joblessness</font> is probably beginning.\n翻译: <u>大衰退也许已经结束，但这个高失业率时代很可能才刚刚开始。</u>\n\n-**high joblessness**：<u>高失业状态。</u>\n\n---\n\nBefore it ends, it will likely change the <font color=\"#ffff00\">life course</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">character</font> of a generation of young adults.\n翻译: <u>在它结束之前，它很可能会改变一代年轻成年人的人生轨迹和性格特征。</u>\n\n-**life course**：<u>人生进程、人生轨迹。</u>\n-**character**：<u>性格、品格、精神面貌。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd ultimately, it is likely to reshape our politics, our culture, and the character of our society <font color=\"#ffff00\">for years</font>.\n翻译: <u>而且最终，它很可能会在多年内重塑我们的政治、文化以及我们社会的特征。</u>\n\n-**for years**：<u>多年。</u>\n\n---\n\nNo one tries harder than the jobless to find <font color=\"#ffff00\">silver linings</font> in this national economic disaster.\n翻译: <u>在这场全国性的经济灾难中，没有人比失业者更努力地去寻找一线希望。</u>\n\n-**silver lining**：<u>困境中的积极面、一线希望；完整表达常来自谚语：Every cloud has a silver lining</u>\n\n---\n\nMany said that unemployment, while extremely painful, had improved them in some ways: they had become less materialistic and more <font color=\"#ffff00\">financially prudent</font>; they were more aware of the struggles of others.\n翻译: <u>许多人说，失业虽然极其痛苦，却在某些方面改善了他们：他们变得不那么物质主义，也更加审慎理财；他们更加意识到他人的艰难处境。</u>\n\n-**financially prudent**：<u>财务上更谨慎。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn <font color=\"#ffff00\">limited respects</font>, perhaps the recession will leave society better off.\n翻译: <u>在有限的方面，也许这场衰退会让社会变得更好。</u>\n\n-**limited respects**：<u>有限方面、某些局部方面。</u>\n\n---\n\nAt the very least, it has awoken us from our national fever dream of easy riches and bigger houses, and put a necessary end to an era of <font color=\"#ffff00\">reckless personal spending</font>.\n翻译: <u>至少，它已经把我们从那种轻松致富和拥有更大房子的全国性狂热幻梦中唤醒，并且给一个不计后果的个人消费时代画上了必要的句号。</u>\n\n-**put an end to…**：<u>终结……。</u>\n-**reckless personal spending**：<u>鲁莽的个人消费、无节制消费。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">for the most part</font>, these benefits seem thin, uncertain, and far off.\n翻译: <u>但在很大程度上，这些好处似乎微弱、不确定，而且遥远。</u>\n\n-**for the most part**：<u>总体上、大体上。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn <font color=\"#ffff00\">The Moral Consequences of Economic Growth</font>, the economic historian Benjamin Friedman argues that both inside and outside the U.S., lengthy periods of economic stagnation or decline have almost always left society more <font color=\"#ffff00\">mean-spirited</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">less inclusive</font>, and have usually stopped or reversed the advance of rights and freedoms.\n翻译: <u>在《经济增长的道德后果》一书中，经济史学家本杰明·弗里德曼认为，无论在美国国内还是美国以外，长期的经济停滞或衰退几乎总是使社会变得更加刻薄、更加缺乏包容性，并且通常会阻止或逆转权利与自由的进步。</u>\n\n-**The Moral Consequences of Economic Growth**：<u>书名，可译为《经济增长的道德后果》。</u>\n-**mean-spirited**：<u>心胸狭窄的、刻薄的、缺乏宽厚精神的。</u>\n-**less inclusive**：<u>更不包容的。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnti-immigrant sentiment typically increases, <font color=\"#ffff00\">as does conflict between races and classes</font>.\n翻译: <u>反移民情绪通常会增加，种族和阶级之间的冲突也会增加。</u>\n\n-**as + 助动词 + 主语**：<u>表示“……也是如此”。</u>\n\n---\n\nIncome inequality usually falls during a recession, but it has not shrunk in this one.\n翻译: <u>收入不平等通常会在经济衰退期间下降，但在这次衰退中并没有缩小。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIndeed, this period of economic weakness may reinforce class divides, and decrease opportunities to cross them – especially for young people.\n翻译: <u>事实上，这一经济疲弱时期可能会强化阶级分化，并减少跨越这些分化的机会，尤其是对年轻人而言。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe research of Till Von Wachter, the economist at Columbia University, suggests that not all people graduating into a recession see their life chances dimmed: those with degrees from elite universities catch up fairly quickly to where they <font color=\"#ffff00\">otherwise</font> would have been if they had graduated in better times; it is the masses beneath them that are left behind.\n翻译: <u>哥伦比亚大学经济学家蒂尔·冯·瓦赫特的研究表明，并非所有在经济衰退时期毕业的人都会看到自己的人生机会变得暗淡：那些拥有精英大学学位的人会相当迅速地赶上他们如果在更好的时期毕业本来会达到的位置；被落下的是他们之下的大多数人。</u>\n\n-**otherwise**：<u>在另一种情况下；这里指“如果不是遇到衰退”。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the Internet age, it is particularly easy to see the resentment that has always been hidden within American society.\n翻译: <u>在互联网时代，人们特别容易看到一直隐藏在美国社会内部的怨恨。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMore difficult, <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the moment</font>, is <font color=\"#ffff00\">discerning</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">precisely</font> how these <font color=\"#ffff00\">lean times</font> are affecting society’s character.\n翻译: <u>在当下，更难的是准确辨明这些艰难时期正在如何影响社会的性格。</u>\n\n-**in the moment**：<u>在当下、眼下。</u>\n-**discern**：<u>辨别、看清、判断。</u>\n-**precisely**：<u>准确地。</u>\n-**lean times**：<u>艰难时期、经济拮据时期。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn many respects, the U.S. was more socially tolerant entering this recession than at any time in its history, and a variety of national polls on social conflict <font color=\"#ffff00\">since then</font> have shown <font color=\"#ffff00\">mixed results</font>.\n翻译: <u>在许多方面，美国进入这场衰退时比其历史上任何时候都更加具有社会宽容度，而此后关于社会冲突的各种全国性民调显示出了混合的结果。</u>\n\n-**since then**：<u>自那以来。</u>\n-**mixed results**：<u>结果不一、有好有坏、不明确。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe will have to wait and see exactly how these hard times will reshape our <font color=\"#ffff00\">social fabric</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们将不得不等待并观察这些艰难时期究竟会如何重塑我们的社会结构。</u>\n\n-**social fabric**：<u>社会结构、社会纽带、社会肌理。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut they certainly will reshape it, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">all the more so</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the longer they extend</font>.\n翻译: <u>但它们肯定会重塑这种结构，而且持续得越久，重塑得就越明显。</u>\n\n-**all the more so**：<u>更加如此、尤其如此。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2013","year":"2013","title":"2013 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2013 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2013 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIn an essay entitled “Making It in America,” the author Adam Davidson <font color=\"#ffff00\">relates</font> a joke from <font color=\"#ffff00\">cotton country</font> about just how much a modern textile mill has been automated: The <font color=\"#ffff00\">average mill</font> has only two employees today, “a man and a dog.\n翻译: <u>在一篇题为《在美国成功》的文章中，作者亚当·戴维森讲述了一个来自棉花产区的笑话，说明现代纺织厂已经自动化到了何种程度：如今普通工厂只有两名员工，“一个人和一条狗。</u>\n\n-**relates**：<u>讲述、叙述（作动词）。</u>\n-**cotton country**：<u>棉花产区（指美国南部依赖棉花和纺织的地区）。</u>\n-**average mill**：<u>普通的、平均水平的工厂。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe man is there to feed the dog, and the dog is there to keep the man away from the machines.”\n翻译: <u>人在那里是为了喂狗，狗在那里是为了让人远离机器。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDavidson’s article is one of <font color=\"#ffff00\">a number of pieces</font> that have recently appeared making the point that the reason we have such stubbornly high unemployment and declining middle-class incomes today is largely because of the big drop in demand because of the Great Recession, but it is also because of the advances in both globalization and the information technology revolution, which are more rapidly than ever replacing labor with machines or foreign workers.\n翻译: <u>戴维森的文章是最近出现的多篇文章之一，这些文章都指出，我们今天之所以有如此顽固的高失业率和不断下降的中产阶级收入，主要是因为大衰退导致需求大幅下降，但也因为全球化和信息技术革命的推进，它们正以前所未有的速度用机器或外国工人取代劳动力。</u>\n\n-**a number of pieces**：<u>许多篇文章（pieces 指代 articles）。</u>\n-**make the point that**：<u>提出……的观点。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the past, workers with average skills, doing an average job, could earn an average lifestyle.\n翻译: <u>过去，拥有普通技能、从事普通工作的工人，可以挣得一种普通的生活方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut, today, average is <font color=\"#ffff00\">officially over</font>.\n翻译: <u>但是，如今，普通已经正式终结。</u>\n\n-**officially over**：<u>正式结束。</u>\n\n---\n\nBeing average just won’t earn you what it used to.\n翻译: <u>保持普通再也不能让你挣到过去那样的收入。</u>\n\n-**what it used to (earn)**：<u>它过去所能赚得的（东西）。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt can’t when so many more employers have so much more access to so much more above average cheap foreign labor, cheap robotics, cheap software, cheap automation and cheap genius.\n翻译: <u>当多得多的雇主能够多得多地接触到多得多的高于平均水平的廉价外国劳动力、廉价机器人、廉价软件、廉价自动化以及廉价天才时，它就不可能做到这一点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTherefore, everyone needs to find their extra – their unique value contribution that makes them stand out in <font color=\"#ffff00\">whatever is</font> their field of employment.\n翻译: <u>因此，每个人都需要找到自己的额外之处，也就是自己独特的价值贡献，使自己无论在哪个就业领域都能脱颖而出。</u>\n\n-**whatever is...**：<u>无论什么（领域）。</u>\n\n---\n\nYes, new technology has been eating jobs forever, and always will.\n翻译: <u>是的，新技术一直在吞噬工作岗位，而且永远会如此。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut there’s been an acceleration.\n翻译: <u>但这种趋势已经加速。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs Davidson notes, “In the 10 years <font color=\"#ffff00\">ending in 2009</font>, [U.S.] factories shed workers so fast that they erased almost all the <font color=\"#ffff00\">gains</font> of the previous 70 years; roughly one out of every three manufacturing jobs – about 6 million in total – disappeared.”\n翻译: <u>正如戴维森所指出的，“截至 2009 年的 10 年里，[美国]工厂裁减工人的速度如此之快，以至于几乎抹去了此前 70 年的所有增长；大约每三个制造业岗位中就有一个，总计约 600 万个，消失了。”</u>\n\n-**ending in 2009**：<u>以2009年为结尾的。</u>\n-**gains**：<u>增长、收益（这里指就业岗位的增加积累）。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere will always be change – new jobs, new products, new services.\n翻译: <u>变化总会存在，包括新的工作、新的产品、新的服务。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the one thing we know for sure is that with each advance in globalization and the I. T. revolution, the best jobs will require workers to have more and better education to make themselves above average.\n翻译: <u>但我们确定知道的一件事是，随着全球化和信息技术革命的每一次推进，最好的工作将要求劳动者拥有更多、更好的教育，以使自己高于平均水平。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn a world <font color=\"#ffff00\">where average is officially over</font>, there are many things we need to do to support employment, but nothing would be more important than passing some kind of <font color=\"#ffff00\">G. I. Bill</font> for the 21st century that ensures that every American has access to <font color=\"#ffff00\">post-high school education</font>.\n翻译: <u>在一个“普通”已经正式终结的世界里，我们需要做很多事情来支持就业，但没有什么比通过某种面向 21 世纪的《退伍军人权利法案》更重要，这项法案要确保每个美国人都能接受高中后的教育。</u>\n\n-**where average is officially over**：<u>修饰 world 的定语从句。</u>\n-**G. I. Bill**：<u>《退伍军人权利法案》。</u>\n-**post-high school education**：<u>高中毕业后的教育（大学、职业培训等高等教育）。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nA century ago, the immigrants <font color=\"#ffff00\">from across the Atlantic</font> included <font color=\"#ffff00\">settlers</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">sojourners</font>.\n翻译: <u>一个世纪以前，来自大西洋彼岸的移民中既有定居者，也有旅居者。</u>\n\n-**from across the Atlantic**：<u>来自大西洋彼岸。</u>\n-**settlers**：<u>定居者，打算长期留下来的人。</u>\n-**sojourners**：<u>旅居者、暂住者，指短期停留、赚钱后可能回国的人。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Along with</font> the many <font color=\"#ffff00\">folks</font> looking to make a permanent home in the United States came those who had no intention to stay, and who <font color=\"#ffff00\">would make some money</font> and then go home.\n翻译: <u>伴随着许多希望在美国建立永久家园的人而来的，还有那些无意留下、只想赚些钱然后回家的人。</u>\n\n-**Along with…**：<u>与……一起、除了……之外还有。</u>\n-**folks**：<u>人们，较口语。</u>\n-**would make some money**：<u>会赚一些钱。</u>\n\n---\n\nBetween 1908 and 1915, about 7 million people arrived while about 2 million departed.\n翻译: <u>1908 年至 1915 年间，大约 700 万人抵达，同时大约 200 万人离开。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAbout a quarter of all Italian immigrants, for example, eventually returned to Italy <font color=\"#ffff00\">for good</font>.\n翻译: <u>例如，大约四分之一的意大利移民最终永久返回了意大利。</u>\n\n-**for good**：<u>永久地、永远地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey even had an <font color=\"#ffff00\">affectionate nickname</font>, “uccelli di passaggio,” <font color=\"#ffff00\">birds of passage</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们甚至有一个亲切的昵称，“uccelli di passaggio”，即候鸟。</u>\n\n-**affectionate nickname**：<u>亲切的昵称。</u>\n-**birds of passage**：<u>候鸟，指迁徙鸟。</u>\n\n---\n\nToday, we are much more rigid about immigrants.\n翻译: <u>今天，我们对移民的态度要僵硬得多。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe divide newcomers into two categories: legal or illegal, good or bad.\n翻译: <u>我们把新来者分成两类：合法或非法，好或坏。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe hail them as <font color=\"#ffff00\">Americans in the making</font>, or brand them as aliens to be kicked out.\n翻译: <u>我们把他们称颂为正在形成中的美国人，或者给他们贴上应被驱逐出去的外国人的标签。</u>\n\n-**hail A as B**：<u>把 A 称赞为 B、赞扬 A 是 B。</u>\n-**Americans in the making**：<u>正在成为美国人的人、未来美国人。</u>\n-**brand A as B**：<u>把 A 标记为 B、给 A 贴上负面标签。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">That framework</font> has contributed <font color=\"#ffff00\">mightily</font> to our broken immigration system and the long political paralysis <font color=\"#ffff00\">over how to fix it</font>.\n翻译: <u>这种框架极大地促成了我们破败的移民制度，以及关于如何修复它的长期政治僵局。</u>\n\n-**That framework**：<u>指前面“合法/非法、好/坏、未来美国人/应驱逐外人”的二元分类框架。</u>\n-**contribute to**：<u>导致、促成。</u>\n-**mightily**：<u>极大地、强有力地。</u>\n-**over how to fix it**：<u>关于如何修复它。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe don’t need more categories, but we need to change the way we think about categories.\n翻译: <u>我们不需要更多类别，但我们需要改变思考类别的方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe need to <font color=\"#ffff00\">look beyond</font> strict definitions of legal and illegal.\n翻译: <u>我们需要超越对合法与非法的严格定义。</u>\n\n-**look beyond…**：<u>超越……看问题，不局限于……。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">To start</font>, we can <font color=\"#ffff00\">recognize</font> the new birds of passage, <font color=\"#ffff00\">those living and thriving</font> in the gray areas.\n翻译: <u>首先，我们可以承认新的候鸟，也就是那些生活并兴旺于灰色地带的人。</u>\n\n-**To start**：<u>首先、作为起点。</u>\n-**recognize**：<u>承认、认识到。</u>\n-**those living and thriving…**：<u>那些正在生活并发展的人。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe might <font color=\"#ffff00\">then</font> begin to solve our immigration challenges.\n翻译: <u>那样，我们或许就能开始解决我们的移民挑战。</u>\n\n-**then**：<u>然后，在那之后。</u>\n\n---\n\nCrop pickers, violinists, construction workers, entrepreneurs, engineers, home health-care aides and physicists are among today’s birds of passage.\n翻译: <u>采摘农作物的人、小提琴手、建筑工人、企业家、工程师、家庭医疗护理助理和物理学家，都属于今天的候鸟。</u>\n\n-**be among…**：<u>是……中的一部分。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey are energetic participants in a global economy driven by the flow of work, money and ideas.\n翻译: <u>他们是由工作、金钱和思想流动所驱动的全球经济中的积极参与者。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey prefer to <font color=\"#ffff00\">come and go</font> as <font color=\"#ffff00\">opportunity calls them</font>.\n翻译: <u>他们更愿意随着机会的召唤来来去去。</u>\n\n-**come and go**：<u>来来去去、往返流动。</u>\n-**opportunity calls them**：<u>机会召唤他们；这是一种拟人表达，把 opportunity 当作会“呼唤人”的东西</u>\n\n---\n\nThey can manage to have a job in one place and a family in another.\n翻译: <u>他们能够做到在一个地方工作，而在另一个地方拥有家庭。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWith or without permission, they straddle laws, jurisdictions and identities <font color=\"#ffff00\">with ease</font>.\n翻译: <u>无论有无许可，他们都能轻松跨越法律、司法管辖区和身份认同。</u>\n\n-**with ease**：<u>轻松地。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe need them to imagine the United States as a place where they can be productive for a while without committing themselves to staying forever.\n翻译: <u>我们需要让他们把美国想象成这样一个地方：他们可以在那里高效工作一段时间，而不必承诺永远留下。</u>\n\n-**commit oneself to doing**：<u>承诺做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe need them to feel that home can be both here and there and that they can belong to two nations <font color=\"#ffff00\">honorably</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们需要让他们感到，家既可以在这里，也可以在那里，并且他们可以体面地归属于两个国家。</u>\n\n-**honorably**：<u>体面地、光明正大地、有尊严地。</u>\n\n---\n\nAccommodating this new world of <font color=\"#ffff00\">people in motion</font> will require new attitudes on both sides of the immigration battle.\n翻译: <u>适应这个人们不断流动的新世界，将要求移民争论双方都采取新的态度。</u>\n\n-**accommodate**：<u>适应、容纳、接纳。</u>\n-**people in motion**：<u>流动中的人们。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Looking beyond</font> the culture war logic of right or wrong means <font color=\"#ffff00\">opening up</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">middle ground</font> and understanding that managing immigration today requires multiple paths and multiple outcomes, including some <font color=\"#ffff00\">that are not easy to accomplish legally</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the existing system</font>.\n翻译: <u>超越非对即错的文化战争逻辑，意味着打开中间地带，并理解当今管理移民需要多种路径和多种结果，其中包括一些在现有制度下不容易合法实现的路径和结果。</u>\n\n-**look beyond…**：<u>超越……看问题。</u>\n-**open up**：<u>打开、开辟。</u>\n-**middle ground**：<u>中间地带、折中空间。</u>\n-**that are not easy to accomplish legally**：<u>不容易通过合法方式实现的。</u>\n-**in the existing system**：<u>在现有制度中。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nScientists have found that although we are prone to <font color=\"#ffff00\">snap</font> overreactions, if we take a moment and think about how we are likely to react, we can reduce or even eliminate the negative effects of our quick, hard-wired responses.\n翻译: <u>科学家发现，尽管我们容易做出瞬间的过度反应，但如果我们花一点时间思考自己可能会如何反应，就能减少甚至消除我们快速、本能反应所带来的负面影响。</u>\n\n-**snap**：<u>仓促的、不假思索的（如 snap decision 仓促的决定）。</u>\n\n---\n\nSnap decisions can be important defense mechanisms; if we are judging whether someone is dangerous, our brains and bodies are hard-wired to react very quickly, within <font color=\"#ffff00\">milliseconds</font>.\n翻译: <u>瞬间决定可以是重要的防御机制；如果我们正在判断某个人是否危险，我们的大脑和身体天生就会在几毫秒内非常迅速地作出反应。</u>\n\n-**milliseconds**：<u>毫秒。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut we need more time to assess other factors.\n翻译: <u>但我们需要更多时间来评估其他因素。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTo <font color=\"#ffff00\">accurately tell</font> whether someone is <font color=\"#ffff00\">sociable</font>, studies show, we need at least a minute, <font color=\"#ffff00\">preferably</font> five.\n翻译: <u>研究显示，要准确判断某个人是否善于交际，我们至少需要一分钟，最好是五分钟。</u>\n\n-**accurately tell**：<u>准确地辨别/判断。</u>\n-**sociable**：<u>好交际的、合群的。</u>\n-**preferably**：<u>最好是、更可取地。这里省略了 minutes。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt takes a while to judge complex aspects of personality, like <font color=\"#ffff00\">neuroticism</font> or open\n翻译: <u>判断人格中复杂的方面需要一段时间，比如神经质或开放</u>\n\n-**neuroticism**：<u>神经质（心理学大五人格模型之一）。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut snap decisions in reaction to <font color=\"#ffff00\">rapid stimuli</font> aren’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">exclusive to</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">interpersonal realm</font>.\n翻译: <u>但是，对快速刺激作出反应而形成的瞬间决定并不只限于人际领域。</u>\n\n-**rapid stimuli**：<u>快速的刺激物（stimuli 是 stimulus 的复数）。</u>\n-**exclusive to**：<u>为……所独有的、局限于……的。</u>\n-**interpersonal realm**：<u>人际关系领域。</u>\n\n---\n\nPsychologists at the University of Toronto found that viewing a fast-food logo for just a few milliseconds primes us to read 20 percent faster, even though reading has little to do with eating.\n翻译: <u>多伦多大学的心理学家发现，仅仅看几毫秒快餐标志，就会促使我们阅读速度提高 20%，尽管阅读与吃东西几乎没有关系。</u>\n\n-**have little to do with**：<u>与……几乎没有关系。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe unconsciously associate fast food with speed and impatience and carry those impulses into whatever else we’re doing, <font color=\"#ffff00\">Subjects</font> exposed to fast-food <font color=\"#ffff00\">flashes</font> also tend to think a musical piece lasts too long.\n翻译: <u>我们会无意识地把快餐与速度和不耐烦联系起来，并把这些冲动带入我们正在做的任何其他事情中；接触过快餐闪现画面的受试者也往往会认为一段音乐持续得太久。</u>\n\n-**Subjects**：<u>实验对象、受试者。</u>\n-**flashes**：<u>一闪而过的画面。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet we can reverse such influences.\n翻译: <u>然而，我们可以逆转这类影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIf we know we will <font color=\"#ffff00\">overreact to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">consumer products</font> or housing options when we see a happy face (one reason good sales representatives and real estate agents are always smiling), we can <font color=\"#ffff00\">take a moment</font> before buying.\n翻译: <u>如果我们知道，当看到一张笑脸时，我们会对消费品或住房选择反应过度（这也是优秀销售代表和房地产经纪人总是面带微笑的一个原因），那么我们就可以在购买前停顿片刻。</u>\n\n-**overreact to**：<u>对……反应过度（在这里指盲目冲动消费）。</u>\n-**consumer products**：<u>消费品。</u>\n-**take a moment**：<u>稍等片刻、停顿一下。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf we know female <font color=\"#ffff00\">job screeners</font> are more likely to reject attractive female applicants, we can help screeners understand their biases – or hire <font color=\"#ffff00\">outside screeners</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果我们知道女性招聘筛选人员更有可能拒绝有吸引力的女性申请者，我们就可以帮助筛选人员理解她们的偏见，或者雇用外部筛选人员。</u>\n\n-**job screeners**：<u>招聘筛选人员、简历筛选员。</u>\n-**outside screeners**：<u>外部（第三方）的筛选人员。</u>\n\n---\n\nJohn Gottman, the marriage expert, explains that we quickly “<font color=\"#ffff00\">thin slice</font>” information <font color=\"#ffff00\">reliably</font> only after we ground such snap reactions in “<font color=\"#ffff00\">thick sliced</font>” long-term study.\n翻译: <u>婚姻专家 John Gottman 解释说，只有在我们把这种快速反应建立在“厚切片式”的长期研究基础上之后，我们才能迅速而可靠地对信息进行“薄切片式”判断。</u>\n\n-**reliably**：<u>可靠地、准确无误地。</u>\n-**ground A in B**：<u>把 A 建立在 B 的基础之上、使 A 以 B 为根据。</u>\n-**thick sliced**：<u>厚切的（与前文的 thin slice 形成巧妙对比，指大量、深度的信息积累）。</u>\n-**thin slice**：<u>薄片提取（心理学术语，指通过极少量的信息样本迅速做出准确判断）。这里作动词用。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhen Dr. Gottman really wants to assess whether a couple will stay together, he invites them to his island <font color=\"#ffff00\">retreat</font> for a much longer evaluation: two days, not two seconds.\n翻译: <u>当 Gottman 博士真正想评估一对伴侣是否会继续在一起时，他会邀请他们到自己的岛上静修地进行时间长得多的评估：两天，而不是两秒。</u>\n\n-**retreat**：<u>隐居处、静居处、度假所。</u>\n\n---\n\nOur ability to mute our hard-wired reactions by pausing is what differentiates us from animals: dogs can think about the future only <font color=\"#ffff00\">intermittently</font> or for a few minutes.\n翻译: <u>我们通过暂停来抑制自身固有反应的能力，正是我们区别于动物之处：狗只能间歇地或在几分钟内思考未来。</u>\n\n-**intermittently**：<u>断断续续地、间歇性地。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">historically</font> we have spent about 12 percent of our days <font color=\"#ffff00\">contemplating</font> the longer term.\n翻译: <u>但从历史上看，我们大约把每天 12% 的时间用于思考更长远的事情。</u>\n\n-**historically**：<u>在历史上、一直以来。</u>\n-**contemplating**：<u>深思、盘算（contemplate）。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlthough technology might change the way we react, it hasn’t changed our nature.\n翻译: <u>尽管技术可能会改变我们的反应方式，但它并没有改变我们的本性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe still have the imaginative capacity to <font color=\"#ffff00\">rise above</font> temptation and reverse the high-speed trend.\n翻译: <u>我们仍然具有超越诱惑、逆转高速趋势的想象能力。</u>\n\n-**rise above**：<u>克服、不受……的影响、超脱于……之上。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nEurope is not a gender-equality heaven.\n翻译: <u>欧洲并不是一个性别平等的天堂。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn particular, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">corporate workplace</font> will never be completely family-friendly until women are part of senior management decisions, and Europe’s top <font color=\"#ffff00\">corporate-governance positions</font> remain overwhelmingly male.\n翻译: <u>尤其是，在女性参与高级管理决策之前，企业工作场所永远不会完全对家庭友好，而欧洲企业治理的最高职位仍然绝大多数由男性担任。</u>\n\n-**corporate workplace**：<u>企业职场。</u>\n-**corporate-governance positions**：<u>公司治理职位，如董事会、监事会、高管决策职位等。</u>\n\n---\n\nIndeed, women hold only 14 per cent of positions on European corporate boards.\n翻译: <u>事实上，女性在欧洲企业董事会中只占 14% 的职位。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe European Union is now considering legislation to compel corporate boards to maintain a certain proportion of women – up to 60 per cent.\n翻译: <u>欧盟现在正在考虑立法，强制企业董事会保持一定比例的女性成员，最高可达 60%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis <font color=\"#ffff00\">proposed mandate</font> was born of <font color=\"#ffff00\">frustration</font>.\n翻译: <u>这项拟议中的强制规定源于挫败感。</u>\n\n-**proposed mandate**：<u>拟议中的强制命令/强制规定。</u>\n-**be born of…**：<u>源于……、由……产生。</u>\n-**frustration**：<u>挫败感、失望。</u>\n\n---\n\nLast year, European Commission Vice President Viviane Reding issued a call to voluntary action.\n翻译: <u>去年，欧盟委员会副主席 Viviane Reding 发出了自愿行动的号召。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nReding invited corporations to sign up for gender balance goals of 40 per cent female board membership.\n翻译: <u>Reding 邀请企业签署协议，承诺实现女性董事会成员占 40% 的性别平衡目标。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut her appeal was considered a failure: only 24 companies took it up.\n翻译: <u>但她的呼吁被认为是失败的：只有 24 家公司响应。</u>\n\n-**take it up**：<u>接受、采纳、响应。</u>\n\n---\n\nDo we need <font color=\"#ffff00\">quotas</font> to ensure that women can continue to climb the corporate ladder fairly as they balance work and family?\n翻译: <u>我们是否需要配额来确保女性在平衡工作与家庭的同时，能够继续公平地攀登企业阶梯？</u>\n\n-**quotas**：<u>配额，指法律规定女性在董事会中必须达到一定比例。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Personally, I don’t like quotas,” Reding said recently.\n翻译: <u>“就我个人而言，我不喜欢配额，”Reding 最近说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“But I like <font color=\"#ffff00\">what the quotas do</font>.”\n翻译: <u>“但我喜欢配额所产生的作用。”</u>\n\n-**what the quotas do**：<u>= the things/effects that quotas produce。</u>\n\n---\n\nQuotas get action: they “open the way to equality and they break through the glass ceiling,” according to Reding, a result seen in France and other countries with <font color=\"#ffff00\">legally binding provisions</font> on placing women in top business positions.\n翻译: <u>配额能促成行动：据 Reding 所说，它们“打开通向平等的道路，并打破玻璃天花板”；这一结果已经在法国以及其他对女性进入企业高层职位有法律约束性规定的国家出现。</u>\n\n-**legally binding provisions**：<u>具有法律约束力的条款。</u>\n\n---\n\nI understand Reding’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">reluctance</font> – and her frustration.\n翻译: <u>我理解 Reding 的不情愿，也理解她的挫败感。</u>\n\n-**reluctance**：<u>不情愿、犹豫。</u>\n\n---\n\nI don’t like quotas either; they <font color=\"#ffff00\">run counter to</font> my <font color=\"#ffff00\">belief in meritocracy</font>, governance by the capable.\n翻译: <u>我也不喜欢配额；它们违背了我对精英治理，即由有能力者治理的信念。</u>\n\n-**run counter to…**：<u>与……相违背。</u>\n-**belief in meritocracy**：<u>对任人唯贤/能力主义的信念。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut, when one considers the obstacles to achieving the meritocratic ideal, it does look <font color=\"#ffff00\">as if</font> a fairer world must be temporarily <font color=\"#ffff00\">ordered</font>.\n翻译: <u>但是，当人们考虑到实现精英治理理想所面临的障碍时，情况看起来确实像是：一个更公平的世界必须暂时通过强制安排来建立。</u>\n\n-**as if**：<u>好像、似乎；作者语气是：虽然不情愿，但现实让人觉得必须采取配额等强制措施</u>\n-**ordered**：<u>这里不是“命令”，而是“安排、建立秩序”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">After all</font>, four decades of evidence has now shown that corporations in Europe as well as the US are <font color=\"#ffff00\">evading</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">meritocratic hiring and promotion</font> of women to top positions – no matter how much “soft pressure” is put upon them.\n翻译: <u>毕竟，四十年的证据现在已经表明，无论施加多少“软压力”，欧洲以及美国的企业都在回避按精英原则招聘和晋升女性进入高层职位。</u>\n\n-**After all**：<u>毕竟、终究；作者用证据支持上一句：为什么需要暂时强制安排</u>\n-**evading**：<u>逃避、规避。</u>\n-**meritocratic hiring and promotion**：<u>基于能力的招聘和晋升。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhen women do break through to the summit of corporate power – as, for example, Sheryl Sandberg recently did at Facebook – they attract massive attention <font color=\"#ffff00\">precisely because</font> they <font color=\"#ffff00\">remain</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the exception to the rule</font>.\n翻译: <u>当女性确实突破并登上企业权力顶峰时，例如 Sheryl Sandberg 最近在 Facebook 所做到的那样，她们会吸引大量关注，恰恰是因为她们仍然是规则之外的例外。</u>\n\n-**precisely because**：<u>正是因为。</u>\n-**remain**：<u>仍然是。</u>\n-**the exception to the rule**：<u>规则中的例外。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">If</font> appropriate public policies <font color=\"#ffff00\">were</font> in place to help all women – whether CEOs or their children’s caregivers – and all families, Sandberg <font color=\"#ffff00\">would</font> be no more <font color=\"#ffff00\">newsworthy</font> than any other highly capable person <font color=\"#ffff00\">living in a more just society</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果有适当的公共政策来帮助所有女性，无论是首席执行官还是她们孩子的照护者，并帮助所有家庭，那么 Sandberg 就不会比生活在一个更公正社会中的任何其他极有能力的人更有新闻价值。</u>\n\n-**If…were…would…**：<u>虚拟语气，表示与现实不完全相符的假设。</u>\n-**newsworthy**：<u>有新闻价值的、值得报道的。</u>\n-**living in a more just society**：<u>生活在更公正社会里。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2014","year":"2014","title":"2014 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2014 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2014 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nWhat would you do with $590m?\n翻译: <u>如果你有 5.9 亿美元，你会做什么？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis is now <font color=\"#ffff00\">a question for</font> Gloria MacKenzie, an 84-year-old widow who recently emerged from her small, tin-roofed house in Florida <font color=\"#ffff00\">to collect</font> the <font color=\"#ffff00\">biggest undivided lottery jackpot</font> in history.\n翻译: <u>这现在是 Gloria MacKenzie 面临的问题；她是一位 84 岁的寡妇，最近从她位于佛罗里达、屋顶覆着铁皮的小房子里走出来，领取了历史上金额最大的单人彩票头奖。</u>\n\n-**a question for…**：<u>对……来说的问题。</u>\n-**to collect…**：<u>去领取……。</u>\n-**biggest undivided lottery jackpot**：<u>最大的一笔未分割彩票头奖。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf she hopes her <font color=\"#ffff00\">new-found fortune</font> will yield lasting feelings of fulfilment, she <font color=\"#ffff00\">could do worse than</font> read Happy Money by Elizabeth Dunn and Michael Norton.\n翻译: <u>如果她希望这笔新获得的财富能带来持久的满足感，她大可以读一读 Elizabeth Dunn 和 Michael Norton 所著的《Happy Money》，这不会有什么坏处。</u>\n\n-**new-found fortune**：<u>新获得的财富。</u>\n-**could do worse than…**：<u>字面是“可以做比……更糟的事”，实际意思是“……是个不错的选择 / 不妨……”；这是含蓄推荐</u>\n\n---\n\nThese two academics use an array of behavioral research to <font color=\"#ffff00\">show that</font> the most rewarding ways to spend money can be <font color=\"#ffff00\">counterintuitive</font>.\n翻译: <u>这两位学者利用一系列行为研究表明，最有回报的花钱方式可能是反直觉的。</u>\n\n-**show that…**：<u>说明、证明。</u>\n-**counterintuitive**：<u>反直觉的，不符合一般人的直觉判断。</u>\n\n---\n\nFantasies of great wealth often involve visions of fancy cars and extravagant homes.\n翻译: <u>关于巨额财富的幻想，常常包含对豪华汽车和奢华住宅的想象。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYet <font color=\"#ffff00\">satisfaction with</font> these material purchases <font color=\"#ffff00\">wears off</font> fairly quickly.\n翻译: <u>然而，对这些物质购买所产生的满足感会相当快地消退。</u>\n\n-**satisfaction with…**：<u>对……的满足感。</u>\n-**wear off**：<u>逐渐消退、慢慢失效。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat was once exciting and new becomes old-hat; regret <font color=\"#ffff00\">creeps in</font>.\n翻译: <u>曾经令人兴奋而新鲜的东西会变得老套；后悔会悄然出现。</u>\n\n-**creep in**：<u>悄悄进入、慢慢出现。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is far better to spend money on experiences, say Ms Dunn and Mr Norton, like interesting trips, unique meals or even going to the cinema.\n翻译: <u>Dunn 女士和 Norton 先生说，把钱花在经历上要好得多，比如有趣的旅行、独特的餐食，甚至是去看电影。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThese purchases often become more valuable <font color=\"#ffff00\">with time</font> – as stories or memories – particularly if they involve feeling more connected to others.\n翻译: <u>这些购买往往会随着时间变得更有价值——作为故事或记忆而增值——尤其是在它们涉及与他人产生更紧密联系的感觉时。</u>\n\n-**with time**：<u>随着时间。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">This slim volume</font> is packed with tips to help wage slaves <font color=\"#ffff00\">as well as</font> lottery winners get the most “happiness bang for your buck.”\n翻译: <u>这本薄薄的书充满了各种建议，帮助工薪族以及彩票中奖者最大限度地获得“每一分钱带来的幸福回报”。</u>\n\n-**This slim volume**：<u>这本薄薄的书，指《Happy Money》。</u>\n-**volume**：<u>书、册。</u>\n-**be packed with…**：<u>充满……。</u>\n-**as well as**：<u>以及。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt seems most people would <font color=\"#ffff00\">be better off</font> if they could shorten their commutes to work, spend more time with friends and family and less of it watching television (something the average American spends a whopping two months a year doing, and is hardly jollier <font color=\"#ffff00\">for it</font>).\n翻译: <u>看起来，如果大多数人能够缩短上班通勤时间，多花些时间与朋友和家人在一起，少花些时间看电视，他们会过得更好（普通美国人每年在看电视上花费惊人的两个月时间，却并没有因此快乐多少）。</u>\n\n-**be better off**：<u>处境更好、更幸福、更有利。</u>\n-**jolly**：<u>快乐的。</u>\n-**for it**：<u>因为这件事。</u>\n\n---\n\nBuying gifts or giving to charity is often more pleasurable than purchasing things for oneself, and luxuries are most enjoyable when they are consumed <font color=\"#ffff00\">sparingly</font>.\n翻译: <u>买礼物或向慈善机构捐赠，往往比为自己购买东西更令人愉快；而奢侈品在被节制消费时最令人享受。</u>\n\n-**sparingly**：<u>节制地、少量地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis is apparently the reason McDonald’s restricts the availability of its popular McRib – a marketing trick that has turned the pork sandwich into an <font color=\"#ffff00\">object of obsession</font>.\n翻译: <u>这显然就是麦当劳限制其受欢迎的 McRib 供应的原因，这是一种营销手段，已把这款猪肉三明治变成了令人痴迷的对象。</u>\n\n-**object of obsession**：<u>痴迷对象。</u>\n\n---\n\nReaders of Happy Money are clearly <font color=\"#ffff00\">a privileged lot</font>, anxious about fulfilment, not hunger.\n翻译: <u>《Happy Money》的读者显然是一群享有特权的人，他们焦虑的是满足感，而不是饥饿。</u>\n\n-**a privileged lot**：<u>一群有特权/条件优越的人。</u>\n-**lot**：<u>在这里指“一群人”。</u>\n\n---\n\nMoney may not <font color=\"#ffff00\">quite</font> buy happiness, but people in wealthier countries are generally happier than those in poor ones.\n翻译: <u>金钱也许并不能完全买来幸福，但较富裕国家的人通常比贫穷国家的人更幸福。</u>\n\n-**quite**：<u>完全地、真正地。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet the link between feeling good and spending money on others can be seen among rich and poor people around the world, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">scarcity</font> enhances the pleasure of most things for most people.\n翻译: <u>然而，在世界各地的富人和穷人中，都可以看到良好感受与把钱花在他人身上之间的联系；而稀缺性会增强大多数事物对大多数人的乐趣。</u>\n\n-**scarcity**：<u>稀缺。</u>\n\n---\n\nNot everyone will agree with the authors’ policy ideas, which range from <font color=\"#ffff00\">mandating more holiday time</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">reducing tax incentives</font> for American homebuyers.\n翻译: <u>并非所有人都会同意作者的政策想法，这些想法从强制规定更多假期时间，到减少给予美国购房者的税收激励不等。</u>\n\n-**mandating more holiday time**：<u>强制规定更多假期时间；这两个修饰的都是 policy ideas,相当于对它的展开说明</u>\n-**reducing tax incentives**：<u>减少税收激励。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut most people will <font color=\"#ffff00\">come away from</font> this book believing it was <font color=\"#ffff00\">money well spent</font>.\n翻译: <u>但大多数人读完这本书后都会相信，这钱花得值。</u>\n\n-**come away from…**：<u>从……中离开后带着某种感受、印象或结论。</u>\n-**money well spent**：<u>花得值的钱、物有所值。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nAn article in Scientific American has pointed out that <font color=\"#ffff00\">empirical research</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">says that</font>, actually, you think you’re more beautiful than you are.\n翻译: <u>《Scientific American》上的一篇文章指出，实证研究表明，事实上，你认为自己比实际更漂亮。</u>\n\n-**empirical research**：<u>实证研究，指基于观察、实验和数据的研究。</u>\n-**says that…**：<u>表明……；这里不是研究“说话”，而是“研究结果显示”</u>\n\n---\n\nWe have a deep-seated need to feel good about ourselves and we naturally <font color=\"#ffff00\">employ</font> a number of <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-enhancing strategies</font> to achieve this.\n翻译: <u>我们有一种根深蒂固的需要，即对自己感觉良好；为了实现这一点，我们自然会采用许多自我提升策略。</u>\n\n-**employ**：<u>使用、采用。</u>\n-**self-enhancing strategies**：<u>自我提升/自我美化策略。</u>\n\n---\n\nSocial psychologists <font color=\"#ffff00\">have amassed</font> oceans of research into what they call the “above average effect”, or “illusory superiority”, and shown that, for example, 70% of us rate ourselves as above average in leadership, 93% in driving and 85% at getting on well with others – all obviously <font color=\"#ffff00\">statistical impossibilities</font>.\n翻译: <u>社会心理学家已经积累了大量关于他们所谓“高于平均效应”或“虚幻优越感”的研究，并表明，例如，我们中有 70% 的人认为自己的领导力高于平均水平，93% 的人认为自己的驾驶能力高于平均水平，85% 的人认为自己善于与他人相处，而这些显然在统计上是不可能的。</u>\n\n-**have amassed**：<u>已经积累。</u>\n-**statistical impossibilities**：<u>统计学上不可能的情况。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe rose-tint our memories and put ourselves into <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-affirming situations</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们给自己的记忆加上玫瑰色滤镜，并把自己置于自我肯定的情境中。</u>\n\n-**self-affirming situations**：<u>能肯定自我的情境。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe become defensive when criticised, and apply negative stereotypes to others to boost our own esteem.\n翻译: <u>当受到批评时，我们会变得防御性很强，并把负面刻板印象套用到他人身上，以提升自己的自尊。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe <font color=\"#ffff00\">stalk around</font> thinking we’re hot stuff.\n翻译: <u>我们四处走动，心里觉得自己很了不起。</u>\n\n-**stalk around**：<u>大摇大摆地走来走去、神气地走动。</u>\n\n---\n\nPsychologist and behavioural scientist Nicholas Epley <font color=\"#ffff00\">oversaw</font> a <font color=\"#ffff00\">key study</font> into self-enhancement and <font color=\"#ffff00\">attractiveness</font>.\n翻译: <u>心理学家和行为科学家 Nicholas Epley 主持了一项关于自我提升与吸引力的关键研究。</u>\n\n-**oversaw**：<u>监督、主持。</u>\n-**key study**：<u>关键研究、重要研究。</u>\n-**attractiveness**：<u>吸引力，尤其指外貌吸引力。</u>\n\n---\n\nRather than have people <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply rate their beauty</font> compared with others, he <font color=\"#ffff00\">asked them to identify</font> an original photograph of themselves from a lineup including versions that had been altered to appear more and less attractive.\n翻译: <u>他并没有让人们简单地将自己的美貌与他人相比并打分，而是要求他们从一组照片中识别出自己的原始照片；这组照片包括经过修改、显得更有吸引力和更没有吸引力的版本。</u>\n\n-**simply rate their beauty**：<u>简单评价自己的美貌。</u>\n-**asked them to identify…**：<u>要求他们识别……。</u>\n\n---\n\nVisual recognition, <font color=\"#ffff00\">reads the study</font>, is “an <font color=\"#ffff00\">automatic psychological process</font>, occurring rapidly and <font color=\"#ffff00\">intuitively</font> with little or no apparent conscious deliberation”.\n翻译: <u>该研究写道，视觉识别是“一个自动的心理过程，迅速而直觉地发生，几乎没有或完全没有明显的有意识思考”。</u>\n\n-**reads the study**：<u>是一种倒装报道表达，正常理解为：</u>\n-**the study reads**：<u>= the study says/states。</u>\n-**automatic psychological process**：<u>自动心理过程。</u>\n-**intuitively**：<u>直觉地。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf the subjects quickly chose a <font color=\"#ffff00\">falsely flattering image</font> – which most did – they genuinely believed it was really how they looked.\n翻译: <u>如果受试者迅速选择了一张虚假美化过的照片，而大多数人确实如此，他们就真诚地相信那确实是自己的样子。</u>\n\n-**falsely flattering image**：<u>虚假但美化人的照片。</u>\n\n---\n\nEpley found no <font color=\"#ffff00\">significant</font> gender difference in responses.\n翻译: <u>Epley 发现，在回答中不存在显著的性别差异。</u>\n\n-**significant**：<u>显著的、有统计意义的。</u>\n\n---\n\nNor was there any evidence that those who self-enhanced the most (<font color=\"#ffff00\">that is</font>, the participants who thought the most <font color=\"#ffff00\">positively doctored pictures</font> were real) were doing so to <font color=\"#ffff00\">make up for</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">profound insecurities</font>.\n翻译: <u>也没有任何证据表明，那些自我提升程度最高的人，也就是那些认为被正向修饰得最多的照片是真实照片的参与者，是在通过这样做来弥补深层的不安全感。</u>\n\n-**that is**：<u>也就是说。</u>\n-**positively doctored pictures**：<u>经过正向修改的照片，即被美化的照片。</u>\n-**make up for…**：<u>弥补、补偿。</u>\n-**profound insecurities**：<u>深层不安全感。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn fact, those who thought that the images higher up the attractiveness scale were real directly corresponded with those who showed other <font color=\"#ffff00\">markers</font> for having <font color=\"#ffff00\">higher self-esteem</font>.\n翻译: <u>事实上，那些认为在吸引力等级上更高的照片是真实照片的人，正好对应于那些表现出其他更高自尊标志的人。</u>\n\n-**markers**：<u>标志、指标。</u>\n-**higher self-esteem**：<u>更高自尊。</u>\n\n---\n\n“I don’t think the findings that we have are any evidence of <font color=\"#ffff00\">personal delusion</font>,” says Epley.\n翻译: <u>“我不认为我们得到的发现是个人妄想的任何证据，”Epley 说。</u>\n\n-**personal delusion**：<u>个人妄想。</u>\n\n---\n\n“It’s a reflection <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply</font> of people generally thinking well of themselves.”\n翻译: <u>“它只是反映了人们通常对自己评价良好。”</u>\n\n-**simply**：<u>仅仅、只是。</u>\n-**think well of oneself**：<u>对自己评价好、看得起自己。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf you are depressed, you won’t be self-enhancing.\n翻译: <u>如果你抑郁，你就不会进行自我提升。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nKnowing the results of Epley’s study, it makes sense that many people hate photographs of themselves <font color=\"#ffff00\">viscerally</font> – <font color=\"#ffff00\">on one level</font>, they don’t even recognise the person in the picture as themselves.\n翻译: <u>了解 Epley 研究的结果后，许多人会本能地讨厌自己的照片就说得通了；在某种层面上，他们甚至不把照片里的人认作自己。</u>\n\n-**viscerally**：<u>发自内心地、本能地、强烈地。</u>\n-**on one level**：<u>在某个层面上。</u>\n-**recognise A as B**：<u>把 A 认作 B。</u>\n\n---\n\nFacebook, therefore, is a self-enhancer’s paradise, where people can share only the most flattering photos, <font color=\"#ffff00\">the cream of</font> their wit, style, beauty, <font color=\"#ffff00\">intellect</font> and lifestyles.\n翻译: <u>因此，Facebook 是自我提升者的天堂；在那里，人们可以只分享最讨人喜欢的照片，以及他们机智、风格、美貌、智力和生活方式中最精华的部分。</u>\n\n-**the cream of…**：<u>……的精华、最好的部分。</u>\n-**intellect**：<u>智力、才智。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s not that people’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">profiles</font> are dishonest, says Catalina Toma of Wisconsin-Madison University, “but they portray an idealised version of themselves.”\n翻译: <u>威斯康星大学麦迪逊分校的 Catalina Toma 说，这并不是说人们的个人资料不诚实，“而是它们呈现了一个理想化版本的自我。”</u>\n\n-**profiles**：<u>个人资料页、社交媒体主页。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nThe concept of man versus machine is at least as old as the industrial revolution, but this phenomenon tends to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">most acutely felt</font> during economic downturns and <font color=\"#ffff00\">fragile recoveries</font>.\n翻译: <u>人与机器对立的概念至少和工业革命一样古老，但这种现象往往在经济衰退和脆弱复苏期间被最强烈地感受到。</u>\n\n-**most acutely felt**：<u>被最强烈地感受到。</u>\n-**acutely**：<u>强烈地、敏锐地。</u>\n-**fragile recoveries**：<u>脆弱复苏。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">And yet</font>, it would be a mistake to think we are right now simply experiencing the painful side of a boom and bust cycle.\n翻译: <u>然而，如果认为我们现在只是正在经历繁荣与萧条周期中痛苦的一面，那将是错误的。</u>\n\n-**And yet**：<u>然而、可是。</u>\n\n---\n\nCertain jobs have gone away for good, <font color=\"#ffff00\">outmoded</font> by machines.\n翻译: <u>某些工作已经永远消失，被机器淘汰了。</u>\n\n-**outmoded**：<u>过时的、被淘汰的。</u>\n\n---\n\nSince technology has such an insatiable appetite for eating up human jobs, this phenomenon will continue to restructure our economy in ways we cannot <font color=\"#ffff00\">immediately</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">foresee</font>.\n翻译: <u>由于技术对吞噬人类工作有着如此难以满足的胃口，这一现象将继续以我们无法立即预见的方式重塑我们的经济。</u>\n\n-**technology has an appetite for…**：<u>技术有……胃口，比喻技术不断吸收/取代某类东西。</u>\n-**foresee**：<u>预见。</u>\n-**immediately**：<u>立刻、眼下。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhen there is rapid improvement in the price and performance of technology, jobs that were once thought to be immune from automation suddenly become threatened.\n翻译: <u>当技术的价格和性能迅速改善时，那些曾经被认为不会受到自动化影响的工作，突然就会受到威胁。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis argument has attracted a lot of attention, via the success of the book Race Against the Machine, by Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee, who both <font color=\"#ffff00\">hail from</font> MIT’s Center for Digital Business.\n翻译: <u>由于埃里克·布林约尔松和安德鲁·麦卡菲所著《与机器赛跑》一书的成功，这一论点吸引了大量关注；两位作者都来自麻省理工学院数字商业中心。</u>\n\n-**hail from**：<u>来自。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis is a powerful argument, and a scary one.\n翻译: <u>这是一个有力的论点，也是一个令人害怕的论点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd yet, John Hagel, author of The Power of Pull and other books, says Brynjolfsson and McAfee miss the reason why these jobs are so vulnerable to technology <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the first place</font>.\n翻译: <u>然而，《拉力的力量》等书的作者约翰·哈格尔说，布林约尔松和麦卡菲没有看到这些工作一开始就如此容易受到技术冲击的原因。</u>\n\n-**in the first place**：<u>一开始、从根本上说。</u>\n\n---\n\nHagel says we have designed jobs in the U.S. that tend to be “tightly scripted” and “highly standardized” ones that leave no room for “individual initiative or creativity”.\n翻译: <u>哈格尔说，我们在美国设计出的工作往往是那些“严格按脚本执行”和“高度标准化”的工作，它们不给“个人主动性或创造力”留下空间。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In short</font>, these are the types of jobs that machines can perform much better at than human beings.\n翻译: <u>简而言之，这些正是机器能够比人类做得好得多的工作类型。</u>\n\n-**In short**：<u>简而言之。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat is how we have put a giant target sign on the backs of American workers, Hagel says.\n翻译: <u>哈格尔说，这就是我们如何在美国工人的背上放上了一个巨大的靶标。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt’s time to <font color=\"#ffff00\">reinvent</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the formula</font> for <font color=\"#ffff00\">how work is conducted</font>, since we are still relying on a very 20th century notion of work, Hagel says.\n翻译: <u>哈格尔说，现在是重新发明工作开展方式的公式的时候了，因为我们仍然依赖一种非常20世纪式的工作观念。</u>\n\n-**reinvent**：<u>重新发明、重新设计。</u>\n-**the formula**：<u>公式、模式。</u>\n-**how work is conducted**：<u>工作如何进行。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn our rapidly changing economy, we more than ever need people in the workplace who can <font color=\"#ffff00\">take initiative</font> and exercise their imagination “to respond to unexpected events”.\n翻译: <u>在我们迅速变化的经济中，我们比以往任何时候都更需要职场中那些能够发挥主动性并运用想象力“应对意外事件”的人。</u>\n\n-**take initiative**：<u>主动行动、发挥主动性。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat is not something machines are good at.\n翻译: <u>这并不是机器擅长的事情。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey are designed to perform very predictable activities.\n翻译: <u>机器被设计出来是为了执行非常可预测的活动。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs Hagel notes, Brynjolfsson and McAfee indeed touched on this point in their book.\n翻译: <u>正如哈格尔指出的那样，布林约尔松和麦卡菲确实在他们的书中触及了这一点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe need to reframe <font color=\"#ffff00\">race against the machine</font> as <font color=\"#ffff00\">race with the machine</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们需要把“与机器赛跑”重新界定为“与机器协同赛跑”。</u>\n\n-**reframe A as B**：<u>把 A 重新理解为 B。</u>\n-**race against the machine**：<u>与机器竞争/对抗。</u>\n-**race with the machine**：<u>与机器协作/和机器一起前进。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn other words, we need to look at the ways in which machines can augment human labor rather than replace it.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，我们需要关注机器能够增强人类劳动而不是取代人类劳动的方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">So then</font> the problem is not really about technology, <font color=\"#ffff00\">but rather</font>, “how do we innovate our institutions and our work practices?”\n翻译: <u>因此，问题实际上并不在于技术，而在于“我们如何创新我们的制度和工作实践？”</u>\n\n-**So then**：<u>那么、因此。</u>\n-**but rather**：<u>而是。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nWhen the government talks about infrastructure contributing to the economy the focus is usually on roads, railways, broadband and energy.\n翻译: <u>当政府谈到基础设施对经济的贡献时，关注点通常放在道路、铁路、宽带和能源上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHousing is seldom mentioned.\n翻译: <u>住房很少被提及。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhy is that?\n翻译: <u>为什么会这样？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTo some extent the <font color=\"#ffff00\">housing sector</font> must <font color=\"#ffff00\">shoulder</font> the blame.\n翻译: <u>在某种程度上，住房部门必须承担责任。</u>\n\n-**housing sector**：<u>住房行业、住宅建设领域。</u>\n-**shoulder**：<u>本义是“肩膀”，作动词表示“承担”。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe have not been good at <font color=\"#ffff00\">communicating</font> the real value that housing can contribute to economic growth.\n翻译: <u>我们一直不善于传达住房能够为经济增长贡献的真正价值。</u>\n\n-**communicating**：<u>传达、沟通。</u>\n\n---\n\nThen there is the scale of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">typical housing project</font>.\n翻译: <u>此外，还有典型住房项目的规模问题。</u>\n\n-**typical housing project**：<u>典型住房项目。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is hard to <font color=\"#ffff00\">shove for attention</font> among multibillion-pound infrastructure projects, so it is inevitable that the attention is focused elsewhere.\n翻译: <u>在数十亿英镑的基础设施项目中争取关注是很难的，因此关注不可避免地会集中到别处。</u>\n\n-**shove for attention**：<u>挤着争夺关注。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut perhaps the most significant reason is that the issue has always been so <font color=\"#ffff00\">politically charged</font>.\n翻译: <u>但也许最重要的原因是，这个问题一直带有强烈的政治色彩。</u>\n\n-**politically charged**：<u>带有强烈政治色彩的、政治上敏感的。</u>\n\n---\n\nNevertheless, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">affordable housing</font> situation is <font color=\"#ffff00\">desperate</font>.\n翻译: <u>尽管如此，保障性住房的形势十分严峻。</u>\n\n-**affordable housing**：<u>保障性住房、可负担住房。</u>\n-**desperate**：<u>危急的、极其严重的。</u>\n\n---\n\nWaiting lists increase all the time and we are <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply</font> not building enough new homes.\n翻译: <u>等待名单一直在增加，而我们新建住房的数量实在不够。</u>\n\n-**simply**：<u>简直、根本，用来加强语气。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">comprehensive spending review</font> offers an opportunity for the government to help <font color=\"#ffff00\">rectify</font> this.\n翻译: <u>全面支出审查为政府帮助纠正这一问题提供了机会。</u>\n\n-**comprehensive spending review**：<u>综合支出审查</u>\n-**rectify**：<u>纠正、改善。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt needs to put historical prejudices to one side and take some steps to address our urgent housing need.\n翻译: <u>政府需要把历史偏见放到一边，并采取一些措施来解决我们迫切的住房需求。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere are some indications that it is preparing to do <font color=\"#ffff00\">just that</font>.\n翻译: <u>有一些迹象表明，政府正准备这样做。</u>\n\n-**just that**：<u>正是那件事。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">communities minister</font>, Don Foster, has hinted that George Osborne, Chancellor of the Exchequer, may introduce more flexibility to the <font color=\"#ffff00\">current cap</font> on the amount that <font color=\"#ffff00\">local authorities</font> can <font color=\"#ffff00\">borrow against</font> their <font color=\"#ffff00\">housing stock</font> debt.\n翻译: <u>社区事务大臣唐·福斯特暗示，财政大臣乔治·奥斯本可能会对目前地方政府可用其住房存量债务作抵押进行借款的金额上限引入更大的灵活性。</u>\n\n-**communities minister**：<u>社区事务大臣。</u>\n-**current cap**：<u>当前上限。</u>\n-**local authorities**：<u>地方政府。</u>\n-**borrow against…**：<u>以……为抵押/担保进行借款。</u>\n-**housing stock**：<u>住房存量，地方政府拥有或管理的住宅资产。</u>\n\n---\n\nEvidence shows that 60,000 extra new homes could be built over the next five years if the cap were lifted, increasing GDP by 0.6%.\n翻译: <u>证据显示，如果取消这一上限，未来五年可额外建造6万套新住房，使国内生产总值增加0.6%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMinisters should also look at creating greater certainty in the rental environment, which would have a significant impact on the ability of registered providers to <font color=\"#ffff00\">fund new developments from revenues</font>.\n翻译: <u>部长们还应考虑在租赁环境中创造更大的确定性，这将对注册住房提供者利用收入为新开发项目融资的能力产生重大影响。</u>\n\n-**fund new developments from revenues**：<u>用收入资助新开发项目。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut it is not just down to the government.\n翻译: <u>但这并不只是政府的责任。</u>\n\n-**be down to…**：<u>取决于……、是……的责任。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile these measures would be welcome in the short term, we must face up to the fact that the existing £ 4.5bn <font color=\"#ffff00\">programme of grants</font> to fund new affordable housing, set to expire in 2015, is unlikely to be extended beyond then.\n翻译: <u>虽然这些措施在短期内会受到欢迎，但我们必须正视这样一个事实：现有的45亿英镑用于资助新保障性住房的拨款项目定于2015年到期，而此后不太可能延长。</u>\n\n-**programme of grants**：<u>拨款项目。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Labour party has recently announced that it will retain a large part of <font color=\"#ffff00\">the coalition’s spending plans</font> if it <font color=\"#ffff00\">returns to power</font>.\n翻译: <u>工党最近宣布，如果重新执政，它将保留联合政府支出计划中的很大一部分。</u>\n\n-**the coalition’s spending plans**：<u>联合政府的支出计划。</u>\n-**return to power**：<u>重新掌权、重新执政。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe housing sector needs to accept that we are very unlikely to ever return to the era of large-scale public grants.\n翻译: <u>住房部门需要接受这样一个事实：我们极不可能再回到大规模公共拨款的时代。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe need to adjust to this changing climate.\n翻译: <u>我们需要适应这种正在变化的环境。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the government’s commitment to long-term funding may have changed, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">very pressing need</font> for more affordable housing is real and is not going away.\n翻译: <u>尽管政府对长期资金投入的承诺可能已经发生变化，但对更多保障性住房的非常迫切的需求是真实存在的，而且不会消失。</u>\n\n-**very pressing need**：<u>非常迫切的需求。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2015","year":"2015","title":"2015 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2015 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2015 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nA new study suggests that <font color=\"#ffff00\">contrary to</font> most surveys, people are actually more stressed at home than at work.\n翻译: <u>一项新研究表明，与大多数调查相反，人们实际上在家里比在工作中压力更大。</u>\n\n-**contrary to…**：<u>与……相反。</u>\n\n---\n\nResearchers measured people’s cortisol, which is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">stress marker</font>, while they were at work and while they were at home and found it higher at what is supposed to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">a place of refuge</font>.\n翻译: <u>研究人员在人们工作时和在家时测量了他们的皮质醇水平，皮质醇是一种压力指标，结果发现，在本应是避难所的地方，皮质醇水平更高。</u>\n\n-**stress marker**：<u>压力标志物、压力指标。</u>\n-**a place of refuge**：<u>避风港、庇护所。</u>\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">Further</font> contradicting <font color=\"#ffff00\">conventional wisdom</font>, we found that women as well as men have lower levels of stress at work than at home,” writes one of the researchers, Sarah Damaske.\n翻译: <u>“进一步与传统看法相矛盾的是，我们发现女性和男性一样，在工作中的压力水平都低于在家中的压力水平，”研究人员之一莎拉·达马斯克写道。</u>\n\n-**Further**：<u>进一步地。</u>\n-**conventional wisdom**：<u>传统看法、普遍认知</u>\n\n---\n\nIn fact women even say they feel better at work, she notes.\n翻译: <u>她指出，事实上，女性甚至说她们在工作中感觉更好。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It is men, not women, who report being happier at home than at work.”\n翻译: <u>“报告说在家里比在工作中更快乐的是男性，而不是女性。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnother surprise is that the findings hold true for both <font color=\"#ffff00\">those with children</font> and without, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">more so</font> for <font color=\"#ffff00\">nonparents</font>.\n翻译: <u>另一个令人意外的发现是，这些结论对有孩子和没有孩子的人都成立，但对非父母群体更为明显。</u>\n\n-**those with children**：<u>有孩子的人。</u>\n-**those without**：<u>没有孩子的人。</u>\n-**more so**：<u>更加如此、尤其如此。</u>\n-**nonparents**：<u>没有孩子的人。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis is why people who work outside the home have better health.\n翻译: <u>这就是为什么外出工作的人健康状况更好。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhat the study doesn’t measure is whether people are still doing work when they’re at home, whether it is household work or work brought home from the office.\n翻译: <u>这项研究没有衡量的是，人们在家时是否仍然在工作，无论是做家务，还是做从办公室带回家的工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFor many men, the end of the workday is a time to <font color=\"#ffff00\">kick back</font>.\n翻译: <u>对许多男性来说，工作日结束意味着可以放松休息。</u>\n\n-**kick back**：<u>放松、休息。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor women who stay home, they never get to leave the office.\n翻译: <u>对于待在家里的女性来说，她们从来没有机会离开办公室。</u>\n\n-**get to do**：<u>有机会做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd for women who work outside the home, they often are <font color=\"#ffff00\">playing catch-up</font>-with-household tasks.\n翻译: <u>而对于外出工作的女性来说，她们常常是在努力补做家务。</u>\n\n-**play catch-up**：<u>追赶、补上落后的部分。</u>\n\n---\n\nWith the blurring of roles, and the fact that <font color=\"#ffff00\">the home front</font> lags <font color=\"#ffff00\">well behind</font> the workplace in making adjustments for working women, it’s not surprising that women are more stressed at home.\n翻译: <u>由于角色界限变得模糊，再加上家庭方面在为职业女性作出调整上远远落后于工作场所，女性在家里压力更大也就不足为奇了。</u>\n\n-**the home front**：<u>家庭方面、家庭领域。</u>\n-**well behind**：<u>远远落后。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut it’s not just a gender thing.\n翻译: <u>但这并不只是性别问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt work, people <font color=\"#ffff00\">pretty much</font> know what they’re supposed to be doing: working, making money, doing the tasks they have to do in order to draw an income.\n翻译: <u>在工作中，人们基本上知道自己应该做什么：工作、赚钱、完成为了获得收入而必须完成的任务。</u>\n\n-**pretty much**：<u>差不多、大体上。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">bargain</font> is very pure: Employee puts in hours of physical or mental labor and employee <font color=\"#ffff00\">draws out</font> life-sustaining moola.\n翻译: <u>这种交易非常纯粹：雇员投入一定时间的体力或脑力劳动，雇员获得维持生活的钱。</u>\n\n-**bargain**：<u>交易、交换关系。</u>\n-**draw out**：<u>取出、获得。</u>\n\n---\n\nOn the home front, however, people have <font color=\"#ffff00\">no such clarity</font>.\n翻译: <u>然而，在家庭方面，人们没有这种清晰性。</u>\n\n-**no such clarity**：<u>没有这种清晰。</u>\n-**such**：<u>指上一句职场中明确的任务、回报和角色。</u>\n\n---\n\nRare is the household in which the <font color=\"#ffff00\">division of labor</font> is so <font color=\"#ffff00\">clinically</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">methodically</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">laid out</font>.\n翻译: <u>很少有家庭会把劳动分工如此临床般精确而有条理地安排清楚。</u>\n\n-**division of labor**：<u>劳动分工。</u>\n-**clinically**：<u>冷静客观地、像临床/科学一样精确地。</u>\n-**methodically**：<u>有条理地、系统地。</u>\n-**laid out**：<u>安排、列明、规划。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere are a lot of tasks to be done, there are inadequate rewards for most of them.\n翻译: <u>有很多任务要完成，而其中大多数任务所得到的回报都不足。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYour home colleagues – your family – have no clear rewards for their labor; they need to be talked into it, or if they’re teenagers, threatened with complete removal of all electronic devices.\n翻译: <u>你的家庭同事，也就是你的家人，并没有明确的劳动回报；他们需要被说服去做，或者如果他们是青少年，就要用彻底没收所有电子设备来威胁他们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Plus</font>, they’re your family.\n翻译: <u>再者，他们是你的家人。</u>\n\n-**Plus**：<u>是口语化连接词，表示补充一点。</u>\n\n---\n\nYou cannot fire your family.\n翻译: <u>你不能解雇你的家人。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYou never really get to go home from home.\n翻译: <u>你从来不能真正从家里回到“家”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSo it’s not surprising that people are more stressed at home.\n翻译: <u>所以，人们在家里压力更大并不令人意外。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNot only are the tasks apparently infinite, the co-workers are much harder to motivate.\n翻译: <u>不仅任务显然是无穷无尽的，而且这些同事也更难被激励。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nFor years, studies have found that first-generation college students – those who do not have a parent with a college degree – <font color=\"#ffff00\">lag</font> other students on a range of <font color=\"#ffff00\">education achievement factors</font>.\n翻译: <u>多年来，研究发现，第一代大学生，也就是父母没有大学学位的学生，在一系列教育成就因素上落后于其他学生。</u>\n\n-**lag**：<u>落后。</u>\n-**education achievement factors**：<u>教育成就因素，比如成绩、毕业率、退学率等。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir grades are lower and their dropout rates are higher.\n翻译: <u>他们的成绩更低，辍学率更高。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut since such students are most likely to advance economically if they succeed in higher education, colleges and universities <font color=\"#ffff00\">have pushed</font> for decades to recruit more of them.\n翻译: <u>但是，由于这类学生如果在高等教育中取得成功，最有可能实现经济上的提升，几十年来，高校一直努力招收更多这样的学生。</u>\n\n-**have pushed**：<u>一直推动、努力。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis has created “a paradox” <font color=\"#ffff00\">in that</font> recruiting first-generation students, but then watching many of them fail, means that higher education has “continued to <font color=\"#ffff00\">reproduce</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">widen</font>, rather than <font color=\"#ffff00\">close</font>” an achievement gap based on social class, according to the depressing beginning of a paper <font color=\"#ffff00\">forthcoming</font> in the journal Psychological Science.\n翻译: <u>根据即将在《心理科学》期刊发表的一篇论文那令人沮丧的开头，这造成了“一种悖论”：招收第一代大学生，但随后又看到他们中的许多人失败，这意味着高等教育“继续复制并扩大，而不是缩小”一个基于社会阶层的成就差距。</u>\n\n-**in that**：<u>在于、因为、原因是。</u>\n-**reproduce**：<u>复制、再生产。</u>\n-**widen**：<u>扩大。</u>\n-**close**：<u>缩小、弥合。</u>\n-**forthcoming**：<u>即将发表的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the article is actually quite optimistic, as it outlines a potential solution to this problem, suggesting that an approach (which involves a one-hour, <font color=\"#ffff00\">next-to-no-cost</font> program) can close 63 percent of the achievement gap (<font color=\"#ffff00\">measured by</font> such factors as grades) between first-generation and other students.\n翻译: <u>但这篇文章实际上相当乐观，因为它概述了这一问题的一个潜在解决方案，提出一种方法（包括一个一小时、几乎零成本的项目）能够弥合第一代学生与其他学生之间63%的成就差距（以成绩等因素衡量）。</u>\n\n-**next-to-no-cost**：<u>几乎没有成本的。</u>\n-**measured by…**：<u>由……衡量。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe authors of the paper are from different universities, and their findings are based on a study involving 147 students (who completed the project) at an <font color=\"#ffff00\">unnamed</font> private university.\n翻译: <u>这篇论文的作者来自不同大学，他们的发现基于一项在某所未具名私立大学进行、涉及147名学生（这些学生完成了该项目）的研究。</u>\n\n-**unnamed**：<u>未透露名称的。</u>\n\n---\n\nFirst generation was defined as <font color=\"#ffff00\">not having</font> a parent with a four-year college degree.\n翻译: <u>第一代学生被定义为父母没有四年制大学学位的学生。</u>\n\n-**not having**：<u>没有。</u>\n\n---\n\nMost of the first-generation students (59.1 percent) were recipients of <font color=\"#ffff00\">Pell Grants</font>, a federal grant for undergraduates with financial need, while this was true only for 8.6 percent of the students with at least one parent with a four-year degree.\n翻译: <u>大多数第一代大学生（59.1%）是佩尔助学金的获得者；佩尔助学金是一项面向有经济需要的本科生的联邦补助，而在至少有一位父母拥有四年制大学学位的学生中，只有8.6%符合这一情况。</u>\n\n-**Pell Grants**：<u>美国联邦佩尔助学金，面向有经济需求的本科生。</u>\n-**this was true for…**：<u>这种情况适用于……。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir <font color=\"#ffff00\">thesis</font> – that a relatively modest intervention could have a big impact – was based on the view that first-generation students may be most lacking not in potential but in practical knowledge about how to deal with the issues that face most college students.\n翻译: <u>他们的论点是，相对适度的干预可能产生巨大影响；这一论点基于这样一种看法：第一代大学生最缺乏的可能不是潜力，而是关于如何应对大多数大学生都会面对的问题的实用知识。</u>\n\n-**thesis**：<u>核心论点、主张。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey <font color=\"#ffff00\">cite</font> past research by several authors to show that this is the gap that must be narrowed to close the achievement gap.\n翻译: <u>他们引用了几位作者过去的研究，以表明这正是必须缩小的差距，才能弥合成就差距。</u>\n\n-**cite**：<u>引用。</u>\n\n---\n\nMany first-generation students “struggle to <font color=\"#ffff00\">navigate</font> the middle-class culture of higher education, learn the ‘rules of the game,’ and take advantage of college resources,” they write.\n翻译: <u>他们写道，许多第一代大学生“难以适应高等教育中的中产阶级文化，学会‘游戏规则’，并利用大学资源”。</u>\n\n-**navigate**：<u>原意是“导航”，这里表示“在复杂环境中找到方向、应对”。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd this becomes <font color=\"#ffff00\">more of a problem</font> when colleges don’t talk about the <font color=\"#ffff00\">class advantages and disadvantages</font> of different groups of students.\n翻译: <u>而当大学不谈论不同学生群体的阶级优势和劣势时，这就会变成更大的问题。</u>\n\n-**more of a problem**：<u>更成问题、更严重。</u>\n-**class advantages and disadvantages**：<u>阶层优势和劣势。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Because US colleges and universities seldom acknowledge how social class can affect students’ educational experiences, many first-generation students lack insight about why they are struggling and do not understand how students ‘like them’ can improve.”\n翻译: <u>“因为美国高校很少承认社会阶层会如何影响学生的教育经历，许多第一代大学生缺乏对自己为何挣扎的认识，也不明白像他们这样的学生如何能够改进。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nEven in traditional offices, “the lingua franca of <font color=\"#ffff00\">corporate America</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">has gotten</font> much more emotional and much more right-brained than it was 20 years ago,” said Harvard Business School professor Nancy Koehn.\n翻译: <u>哈佛商学院教授Nancy Koehn说，即使在传统办公室里，“美国企业界的通用语言也已经比20年前变得更加情绪化、更加右脑化。”</u>\n\n-**corporate America**：<u>美国企业界。</u>\n-**has gotten**：<u>已经变得。</u>\n\n---\n\nShe started <font color=\"#ffff00\">spinning off</font> examples.\n翻译: <u>她开始接连举出例子。</u>\n\n-**spin off**：<u>原意可指“派生、衍生”，这里有“顺势说出、连续给出”的意思。</u>\n\n---\n\n“If you and I <font color=\"#ffff00\">parachuted back to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">Fortune 500 companies</font> in 1990, we would see much less frequent use of terms like journey, mission, passion.\n翻译: <u>“如果你我空降回1990年的《财富》500强公司，我们会看到像journey、mission、passion这样的词被使用得少得多。</u>\n\n-**parachute back to…**：<u>字面是“空降回……”，这里是形象说法，表示“突然回到过去的某个场景”。</u>\n-**Fortune 500 companies**：<u>财富 500 强公司。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere were goals, there were strategies, there were <font color=\"#ffff00\">objectives</font>, but we didn’t talk about energy; we didn’t talk about passion.”\n翻译: <u>那时有目标，有战略，有目的，但我们不谈能量；我们不谈激情。”</u>\n\n-**objectives**：<u>具体目标、阶段性目标。</u>\n\n---\n\nKoehn pointed out that this new era of corporate vocabulary is very “team”-oriented – and <font color=\"#ffff00\">not by coincidence</font>.\n翻译: <u>Koehn指出，企业词汇的这个新时代非常以“团队”为导向，而且这并非巧合。</u>\n\n-**not by coincidence**：<u>不是偶然的。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Let’s not forget sports – in male-dominated corporate America, it’s still a big deal.\n翻译: <u>“别忘了体育，在男性主导的美国企业界，它仍然是一件大事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt’s not <font color=\"#ffff00\">explicitly</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">conscious</font>; it’s the idea that I’m a coach, and you’re my team, and we’re in this together.\n翻译: <u>这并不是明确有意识的；它是一种观念：我是教练，你们是我的团队，我们一起参与其中。</u>\n\n-**explicitly**：<u>明确地、清楚地。</u>\n-**conscious**：<u>有意识的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere are lots and lots of CEOs in very different companies, but most think of themselves as coaches and this is their team and they want to win. ”\n翻译: <u>在非常不同的公司里有许许多多的CEO，但大多数人把自己看作教练，把这看作他们的团队，而且他们想赢。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThese terms are also intended to infuse work with meaning – and, as Rakesh Khurana, another professor, points out, increase <font color=\"#ffff00\">allegiance</font> to the firm.\n翻译: <u>这些术语还旨在为工作注入意义；而且，正如另一位教授Rakesh Khurana指出的那样，它们还会增强对公司的忠诚。</u>\n\n-**infuse A with B**：<u>给 A 注入 B。</u>\n-**allegiance**：<u>忠诚、效忠。</u>\n\n---\n\n“You have the <font color=\"#ffff00\">importation</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">terminology</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">historically</font> used to be associated with non-profit organizations and religious organizations: terms like vision, values, passion, and purpose,” said Khurana.\n翻译: <u>Khurana说：“你会看到一些术语被引入进来，而这些术语在历史上曾经与非营利组织和宗教组织相关，比如愿景、价值观、激情和目标这样的词。”</u>\n\n-**importation**：<u>引入、输入。</u>\n-**terminology**：<u>术语、专门词汇。</u>\n-**historically**：<u>历史上、过去。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis new focus on personal fulfillment can help keep employees <font color=\"#ffff00\">motivated</font> amid increasingly loud debates over work-life balance.\n翻译: <u>在围绕工作与生活平衡的争论变得越来越激烈之际，这种对个人满足感的新关注有助于保持员工的积极性。</u>\n\n-**motivated**：<u>有动力的、受激励的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe “mommy wars” of the 1990s are still going on today, <font color=\"#ffff00\">prompting</font> arguments about why women still can’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">have it all</font> and books like Sheryl Sandberg’s Lean In, whose title has become a <font color=\"#ffff00\">buzzword</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">in its own right</font>.\n翻译: <u>20世纪90年代的“妈妈战争”今天仍在继续，引发了关于为什么女性仍然不能拥有一切的争论，也催生了像Sheryl Sandberg的《Lean In》这样的书，其书名本身已经成了一个流行语。</u>\n\n-**prompting**：<u>引发、促使。</u>\n-**have it all**：<u>事业、家庭、个人生活都拥有/兼顾。</u>\n-**buzzword**：<u>流行语、热词。</u>\n-**in its own right**：<u>凭自身资格、本身就。</u>\n\n---\n\nTerms like unplug, offline, <font color=\"#ffff00\">life-hack</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">bandwidth</font>, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">capacity</font> are all about setting boundaries between the office and the home.\n翻译: <u>像unplug、offline、life-hack、bandwidth和capacity这样的词，都是关于在办公室和家庭之间设定界限的。</u>\n\n-**life-hack**：<u>生活技巧、效率技巧。</u>\n-**bandwidth**：<u>带宽，引申为精力、时间、处理能力。</u>\n-**capacity**：<u>容量、承受能力、工作负荷能力。</u>\n-**be all about…**：<u>核心就是…… / 主要关于……。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut if your work is your “passion,” you’ll be more likely to devote yourself to it, even if that means going home for dinner and then working long after the kids are in bed.\n翻译: <u>但是，如果你的工作就是你的“激情”，你就更有可能全身心投入其中，即使这意味着回家吃晚饭，然后在孩子们睡觉很久之后继续工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut this seems to be the irony of office speak: Everyone <font color=\"#ffff00\">makes fun of</font> it, but managers love it, companies depend on it, and regular people willingly absorb it.\n翻译: <u>但这似乎就是办公室用语的讽刺之处：人人都取笑它，但经理们喜欢它，公司依赖它，普通人也心甘情愿地吸收它。</u>\n\n-**make fun of…**：<u>取笑、嘲笑。</u>\n\n---\n\nAs a linguist once said, “You can get people to think it’s nonsense at the same time that you <font color=\"#ffff00\">buy into</font> it.”\n翻译: <u>正如一位语言学家曾经说过的：“你可以让人们在认为它是胡说的同时，又接受它。”</u>\n\n-**get people to do**：<u>让人们做某事。</u>\n-**buy into…**：<u>相信、接受、认同某种观念。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a workplace <font color=\"#ffff00\">that’s</font> fundamentally indifferent to <font color=\"#ffff00\">your life and its meaning</font>, office speak can help you figure out how you relate to your work – and how your work defines who you are.\n翻译: <u>在一个从根本上对你的生活及其意义漠不关心的职场中，办公室用语可以帮助你弄清楚你如何与工作发生关系，以及你的工作如何定义你是谁。</u>\n\n-**that’s**：<u>= that is。</u>\n-**your life and its meaning**：<u>你的生活及其意义。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nMany people talked of the 288,000 new jobs <font color=\"#ffff00\">the Labor Department</font> reported for June, along with the drop in the unemployment rate to 6.1 percent, as good news.\n翻译: <u>许多人把劳工部报告的6月份新增28.8万个就业岗位，以及失业率降至6.1%，称作好消息。</u>\n\n-**the Labor Department**：<u>劳工部。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd they were right.\n翻译: <u>他们是对的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For now</font> it <font color=\"#ffff00\">appears</font> the economy is creating jobs <font color=\"#ffff00\">at a decent pace</font>.\n翻译: <u>就目前而言，经济似乎正在以相当不错的速度创造就业。</u>\n\n-**for now**：<u>目前、眼下。</u>\n-**appear**：<u>似乎、看起来。</u>\n-**at a decent pace**：<u>以相当不错的速度。</u>\n-**decent**：<u>在这里不是“体面”的意思，而是“不错的、尚可的”。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe still have a long way to go to get back to <font color=\"#ffff00\">full employment</font>, but at least we are now finally moving forward at a faster pace.\n翻译: <u>我们距离恢复充分就业仍有很长的路要走，但至少我们现在终于正以更快的速度向前推进。</u>\n\n-**full employment**：<u>充分就业，指想工作的人基本都能找到工作的状态。</u>\n\n---\n\nHowever, there is another important part of the jobs picture that was <font color=\"#ffff00\">largely</font> overlooked.\n翻译: <u>然而，就业图景中还有另一个重要部分在很大程度上被忽视了。</u>\n\n-**largely**：<u>很大程度上。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere was <font color=\"#ffff00\">a big jump</font> in the number of people who report voluntarily working part-time.\n翻译: <u>报告自愿从事兼职工作的人数出现了大幅增加。</u>\n\n-**a big jump**：<u>大幅跃升、大幅增加。</u>\n-**report doing**：<u>报告自己做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis figure is now 830,000（4.4 percent）above its year ago level.\n翻译: <u>这一数字现在比一年前的水平高出83万人（4.4%）。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBefore explaining the connection to the Obamacare, it is worth making an important distinction.\n翻译: <u>在解释它与奥巴马医改的联系之前，有必要作出一个重要区分。</u>\n\n-**make a distinction**：<u>作区分。</u>\n\n---\n\nMany people who work part-time jobs actually want full-time jobs.\n翻译: <u>许多从事兼职工作的人实际上想要全职工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey take part-time work because this is all they can get.\n翻译: <u>他们接受兼职工作，是因为这是他们唯一能得到的工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAn increase in involuntary part-time work is evidence of weakness in the labor market and it means\n翻译: <u>非自愿兼职工作的增加是劳动力市场疲软的证据，而且它意味着</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nthat many people will be having a very hard time making ends meet.\n翻译: <u>许多人将会非常难以维持收支平衡。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere was an increase in involuntary part-time in June, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">the general direction</font> has been down.\n翻译: <u>6月份非自愿兼职有所增加，但总体方向一直是下降的。</u>\n\n-**the general direction**：<u>总体趋势。</u>\n\n---\n\nInvoluntary part-time employment is still far higher than <font color=\"#ffff00\">before the recession</font>, but it is down by 640,000 (7.9 percent) from its year ago level.\n翻译: <u>非自愿兼职就业仍远高于衰退前的水平，但它比一年前的水平减少了64万人（7.9%）。</u>\n\n-**before the recession**：<u>经济衰退前。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe know the difference between voluntary and involuntary part-time employment because people tell us.\n翻译: <u>我们知道自愿兼职就业和非自愿兼职就业之间的区别，是因为人们会告诉我们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe survey used by the Labor Department asks people if they worked less than 35 hours in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">reference week</font>.\n翻译: <u>劳工部使用的调查会询问人们在参照周内工作时间是否少于35小时。</u>\n\n-**reference week**：<u>调查参考周，即统计调查所选定的那一周。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf the answer is “yes,” they are classified as working part-time.\n翻译: <u>如果答案是“是”，他们就被归类为从事兼职工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe survey then asks whether they worked less than 35 hours in that week because they wanted to work less than full time or because they had no choice.\n翻译: <u>然后，调查会询问他们那一周工作时间少于35小时，是因为他们想要少于全职工作，还是因为他们别无选择。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey are only classified as <font color=\"#ffff00\">voluntary part-time workers</font> if they tell the survey taker they chose to work less than 35 hours a week.\n翻译: <u>只有当他们告诉调查员自己选择每周工作少于35小时时，他们才会被归类为自愿兼职工作者。</u>\n\n-**voluntary part-time workers**：<u>自愿兼职工作者。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe issue of voluntary part-time relates to Obamacare because one of the main purposes was to allow people to get insurance <font color=\"#ffff00\">outside of employment</font>.\n翻译: <u>自愿兼职的问题与奥巴马医改有关，因为该法案的主要目的之一，就是让人们能够在就业之外获得保险。</u>\n\n-**outside of employment**：<u>不通过雇佣关系、在工作之外。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor many people, especially those with serious health conditions or family members with serious health conditions, before Obamacare the only way to get insurance was through a job that provided health insurance.\n翻译: <u>对许多人来说，尤其是那些本人有严重健康问题或家庭成员有严重健康问题的人，在奥巴马医改之前，获得保险的唯一途径是通过一份提供健康保险的工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHowever, Obamacare has allowed more than 12 million people to either get insurance through Medicaid or the <font color=\"#ffff00\">exchanges</font>.\n翻译: <u>然而，奥巴马医改已经使1200多万人能够通过医疗补助计划或保险交易所获得保险。</u>\n\n-**exchanges**：<u>医保交易所，即 Obamacare 下购买保险的平台。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese are people who <font color=\"#ffff00\">may previously have felt</font> the need to get a full-time job that provided insurance in order to <font color=\"#ffff00\">cover</font> themselves and their families.\n翻译: <u>这些人以前可能觉得有必要找一份提供保险的全职工作，以便保障自己和家人。</u>\n\n-**may previously have felt**：<u>过去可能曾经觉得。</u>\n-**cover**：<u>在医保语境中表示“为……提供保险保障”。</u>\n\n---\n\nWith Obamacare there is no longer a link between employment and insurance.\n翻译: <u>有了奥巴马医改，就业和保险之间不再存在联系。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2016","year":"2016","title":"2016 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2016 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2016 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIt’s true that high-school coding classes aren’t essential for learning computer science in college.\n翻译: <u>确实，高中编程课对于在大学学习计算机科学并不是必不可少的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nStudents without experience can catch up after a few introductory courses, said Tom Cortina, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">assistant dean</font> at Carnegie Mellon’s School of Computer Science.\n翻译: <u>卡内基梅隆大学计算机科学学院副院长Tom Cortina说，没有经验的学生可以在上完几门入门课程后赶上来。</u>\n\n-**assistant dean**：<u>副院长、助理院长。</u>\n\n---\n\nHowever, Cortina said, early exposure is beneficial.\n翻译: <u>然而，Cortina说，早期接触是有益的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen younger kids learn computer science, they <font color=\"#ffff00\">learn that</font> it’s not just a confusing, endless string of letters and numbers – but a tool to build apps, or create artwork, or test hypotheses.\n翻译: <u>当年龄较小的孩子学习计算机科学时，他们会了解到，它不只是一串令人困惑、没完没了的字母和数字，而是一种可以用来开发应用程序、创作艺术作品或检验假设的工具。</u>\n\n-**learn that…**：<u>了解到、认识到……</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s not as hard for them to transform their <font color=\"#ffff00\">thought processes</font> as it is for older students.\n翻译: <u>对他们来说，转变自己的思维过程并不像对年龄较大的学生那样困难。</u>\n\n-**thought processes**：<u>思维过程、思考方式。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Breaking down</font> problems into bite-sized chunks and using code to solve them becomes normal.\n翻译: <u>把问题分解成一小块一小块，并用代码来解决它们，会变得很正常。</u>\n\n-**break down**：<u>分解、拆解。</u>\n\n---\n\nGiving more children this training could increase the number of people interested in the field and help fill the <font color=\"#ffff00\">jobs gap</font>, Cortina said.\n翻译: <u>Cortina说，让更多孩子接受这种训练，可能会增加对这一领域感兴趣的人数，并帮助填补就业缺口。</u>\n\n-**jobs gap**：<u>岗位缺口、人才缺口。</u>\n\n---\n\nStudents also benefit from learning something about coding before they get to college, where introductory computer-science classes are <font color=\"#ffff00\">packed to the brim</font>, which can drive the less-experienced or -determined students away.\n翻译: <u>学生在上大学之前学习一些有关编程的东西也会受益，因为大学里的计算机科学入门课程往往挤得满满当当，这可能会把经验较少或决心较弱的学生赶走。</u>\n\n-**packed to the brim**：<u>挤得满满的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Flatiron School, where people pay to learn programming, started as one of the many <font color=\"#ffff00\">coding bootcamps</font> that’s become popular for adults looking for a career change.\n翻译: <u>Flatiron School是一所人们付费学习编程的学校，它最初是众多编程训练营之一；这些训练营已经在寻求转行的成年人中变得流行。</u>\n\n-**coding bootcamp**：<u>编程训练营，通常是短期、高强度职业培训。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe high-schoolers get the same curriculum, but “we try to gear lessons toward things they’re interested in,” said Victoria Friedman, an <font color=\"#ffff00\">instructor</font>.\n翻译: <u>高中生学习同样的课程，但教师Victoria Friedman说，“我们努力把课程调整得更贴近他们感兴趣的东西”。</u>\n\n-**gear A toward B**：<u>使 A 面向 B / 根据 B 调整 A。</u>\n-**instructor**：<u>教师、讲师。</u>\n\n---\n\nFor instance, one of the apps the students are developing <font color=\"#ffff00\">suggests</font> movies based on your mood.\n翻译: <u>例如，学生们正在开发的一个应用程序会根据你的心情推荐电影。</u>\n\n-**suggest**：<u>推荐、建议。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe students in the Flatiron class probably won’t drop out of high school and build the next Facebook.\n翻译: <u>Flatiron班上的学生很可能不会从高中退学，然后打造出下一个Facebook。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nProgramming languages have a <font color=\"#ffff00\">quick turnover</font>, so the “Ruby on Rails” language they learned <font color=\"#ffff00\">may not even be relevant</font> by the time they enter the job market.\n翻译: <u>编程语言更新换代很快，所以他们学的“Ruby on Rails”语言，等到他们进入就业市场时，甚至可能已经不再相关。</u>\n\n-**quick turnover**：<u>快速更替。</u>\n-**may not even be relevant**：<u>甚至可能不再有用 / 不再相关。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the skills they learn – how to think logically through a problem and organize the results – apply to any coding language, said Deborah Seehorn, an education consultant for the state of North Carolina.\n翻译: <u>但北卡罗来纳州教育顾问Deborah Seehorn说，他们学到的技能，即如何通过逻辑思维处理一个问题并组织结果，适用于任何编程语言。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIndeed, the Flatiron students might not go into IT at all.\n翻译: <u>事实上，Flatiron的学生可能根本不会进入IT行业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut creating a future army of coders is not the sole purpose of the classes.\n翻译: <u>但是，培养未来的一支程序员大军并不是这些课程的唯一目的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThese kids are going to be surrounded by computers – in their pockets, in their offices, in their homes – for the rest of their lives.\n翻译: <u>这些孩子余生都将被电脑包围：在他们的口袋里，在他们的办公室里，在他们的家里。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe younger they learn how computers think, how to coax the machine into producing what they want – the earlier they learn that they have the power to do that – the better.\n翻译: <u>他们越早学会计算机如何思考，如何诱导机器产出他们想要的东西，越早明白自己有能力做到这一点，就越好。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nBiologists <font color=\"#ffff00\">estimate</font> that <font color=\"#ffff00\">as many as</font> 2 million lesser prairie chickens – a kind of bird <font color=\"#ffff00\">living on stretching grasslands</font> – once lent red to the often grey landscape of the midwestern and southwestern United States.\n翻译: <u>生物学家估计，曾经有多达200万只小草原松鸡，一种生活在绵延草原上的鸟类，为美国中西部和西南部常常灰暗的景观增添了红色。</u>\n\n-**estimate**：<u>估计。</u>\n-**as many as**：<u>多达。</u>\n-**living on stretching grasslands**：<u>生活在绵延伸展的草原上。</u>\n-**lend A to B**：<u>给 B 增添 A / 赋予 B 某种特征。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut just some 22,000 birds remain today, occupying about 16% of the species’ historic range.\n翻译: <u>但如今只剩下约2.2万只鸟，占据着该物种历史分布范围的大约16%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe crash was a major reason the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (USFWS) decided to formally list the bird as threatened.\n翻译: <u>数量暴跌是美国鱼类及野生动物管理局（USFWS）决定正式将这种鸟列为受威胁物种的一个主要原因。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“The lesser prairie chicken is in a desperate situation,” said USFWS Director Daniel Ashe.\n翻译: <u>USFWS局长Daniel Ashe说：“小草原松鸡正处于绝境。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome environmentalists, however, were disappointed.\n翻译: <u>然而，一些环保人士感到失望。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey had pushed the agency to designate the bird as “<font color=\"#ffff00\">endangered</font>,” <font color=\"#ffff00\">a status</font> that gives <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal officials</font> greater regulatory power to crack down on threats.\n翻译: <u>他们曾推动该机构把这种鸟指定为“濒危”物种；这一身份会赋予联邦官员更大的监管权力，以严厉打击各种威胁。</u>\n\n-**designate A as B**：<u>把 A 指定/认定为 B。</u>\n-**a status**：<u>指</u>\n-**endangered**：<u>a status 指 endangered 这个法律保护状态。</u>\n-**federal officials**：<u>联邦官员。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut Ashe and others argued that the “threatened” tag gave the federal government flexibility to <font color=\"#ffff00\">try out</font> new, potentially <font color=\"#ffff00\">less confrontational</font> conservation approaches.\n翻译: <u>但 Ashe 和其他人认为，“受威胁”这一标签给予联邦政府灵活性，使其能够尝试新的、可能不那么对抗性的保护方式。</u>\n\n-**try out**：<u>试用、尝试。</u>\n-**less confrontational**：<u>较少对抗性的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn particular, they <font color=\"#ffff00\">called for</font> forging closer collaborations with western state governments, which are often uneasy with federal action, and with the private landowners who control <font color=\"#ffff00\">an estimated 95%</font> of the prairie chicken’s habitat.\n翻译: <u>尤其是，他们呼吁与西部各州政府建立更紧密的合作关系，这些州政府往往对联邦行动感到不安；同时也要与私人土地所有者合作，后者控制着估计 95% 的草原榛鸡栖息地。</u>\n\n-**call for**：<u>呼吁、要求。</u>\n-**forge**：<u>建立、打造。</u>\n-**an estimated 95%**：<u>估计 95%。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnder the plan, for example, the agency said it would not prosecute landowners or businesses that <font color=\"#ffff00\">unintentionally</font> kill, harm, or disturb the bird, as long as they had signed a <font color=\"#ffff00\">range-wide</font> management plan to restore prairie chicken habitat.\n翻译: <u>例如，根据该计划，该机构表示，只要土地所有者或企业已经签署了一项覆盖整个分布范围的管理计划，以恢复草原榛鸡栖息地，那么对于那些无意中杀死、伤害或惊扰这种鸟的土地所有者或企业，该机构将不会起诉。</u>\n\n-**unintentionally**：<u>无意地、非故意地。</u>\n-**range-wide**：<u>覆盖整个分布区的、全范围的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Negotiated</font> by USFWS and the states, the plan requires individuals and businesses that damage habitat <font color=\"#ffff00\">as part of their operations</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">pay into a fund</font> to replace every acre destroyed with 2 new acres of suitable habitat.\n翻译: <u>这项由 USFWS 与各州谈判达成的计划要求，凡是个人和企业在运营过程中破坏栖息地，都必须向一个基金缴款，以便每破坏一英亩土地，就用两英亩新的适宜栖息地来替代。</u>\n\n-**negotiate**：<u>协商、谈判。</u>\n-**as part of their operations**：<u>作为其经营活动的一部分。</u>\n-**pay into a fund**：<u>向基金缴费/出资。</u>\n-**replace A with B**：<u>用 B 替代 A。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe fund will also be used to compensate landowners who <font color=\"#ffff00\">set aside</font> habitat.\n翻译: <u>该基金还将用于补偿那些划出栖息地的土地所有者。</u>\n\n-**set aside**：<u>留出、划出、预留。</u>\n\n---\n\nUSFWS also set an interim goal of restoring prairie chicken populations to an annual average of 67,000 birds over the next 10 years.\n翻译: <u>USFWS 还设定了一个中期目标：在未来 10 年内，将草原榛鸡种群恢复到年均 67000 只。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd it gives the Western Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies (WAFWA), a coalition of state agencies, the job of monitoring progress.\n翻译: <u>并且，它把监督进展的任务交给了西部鱼类和野生动物机构协会（WAFWA），这是一个由州级机构组成的联盟。</u>\n\n-**the job of doing…**：<u>做某事的工作/职责。</u>\n\n---\n\nOverall, the idea is to let “states <font color=\"#ffff00\">remain in the driver’s seat</font> for managing the species,” Ashe said.\n翻译: <u>总体而言，Ashe 说，这一想法是让“各州在管理该物种方面继续掌握主导权”。</u>\n\n-**remain in the driver’s seat**：<u>继续坐在驾驶位上，比喻“掌握主导权”。</u>\n\n---\n\nNot everyone buys the <font color=\"#ffff00\">win-win rhetoric</font>.\n翻译: <u>并非所有人都相信这种双赢说辞。</u>\n\n-**win-win rhetoric**：<u>双赢话术/说法。</u>\n-**rhetoric**：<u>有时带贬义，指漂亮但未必真实的话术。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome Congress members are trying to block the plan, and at least a dozen industry groups, four states, and three environmental groups are challenging it in federal court.\n翻译: <u>一些国会议员正试图阻止该计划，至少十几个行业团体、四个州以及三个环保组织正在联邦法院对其提出挑战。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNot surprisingly, industry groups and states generally argue it goes too far; environmentalists say it doesn’t go far enough.\n翻译: <u>毫不意外，行业团体和各州通常认为它做得过头了；环保人士则说它做得还不够。</u>\n\n-**go too far**：<u>做得过头、过度。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The federal government is giving responsibility for managing the bird to <font color=\"#ffff00\">the same industries</font> that are pushing it to extinction,” says biologist Jay Lininger.\n翻译: <u>生物学家 Jay Lininger 说：“联邦政府正在把管理这种鸟的责任交给那些正把它推向灭绝的同一批行业。”</u>\n\n-**the same industries**：<u>正是那些行业。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nThat everyone’s too busy these days is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">cliché</font>.\n翻译: <u>如今每个人都太忙，这已经是陈词滥调。</u>\n\n-**cliché**：<u>陈词滥调、老生常谈。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut one specific complaint is made especially <font color=\"#ffff00\">mournfully</font>: There’s never any time to read.\n翻译: <u>但有一种具体抱怨尤其带着哀叹的语气：永远没有时间读书。</u>\n\n-**mournfully**：<u>悲伤地、哀叹地。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat makes the problem <font color=\"#ffff00\">thornier</font> is that the usual time-management techniques don’t seem sufficient.\n翻译: <u>使这个问题更加棘手的是，通常的时间管理技巧似乎并不够用。</u>\n\n-**thornier**：<u>更棘手的、更麻烦的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe web’s full of articles offering tips on making time to read: “Give up TV” or “Carry a book with you at all times.”\n翻译: <u>网上充斥着提供建议、教人如何挤出时间阅读的文章：“放弃看电视”或者“随时带一本书”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut in my experience, using such methods to free up <font color=\"#ffff00\">the odd 30 minutes</font> doesn’t work.\n翻译: <u>但根据我的经验，用这类方法腾出零散的 30 分钟并不起作用。</u>\n\n-**the odd 30 minutes**：<u>偶尔零散出来的 30 分钟。</u>\n-**odd**：<u>这里 odd 不是“奇怪的”，而是“零散的、偶尔的、不固定的”。</u>\n\n---\n\nSit down to read and the <font color=\"#ffff00\">flywheel</font> of work-related thoughts keeps spinning – <font color=\"#ffff00\">or else</font> you’re so exhausted that a challenging book’s the last thing you need.\n翻译: <u>坐下来读书时，与工作相关的想法所形成的飞轮仍在不停转动；要不然，你已经疲惫到一本有挑战性的书成了你最不需要的东西。</u>\n\n-**flywheel**：<u>飞轮；这里是比喻，指脑子里的工作想法像飞轮一样停不下来。</u>\n-**or else**：<u>表示“否则 / 或者另一种情况是”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">modern mind</font>, Tim Parks, a novelist and critic, writes, “is overwhelmingly inclined toward communication...\n翻译: <u>小说家兼评论家 Tim Parks 写道，现代人的心智“极度倾向于交流……”</u>\n\n-**modern mind**：<u>现代心智、现代人的思维状态。</u>\n-**be inclined toward…**：<u>倾向于……。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is <font color=\"#ffff00\">not simply that</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">one</font> is interrupted; it is that one is actually inclined to interruption.”\n翻译: <u>“并不只是说一个人被打断；而是说一个人实际上倾向于被打断。”</u>\n\n-**not simply that…**：<u>并不只是……。</u>\n-**one**：<u>泛指“一个人 / 人们”。</u>\n\n---\n\nDeep reading requires not just time, but a special kind of time which can’t be obtained merely by becoming more efficient.\n翻译: <u>深度阅读需要的不只是时间，而是一种特殊的时间；这种时间无法仅仅通过变得更高效来获得。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn fact, “becoming more efficient” is part of the problem.\n翻译: <u>事实上，“变得更高效”本身就是问题的一部分。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThinking of time as a resource to be maximised means you approach it <font color=\"#ffff00\">instrumentally</font>, judging <font color=\"#ffff00\">any given moment</font> as <font color=\"#ffff00\">well spent</font> only <font color=\"#ffff00\">in so far as</font> it advances progress toward some goal.\n翻译: <u>把时间看作一种应当最大化利用的资源，意味着你会以工具性的方式对待它，并且只有在某个给定时刻推动你朝某个目标取得进展的程度上，你才会判断它花得值得。</u>\n\n-**instrumentally**：<u>工具性地、把它当工具看。</u>\n-**any given moment**：<u>任何一个特定时刻。</u>\n-**well spent**：<u>花得值得、用得好。</u>\n-**insofar as**：<u>在……程度上；只要……；这里不要按字面理解成“在如此远的地方”。它是一个固定连接词</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Immersive</font> reading, by contrast, depends on being willing to risk inefficiency, goallessness, even time-wasting.\n翻译: <u>相比之下，沉浸式阅读依赖于一种意愿：愿意冒着低效率、无目标，甚至浪费时间的风险。</u>\n\n-**immersive**：<u>沉浸式的；相比之下；这里与上一句的“工具化时间观”形成对比</u>\n\n---\n\nTry to <font color=\"#ffff00\">slot it in</font> as a to-do list item and you’ll manage only goal-focused reading – useful, sometimes, but not the most fulfilling kind.\n翻译: <u>试图把它塞进待办事项清单中，你最终只能做到以目标为导向的阅读；这种阅读有时有用，但不是最令人满足的那一种。</u>\n\n-**slot it in**：<u>把它安排进去、塞进日程。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The future comes at us like empty bottles along an unstoppable and nearly infinite <font color=\"#ffff00\">conveyor belt</font>,” writes Gary Eberle in his book Sacred Time, and “we feel a pressure to fill these different-sized bottles (days, hours, minutes) as they pass, <font color=\"#ffff00\">for</font> if they get by without being filled, we will have wasted them.”\n翻译: <u>Gary Eberle 在他的《Sacred Time》一书中写道：“未来像空瓶子一样，沿着一条不可阻挡、近乎无限的传送带向我们而来，”而且“我们感到一种压力，要在这些大小不一的瓶子（天、小时、分钟）经过时把它们装满，因为如果它们没有被装满就过去了，我们就会觉得自己浪费了它们。”</u>\n\n-**conveyor belt**：<u>传送带。</u>\n-**for**：<u>这里的 for 比 because 更书面，表示解释原因。</u>\n\n---\n\nNo mind-set could be worse for losing yourself in a book.\n翻译: <u>没有哪种心态比这更不利于让自己沉浸在一本书中。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSo <font color=\"#ffff00\">what does work?</font>\n翻译: <u>那么，什么方法有效呢？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPerhaps surprisingly, scheduling regular times for reading.\n翻译: <u>也许令人意外的是：安排固定的阅读时间。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYou’d think this might <font color=\"#ffff00\">fuel</font> the efficiency mind-set, but in fact, Eberle notes, such ritualistic behaviour helps us “step outside time’s flow” into “soul time.”\n翻译: <u>你可能会以为这会助长效率心态，但事实上，Eberle 指出，这种仪式化行为帮助我们“走出时间的流动”，进入“灵魂时间”。</u>\n\n-**fuel**：<u>助长、刺激、加剧。</u>\n\n---\n\nYou could limit distractions by reading only physical books, or on single-purpose e-readers.\n翻译: <u>你可以通过只读纸质书，或者只用单一用途的电子阅读器，来减少干扰。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Carry a book with you at all times” can actually work, too – providing you dip in often enough, so that reading becomes the default state from which you temporarily surface to take care of business, before dropping back down.\n翻译: <u>“随时带一本书”实际上也能起作用，前提是你足够频繁地读上几页，以至于阅读成为你的默认状态；你只是暂时浮出水面去处理事务，然后再沉回阅读之中。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOn a really good day, it no longer feels as if you’re “making time to read,” but just reading, and making time for everything else.\n翻译: <u>在真正状态很好的一天，它不再感觉像是你在“挤时间读书”，而只是读书，并为其他一切挤出时间。</u>\n\n-**make time to read**：<u>腾出时间读书。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Against a backdrop of</font> drastic changes in economy and population structure, younger Americans are drawing a new 21st-century road map to success, a latest poll has found.\n翻译: <u>一项最新民调发现，在经济和人口结构发生剧烈变化的背景下，较年轻的美国人正在绘制一幅新的 21 世纪成功路线图。</u>\n\n-**against a backdrop of…**：<u>在……背景下。</u>\n\n---\n\nAcross <font color=\"#ffff00\">generational lines</font>, Americans continue to <font color=\"#ffff00\">prize</font> many of the same traditional milestones of a successful life, including getting married, having children, owning a home, and retiring in their sixties.\n翻译: <u>跨越代际界限，美国人仍然珍视成功人生的许多相同传统里程碑，包括结婚、生子、拥有住房以及在 60 多岁退休。</u>\n\n-**generational lines**：<u>代际界线。</u>\n-**prize**：<u>作动词时意思是“珍视、重视”。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut while young and old mostly agree on what constitutes the finish line of a fulfilling life, they offer strikingly different paths for reaching it.\n翻译: <u>但是，尽管年轻人和老年人在什么构成充实人生的终点上大体一致，他们却为到达这一终点提出了截然不同的路径。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYoung people who are still getting started in life were <font color=\"#ffff00\">more likely than older adults to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">prioritize</font> personal fulfillment in their work, to believe they will advance their careers most <font color=\"#ffff00\">by regularly changing jobs</font>, to favor communities with more public services and a faster pace of life, to agree that couples should be financially secure before getting married or having children, and to <font color=\"#ffff00\">maintain that</font> children are best served by two parents working outside the home, the survey found.\n翻译: <u>调查发现，仍处在人生起步阶段的年轻人比年长成年人更可能优先考虑工作中的个人满足感，更可能相信他们将通过定期换工作来最大程度推进职业发展，更可能偏爱公共服务更多、生活节奏更快的社区，更可能赞同夫妻在结婚或生孩子之前应当有经济保障，也更可能坚持认为，如果父母双方都在外工作，孩子会得到最好的照顾。</u>\n\n-**more likely than older adults to…**：<u>比年长者更可能……</u>\n-**prioritize**：<u>优先考虑、更加重视。</u>\n-**by regularly changing jobs**：<u>通过经常换工作。</u>\n-**maintain that…**：<u>坚持认为。</u>\n\n---\n\nFrom career to community and family, these contrasts suggest that in the aftermath of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">searing</font> Great Recession, those <font color=\"#ffff00\">just starting out in life</font> are defining priorities and expectations that will increasingly <font color=\"#ffff00\">spread through</font> virtually all aspects of American life, from consumer preferences to <font color=\"#ffff00\">housing patterns</font> to politics.\n翻译: <u>从职业到社区再到家庭，这些反差表明，在令人痛苦的大衰退之后，那些刚刚开始人生道路的人正在界定一些优先事项和期望，而这些优先事项和期望将越来越多地扩展到美国生活几乎所有方面，从消费偏好到住房模式，再到政治。</u>\n\n-**searing**：<u>灼痛的、严酷的、创伤性的。</u>\n-**just starting out in life**：<u>刚刚开启成年生活、刚进入社会。</u>\n-**spread through**：<u>扩散到、贯穿。</u>\n-**housing patterns**：<u>住房模式，比如住城市还是郊区、买房还是租房。</u>\n\n---\n\nYoung and old converge on one key point: Overwhelming majorities of both groups said they believe it is harder for young people today to get started in life than it was for earlier generations.\n翻译: <u>年轻人和老年人在一个关键点上趋同：两组中压倒性的多数都表示，他们认为今天的年轻人开始人生道路比早先几代人更难。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile younger people are somewhat more optimistic than their elders about the prospects for those starting out today, big majorities in both groups believe those “just getting started in life” face a tougher climb than earlier generations in reaching such signpost achievements as securing a good-paying job, starting a family, managing debt, and finding affordable housing.\n翻译: <u>尽管年轻人对今天刚起步者的前景比他们的长辈略微更乐观，但两组中的大多数人都认为，那些“刚开始人生道路”的人在实现一些标志性成就方面，比早先几代人面临更艰难的攀登，例如获得一份薪酬不错的工作、组建家庭、管理债务以及找到负担得起的住房。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPete Schneider considers the climb tougher today.\n翻译: <u>Pete Schneider 认为今天的攀登更加艰难。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSchneider, a 27-year-old <font color=\"#ffff00\">auto technician</font> from the Chicago suburbs, says he struggled to find a job after graduating from college.\n翻译: <u>Schneider 是一名来自芝加哥郊区的 27 岁汽车技师，他说自己大学毕业后曾艰难地寻找工作。</u>\n\n-**auto technician**：<u>汽车技师。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Even now that</font> he is working steadily, he said, “I can’t afford to <font color=\"#ffff00\">pay my monthly mortgage payments</font> on my own, so I have to rent rooms out to people to make that happen.”\n翻译: <u>他说，即使现在工作稳定，“我也负担不起独自支付每月的抵押贷款还款，所以我不得不把房间租给别人，才能做到这一点。”</u>\n\n-**now that**：<u>既然现在 / 现在由于。</u>\n-**even now that…**：<u>即便现在已经……</u>\n-**pay my monthly mortgage payments**：<u>支付每月房贷。</u>\n\n---\n\nLooking back, he is struck that his parents could provide a comfortable life for their children even though neither had completed college when he was young.\n翻译: <u>回顾过去，他感到震惊的是，在他年幼时，尽管父母都没有完成大学学业，他们却能为孩子提供舒适的生活。</u>\n\n-**be struck that…**：<u>被……触动、对……感到惊讶。</u>\n\n---\n\n“I still grew up in an upper middle-class home with parents who didn’t have college degrees,” Schneider said.\n翻译: <u>Schneider 说：“我仍然是在一个上中产阶级家庭中长大的，父母都没有大学学位。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I don’t think people are capable of that anymore.”\n翻译: <u>“我认为现在的人已经做不到这一点了。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2017","year":"2017","title":"2017 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2017 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2017 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nEvery Saturday morning, at 9 am, more than 50,000 runners set off to run 5km around their local park.\n翻译: <u>每个星期六早上 9 点，超过 50000 名跑者出发，在他们当地的公园周围跑 5 公里。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe Parkrun phenomenon began with a dozen friends and has <font color=\"#ffff00\">inspired</font> 400 events in the UK and more abroad.\n翻译: <u>Parkrun 现象始于十几个朋友，并已在英国激发出 400 场活动，在海外也有更多活动。</u>\n\n-**inspire**：<u>在这里不是简单“鼓舞”，而是“激发、促成”。</u>\n\n---\n\nEvents are free, staffed by thousands of volunteers.\n翻译: <u>这些活动免费，由数千名志愿者提供人员支持。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRunners range from four years old to grandparents; their times range from Andrew Baddeley’s world record 13 minutes 48 seconds up to an hour.\n翻译: <u>跑者从 4 岁儿童到祖父母辈都有；他们的用时从 Andrew Baddeley 创下的 13 分 48 秒世界纪录到一小时不等。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nParkrun is succeeding where London’s Olympic “legacy” is failing.\n翻译: <u>Parkrun 正在伦敦奥运“遗产”失败的地方取得成功。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTen years ago on Monday, it was announced that the Games of the 30th Olympiad would be in London.\n翻译: <u>十年前的那个星期一，人们宣布第 30 届奥林匹克运动会将在伦敦举行。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Planning documents</font> pledged that the great <font color=\"#ffff00\">legacy</font> of the Games would be to lever a nation of sport lovers away from their <font color=\"#ffff00\">couches</font>.\n翻译: <u>规划文件承诺，奥运会的伟大遗产将是把一个热爱体育的国家从沙发上拉起来。</u>\n\n-**planning documents**：<u>规划文件。</u>\n-**legacy**：<u>遗产、长期影响。</u>\n-**couches**：<u>沙发。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">population</font> would be fitter, healthier and produce more winners.\n翻译: <u>民众会更加健康、更加强健，并产生更多获胜者。</u>\n\n-**population**：<u>指英国整体人口。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt has not happened.\n翻译: <u>这并没有发生。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe number of adults doing weekly sport did rise, by nearly 2 million in the <font color=\"#ffff00\">run-up to</font> 2012 – but the general population was growing faster.\n翻译: <u>每周参加体育运动的成年人数量确实增加了，在 2012 年之前增加了近 200 万，但总人口增长得更快。</u>\n\n-**run-up to…**：<u>某事件前的准备阶段、前夕。</u>\n\n---\n\nWorse, the numbers are now falling at an accelerating rate.\n翻译: <u>更糟糕的是，这些数字如今正以加快的速度下降。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The opposition</font> claims primary school pupils doing at least two hours of sport a week have nearly halved.\n翻译: <u>反对党声称，每周至少进行两小时体育运动的小学生人数几乎减半。</u>\n\n-**the opposition**：<u>反对党。</u>\n\n---\n\nObesity has risen among adults and children.\n翻译: <u>成年人和儿童中的肥胖率都上升了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOfficial <font color=\"#ffff00\">retrospections</font> continue <font color=\"#ffff00\">as to why</font> London 2012 failed to “inspire a generation.”\n翻译: <u>官方仍在回顾反思，为什么 2012 年伦敦奥运会未能“激励一代人”。</u>\n\n-**retrospections**：<u>回顾、反思、检讨。</u>\n-**as to why…**：<u>关于为什么……。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe success of Parkrun offers answers.\n翻译: <u>Parkrun 的成功提供了答案。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nParkun is not a race but a <font color=\"#ffff00\">time trial</font>: Your only competitor is the clock.\n翻译: <u>Parkrun 不是一场比赛，而是一次计时测试：你唯一的竞争对手是时钟。</u>\n\n-**time trial**：<u>计时赛、计时测试，强调和自己的时间比较。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">ethos</font> welcomes anybody.\n翻译: <u>它的理念欢迎任何人。</u>\n\n-**ethos**：<u>精神、价值理念、风气。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere is as much joy over a puffed-out first-timer being clapped over the line as there is about top talent <font color=\"#ffff00\">shining</font>.\n翻译: <u>一个气喘吁吁的初次参加者在掌声中越过终点线所带来的喜悦，并不亚于顶尖人才表现出色所带来的喜悦。</u>\n\n-**shining**：<u>闪耀、表现出色。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe Olympic <font color=\"#ffff00\">bidders</font>, by contrast, wanted to get more people doing sport and to produce more elite athletes.\n翻译: <u>相比之下，奥运申办者既想让更多人参加体育运动，又想培养更多精英运动员。</u>\n\n-**bidders**：<u>申办者。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe dual aim was mixed up: The stress on <font color=\"#ffff00\">success over taking part</font> was <font color=\"#ffff00\">intimidating</font> for newcomers.\n翻译: <u>这种双重目标被混在了一起：强调成功而不是参与，对新来者来说令人望而生畏。</u>\n\n-**success over taking part**：<u>强调成功胜过参与。</u>\n-**intimidating**：<u>令人畏惧的、使人却步的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIndeed, there is something a little absurd in <font color=\"#ffff00\">the state</font> getting involved in the planning of such a fundamentally “grassroots” concept as community sports associations.\n翻译: <u>事实上，让国家参与规划社区体育协会这样一种根本上属于“草根”的概念，本身就有点荒唐。</u>\n\n-**the state**：<u>国家、政府。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf <font color=\"#ffff00\">there is a role for government</font>, it should really be getting involved in <font color=\"#ffff00\">providing common goods</font> – making sure there is space for playing fields and the money to pave tennis and netball courts, and encouraging the provision of all these activities in schools.\n翻译: <u>如果政府确有角色，它真正应该参与的是提供公共物品，确保有运动场地的空间，有资金来铺设网球场和无板篮球场，并鼓励学校提供所有这些活动。</u>\n\n-**there is a role for government**：<u>政府有可发挥的作用。</u>\n-**providing common goods**：<u>提供公共物品 / 公共资源。</u>\n-**common goods**：<u>指大家共同受益的基础条件，比如场地、设施、学校体育资源。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut successive governments have presided over selling <font color=\"#ffff00\">green spaces</font>, squeezing money from local authorities and declining attention on sport in education.\n翻译: <u>但历届政府却一直主导着出售绿地、压缩地方政府资金以及减少对教育中体育的关注。</u>\n\n-**green spaces**：<u>绿地、公园、运动场等公共绿色空间。</u>\n\n---\n\nInstead of <font color=\"#ffff00\">wordy</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">worthy</font> strategies, future governments need to do more to provide the conditions for sport to thrive.\n翻译: <u>未来的政府需要做更多事情来为体育运动的蓬勃发展提供条件，而不是提出冗长却看似高尚的策略。</u>\n\n-**wordy**：<u>冗长的、废话多的。</u>\n-**worthy**：<u>高尚的、值得赞许的；这里略带讽刺，指听起来正确但不一定有效的。</u>\n\n---\n\nOr at least not make them worse.\n翻译: <u>或者至少不要让这些条件变得更糟。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nWith so much focus on children’s use of screens, it’s easy for parents to forget about their own screen use.\n翻译: <u>由于人们如此关注孩子使用屏幕的问题，父母很容易忘记他们自己对屏幕的使用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Tech is designed to really suck you in,” says Jenny Radesky in her study of digital play, “and digital products are there to promote maximal engagement.\n翻译: <u>“科技产品的设计就是为了真正把你吸引进去，”Jenny Radesky 在她关于数字游戏的研究中说，“而数字产品的存在就是为了促进最大程度的参与。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt makes it hard to disengage, and leads to a lot of <font color=\"#ffff00\">bleed-over</font> into the family routine.”\n翻译: <u>这使人很难脱离出来，并导致它大量渗透到家庭日常安排之中。”</u>\n\n-**bleed-over**：<u>溢出、渗透、蔓延影响。</u>\n\n---\n\nRadesky has studied the use of mobile phones and tablets <font color=\"#ffff00\">at mealtimes</font> by giving mother-child pairs a <font color=\"#ffff00\">food-testing exercise</font>.\n翻译: <u>Radesky 通过让母子组合进行一项食物测试练习，研究了用餐时间使用手机和平板电脑的情况。</u>\n\n-**at mealtimes**：<u>在吃饭时间。</u>\n-**food-testing exercise**：<u>食物测试练习/实验任务。</u>\n\n---\n\nShe found that mothers who used devices during the exercise started 20 per cent fewer verbal and 39 per cent fewer nonverbal interactions with their children.\n翻译: <u>她发现，在练习过程中使用设备的母亲，与孩子发起的语言互动少了20%，非语言互动少了39%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDuring a <font color=\"#ffff00\">separate</font> observation, she <font color=\"#ffff00\">saw</font> that phones became a source of tension in the family.\n翻译: <u>在另一次单独观察中，她看到手机成了家庭中紧张关系的一个来源。</u>\n\n-**separate**：<u>单独的、另外的。</u>\n-**saw**：<u>这里不只是“看见”，也可以理解为“观察到、发现”。</u>\n\n---\n\nParents would be looking at their emails while the children would be making excited <font color=\"#ffff00\">bids</font> for their attention.\n翻译: <u>父母会在看他们的电子邮件，而孩子们则会兴奋地试图吸引他们的注意。</u>\n\n-**bid**：<u>这里不是“投标”，而是“努力争取、尝试获得”。</u>\n\n---\n\nInfants are wired to look at parents’ faces to try to understand their world, and if those faces are blank and unresponsive – as they often are when absorbed in a device – it can be extremely <font color=\"#ffff00\">disconcerting</font> for the children.\n翻译: <u>婴儿天生就会看父母的脸，试图理解他们的世界；而如果这些脸空白且没有回应——就像沉浸在设备中时常常出现的那样——这可能会让孩子极度不安。</u>\n\n-**be wired to do**：<u>天生被设定为做某事 / 生来就倾向于做某事。</u>\n-**disconcerting**：<u>令人不安的、令人困惑焦虑的。</u>\n\n---\n\nRadesky cites the “still face experiment” devised by developmental psychologist Ed Tronick in the 1970s.\n翻译: <u>Radesky 引用了发展心理学家 Ed Tronick 在20世纪70年代设计的“静止脸实验”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn it, a mother is asked to interact with her child in a normal way before putting on a blank expression and not giving them any visual social feedback: The child becomes increasingly distressed as she tries to capture her mother’s attention.\n翻译: <u>在这个实验中，一位母亲被要求先以正常方式与孩子互动，然后摆出空白表情，并不给孩子任何视觉上的社会反馈：当孩子试图吸引母亲注意时，她会变得越来越痛苦。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Parents don’t have to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">exquisitely</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">present</font> at all times, but there needs to be a balance and parents need to be responsive and sensitive to a child’s verbal or nonverbal expressions of an emotional need,” says Radesky.\n翻译: <u>“父母不必时时刻刻都极其专注地陪在孩子身边，但需要有一种平衡，而且父母需要对孩子通过语言或非语言方式表达出的情感需求作出回应并保持敏感，”Radesky 说。</u>\n\n-**exquisitely**：<u>极其、非常精细地。</u>\n-**present**：<u>在场的、投入陪伴的。</u>\n\n---\n\nOn the other hand, Tronick himself is concerned that the worries about kids’ use of screens are born out of an “<font color=\"#ffff00\">oppressive ideology</font> that demands that parents should always be interacting” with their children: “It’s based on a <font color=\"#ffff00\">somewhat fantasised</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">very white</font>, very upper-middle-class ideology that <font color=\"#ffff00\">says</font> if you’re failing to expose your child to 30,000 words you are neglecting them.”\n翻译: <u>另一方面，Tronick 本人担心，人们对孩子使用屏幕的忧虑源自一种“压迫性的意识形态，它要求父母应该始终”与孩子互动：“它建立在一种有些幻想化的、非常白人化的、非常上层中产阶级的意识形态之上，这种意识形态认为，如果你没有让孩子接触到3万个词，你就是在忽视他们。”</u>\n\n-**be born out of…**：<u>产生于、源于。</u>\n-**oppressive ideology**：<u>压迫性的意识形态 / 令人窒息的观念体系。</u>\n-**somewhat fantasised**：<u>有些幻想化的、不切实际的。</u>\n-**very white**：<u>非常白人化的。</u>\n-**says**：<u>在这里不是“说话”，而是“宣称、认为”。</u>\n\n---\n\nTronick believes that just because a child isn’t learning from the screen doesn’t mean there’s no value to it – particularly if it gives parents time to have a shower, do housework or simply have a break from their child.\n翻译: <u>Tronick 认为，仅仅因为孩子没有从屏幕中学习，并不意味着屏幕对孩子没有价值——尤其是如果它能给父母时间去洗个澡、做家务，或者只是从孩子身边休息一下。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nParents, he says, can get a lot out of using their devices to speak to a friend or get some work out of the way.\n翻译: <u>他说，父母可以通过使用设备和朋友交谈或处理完一些工作，从中获得很多好处。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis can make them feel happier, which lets them be more available to their child the rest of the time.\n翻译: <u>这可以让他们感到更快乐，从而使他们在其余时间更能陪伴孩子。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nToday, widespread social pressure to immediately go to college in conjunction with increasingly high expectations in a fast-moving world often causes students to completely overlook the possibility of taking a gap year.\n翻译: <u>如今，在一个快速变化的世界里，普遍存在的要求学生立即上大学的社会压力，与越来越高的期望相结合，常常使学生完全忽视了休间隔年的可能性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAfter all, if everyone you know is going to college in the fall, it seems silly to stay back a year, doesn’t it?\n翻译: <u>毕竟，如果你认识的每个人都将在秋天去上大学，那么晚一年再去似乎很愚蠢，不是吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd after going to school for 12 years, it doesn’t feel natural to spend a year doing something that isn’t academic.\n翻译: <u>而且，在上了12年学之后，花一年时间去做与学业无关的事情，感觉并不自然。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut while this may be true, it’s not a good enough reason to condemn gap years.\n翻译: <u>但是，尽管这可能是真的，它并不是一个足以谴责间隔年的理由。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere’s always a constant fear of falling behind everyone else on the <font color=\"#ffff00\">socially perpetuated</font> “race to the finish line,” whether that be toward graduate school, medical school or a <font color=\"#ffff00\">lucrative career</font>.\n翻译: <u>在社会不断推动的“冲向终点线”的竞赛中，人们总是持续害怕落后于其他所有人，无论那条终点线是研究生院、医学院，还是一份收入丰厚的职业。</u>\n\n-**socially perpetuated**：<u>由社会不断延续、不断强化的。</u>\n-**perpetuate**：<u>使持续、使延续。</u>\n-**lucrative career**：<u>赚钱多的职业、高薪职业。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut despite <font color=\"#ffff00\">common misconceptions</font>, a gap year does not hinder the success of academic pursuits – in fact, it probably enhances it.\n翻译: <u>但是，尽管存在普遍的误解，间隔年并不会阻碍学业追求的成功——事实上，它很可能会促进这种成功。</u>\n\n-**common misconceptions**：<u>常见误解。</u>\n\n---\n\nStudies from the United States and Australia show that students who take a gap year are generally better prepared for and perform better in college than those who do not.\n翻译: <u>来自美国和澳大利亚的研究显示，休间隔年的学生通常比不休间隔年的学生为大学学习准备得更充分，并且在大学中表现更好。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRather than <font color=\"#ffff00\">pulling students back</font>, a gap year pushes them ahead by preparing them for independence, new responsibilities and environmental changes\n翻译: <u>间隔年不是把学生拉在后面，而是通过让他们为独立、新责任和环境变化做好准备，推动他们走在前面。</u>\n\n-**pull students back**：<u>把学生往后拉、拖后腿。</u>\n\n---\n\n– all things that first-year students often struggle with <font color=\"#ffff00\">the most</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些都是一年级学生往往最难应对的事情。</u>\n\n-**the most**：<u>最。</u>\n\n---\n\nGap year experiences can lessen the blow when it comes to adjusting to college and being thrown into a brand new environment, making it easier to focus on academics and activities rather than <font color=\"#ffff00\">acclimation blunders</font>.\n翻译: <u>间隔年的经历可以减轻适应大学以及被投入一个全新环境时所带来的冲击，使学生更容易专注于学业和活动，而不是因适应不当而犯错。</u>\n\n-**acclimation blunders**：<u>适应新环境时犯的错误，</u>\n\n---\n\nIf you’re not convinced of the inherent value in taking a year off to explore interests, then consider its financial impact on future academic choices.\n翻译: <u>如果你还没有被花一年时间去探索兴趣这一本身价值说服，那么就考虑一下它对未来学业选择的经济影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAccording to the National Center for Education Statistics, nearly 80 percent of college students end up changing their majors at least once.\n翻译: <u>根据国家教育统计中心的数据，近80%的大学生最终至少会换一次专业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis isn’t surprising, <font color=\"#ffff00\">considering</font> the basic <font color=\"#ffff00\">mandatory</font> high school curriculum leaves students with a poor understanding of the vast academic possibilities that await them in college.\n翻译: <u>考虑到高中基本的必修课程使学生对大学里等待着他们的广泛学术可能性了解不足，这并不令人意外。</u>\n\n-**considering…**：<u>考虑到……、鉴于……。</u>\n-**mandatory**：<u>强制的、必修的。</u>\n\n---\n\nMany students find themselves listing one major on their <font color=\"#ffff00\">college applications</font>, but switching to another after taking college classes.\n翻译: <u>许多学生发现自己在大学申请表上填写的是一个专业，但在上了大学课程之后又转到另一个专业。</u>\n\n-**college applications**：<u>大学申请材料。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s not necessarily a bad thing, but depending on the school, it can be costly to make up credits after switching too late in the game.\n翻译: <u>这不一定是一件坏事，但根据学校不同，如果太晚转换专业，补修学分可能会代价高昂。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt Boston College, for example, you <font color=\"#ffff00\">would have to</font> complete an extra year were you to switch to the nursing school from another department.\n翻译: <u>例如，在波士顿学院，如果你要从另一个院系转到护理学院，就必须额外完成一年的学习。</u>\n\n-**would have to**：<u>将不得不，表示假设情况下的结果。</u>\n\n---\n\nTaking a gap year to figure things out <font color=\"#ffff00\">initially</font> can help prevent stress and save money <font color=\"#ffff00\">later on</font>.\n翻译: <u>一开始就休一个间隔年来弄清楚事情，可以帮助以后避免压力并节省金钱。</u>\n\n-**initially**：<u>一开始、最初阶段。</u>\n-**later on**：<u>后来、以后。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nThough often viewed as a problem for western states, the growing frequency of wildfires is a national concern because of its impact on <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal tax dollars</font>, says Professor Max Moritz, a specialist in fire ecology and management.\n翻译: <u>火生态与管理专家 Max Moritz 教授说，野火发生频率不断上升，虽然常被视为西部各州的问题，但由于其对联邦税款的影响，它是一个全国性的关切。</u>\n\n-**federal tax dollars**：<u>联邦税款，也就是全国纳税人的钱。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn 2015, the US Forest Service for the first time spent more than half of its $5.5 billion annual budget fighting fires – nearly double the percentage it spent on such efforts 20 years ago.\n翻译: <u>2015年，美国林务局首次将其55亿美元年度预算的一半以上用于灭火——这一比例几乎是20年前用于此类工作的比例的两倍。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In effect</font>, fewer federal funds today are going towards the agency’s other work – such as forest conservation, watershed and cultural resources management, and infrastructure upkeep – that affect the lives of all Americans.\n翻译: <u>实际上，如今用于该机构其他工作的联邦资金减少了——例如森林保护、流域和文化资源管理以及基础设施维护——而这些工作影响着所有美国人的生活。</u>\n\n-**in effect**：<u>实际上、事实上、结果等于是；它引出上一句预算倾斜带来的实际后果</u>\n\n---\n\nAnother nationwide concern is whether public funds from other agencies are going into construction in fire-prone districts.\n翻译: <u>另一个全国性的关切是，来自其他机构的公共资金是否正在流向火灾易发地区的建设。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs Moritz puts it, how often are federal dollars building homes that are likely to be lost to a wildfire?\n翻译: <u>正如 Moritz 所说，联邦资金有多频繁地被用来建造那些很可能会毁于野火的房屋？</u>\n\n-**as someone puts it**：<u>正如某人所说 / 用某人的说法。</u>\n\n---\n\n“It’s already a huge problem from a public expenditure perspective for the whole country,” he says.\n翻译: <u>“从全国公共支出的角度来看，这已经是一个巨大的问题，”他说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We need to take a magnifying glass to that.\n翻译: <u>“我们需要用放大镜仔细审视这一点。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nLike, ‘Wait a minute, is this OK?’ Do we want instead to redirect those funds to concentrate on lower-hazard <font color=\"#ffff00\">parts of the landscape</font>?”\n翻译: <u>比如，‘等一下，这样可以吗？’我们是否反而想要重新调配这些资金，把重点放在地貌中危险性较低的区域？”</u>\n\n-**parts of the landscape**：<u>地貌/地区中的部分区域。</u>\n\n---\n\nSuch a view would require a corresponding shift in the way US society today views fire, researchers say.\n翻译: <u>研究人员说，这样一种观点将要求美国社会如今看待火的方式发生相应转变。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For one thing</font>, conversations about wildfires need to be more <font color=\"#ffff00\">inclusive</font>.\n翻译: <u>首先，关于野火的讨论需要更具包容性。</u>\n\n-**For one thing**：<u>用来列举原因或方面，意思是“首先一点是”。</u>\n-**inclusive**：<u>包容的、覆盖面更广的；这里意思是：讨论野火问题时，不应只谈气候变化，还应纳入人类居住、土地使用、政策和社会系统等因素。</u>\n\n---\n\nOver the past decade, the focus has been on climate change – how the warming of the Earth from greenhouse gases is leading to conditions that worsen fires.\n翻译: <u>在过去十年里，焦点一直放在气候变化上——温室气体导致的地球变暖如何造成使火灾恶化的条件。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile climate is <font color=\"#ffff00\">a key element</font>, Moritz says, it shouldn’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">come at the expense of</font> the rest of the equation.\n翻译: <u>Moritz 说，虽然气候是一个关键因素，但它不应以牺牲等式中其余部分为代价。</u>\n\n-**a key element**：<u>关键因素。</u>\n-**come at the expense of…**：<u>以牺牲……为代价。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The human systems and the <font color=\"#ffff00\">landscapes</font> we live on are linked, and the interactions <font color=\"#ffff00\">go both ways</font>,” he says.\n翻译: <u>“人类系统与我们生活其上的景观是相互关联的，而且这种相互作用是双向的，”他说。</u>\n\n-**landscapes**：<u>地貌、自然景观、土地环境。</u>\n-**go both ways**：<u>双向发生；意思是：不是只有气候/自然影响人类，人类建设、土地管理也会反过来影响火灾风险</u>\n\n---\n\nFailing to recognize that, he notes, leads to “an overly simplified view of what the solutions might be.\n翻译: <u>他指出，未能认识到这一点，会导致“对可能的解决方案形成一种过于简化的看法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOur <font color=\"#ffff00\">perception</font> of the problem and of what the solution is becomes very limited.”\n翻译: <u>我们对问题以及解决方案是什么的认识变得非常有限。”</u>\n\n-**perception**：<u>认知、看法、理解。</u>\n\n---\n\nAt the same time, people continue to treat fire as an event that needs to be wholly controlled and <font color=\"#ffff00\">unleashed</font> only out of necessity, says Professor Balch at the University of Colorado.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，科罗拉多大学的 Balch 教授说，人们继续把火视为一种需要被完全控制、并且只有在必要时才释放出来的事件。</u>\n\n-**unleash**：<u>释放、放开；这里指有时人们会有控制性用火，比如 prescribed burn，即计划烧除、控制性燃烧</u>\n\n---\n\nBut acknowledging <font color=\"#ffff00\">fire’s inevitable presence</font> in human life is an attitude crucial to developing the laws, policies, and practices that make it as safe as possible, she says.\n翻译: <u>但她说，承认火在人类生活中不可避免的存在，是形成法律、政策和实践的一种关键态度，这些法律、政策和实践能使火尽可能安全。</u>\n\n-**fire’s inevitable presence**：<u>火不可避免的存在。</u>\n\n---\n\n“We’ve disconnected ourselves from living with fire,” Balch says.\n翻译: <u>“我们已经使自己与同火共处这件事脱节了，”Balch 说。</u>\n\n-**disconnect oneself from…**：<u>使自己与……脱离 / 切断自己与……的联系；这里指现代社会不再把火看作生活和生态的一部分，而只把它当成灾害</u>\n\n---\n\n“It is really important to understand and try and <font color=\"#ffff00\">tease out</font> what is the human connection with fire today.”\n翻译: <u>“理解并努力梳理清楚当今人类与火之间的联系是什么，真的非常重要。”</u>\n\n-**tease out**：<u>梳理出、弄清楚、细致分辨出。</u>\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2018","year":"2018","title":"2018 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2018 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2018 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIt is <font color=\"#ffff00\">curious</font> that Stephen Koziatek feels almost <font color=\"#ffff00\">as though</font> he has to <font color=\"#ffff00\">justify</font> his efforts to give his students a better future.\n翻译: <u>Stephen Koziatek 似乎觉得自己几乎必须为努力给学生一个更好的未来而辩护，这一点很奇怪。</u>\n\n-**curious**：<u>在这里不是“好奇的”，而是“奇怪的、耐人寻味的”。</u>\n-**as though**：<u>好像、仿佛。</u>\n-**justify**：<u>证明……是合理的、为……辩解。</u>\n\n---\n\nMr. Koziatek is part of <font color=\"#ffff00\">something pioneering</font>.\n翻译: <u>Koziatek 先生是某种开创性事物的一部分。</u>\n\n-**something pioneering**：<u>某种开创性的东西。</u>\n\n---\n\nHe is a teacher at a New Hampshire high school where learning is not something of books and tests and mechanical memorization, but practical.\n翻译: <u>他是新罕布什尔州一所高中的教师，在那里，学习不是书本、考试和机械记忆之类的东西，而是实践性的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen did it become <font color=\"#ffff00\">accepted wisdom</font> that students should be able to name the 13th president of the United States but be utterly overwhelmed by a broken bike chain?\n翻译: <u>什么时候起，学生应该能够说出美国第13任总统的名字，却会被一条断掉的自行车链彻底难倒，竟成了被接受的普遍看法？</u>\n\n-**accepted wisdom**：<u>公认的看法、普遍接受的观点。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">As</font> Koziatek knows, there is learning in just about everything.\n翻译: <u>正如 Koziatek 所知道的，几乎一切事物中都有学习。</u>\n\n-**as**：<u>正如。</u>\n\n---\n\nNothing is <font color=\"#ffff00\">necessarily</font> gained by forcing students to <font color=\"#ffff00\">learn geometry</font> at a graffitied desk <font color=\"#ffff00\">stuck with</font> generations of discarded chewing gum.\n翻译: <u>强迫学生坐在一张涂满涂鸦、粘着几代人丢弃的口香糖的课桌前学习几何，并不一定能获得什么。</u>\n\n-**necessarily**：<u>必然地、一定。</u>\n-**learn geometry**：<u>学习几何。</u>\n-**stuck with…**：<u>粘着……。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey can also learn geometry by assembling a bicycle.\n翻译: <u>他们也可以通过组装一辆自行车来学习几何。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut he’s also found a kind of insidious prejudice.\n翻译: <u>但他也发现了一种隐蔽的偏见。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWorking with your hands is seen as almost a mark of <font color=\"#ffff00\">inferiority</font>.\n翻译: <u>用双手劳动几乎被视为低人一等的标志。</u>\n\n-**inferiority**：<u>低等、劣等。</u>\n\n---\n\nSchools <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the family of vocational education</font> “have that stereotype...that it’s for kids who can’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">make it academically</font>,” he says.\n翻译: <u>他说，职业教育这一类学校“有那种刻板印象……认为它是给那些在学业上不行的孩子准备的”。</u>\n\n-**in the family of vocational education**：<u>属于职业教育这一类的学校。</u>\n-**make it academically**：<u>在学业上成功、适应学术道路。</u>\n\n---\n\nOn one hand, that viewpoint is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">logical product</font> of America’s evolution.\n翻译: <u>一方面，这种观点是美国演变过程中的一个合乎逻辑的产物。</u>\n\n-**logical product**：<u>合乎逻辑的产物。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Manufacturing</font> is not the economic engine that it once was.\n翻译: <u>制造业不再是它曾经那样的经济引擎。</u>\n\n-**manufacturing**：<u>制造业。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe <font color=\"#ffff00\">job security</font> that the US economy once offered to high school graduates has largely evaporated.\n翻译: <u>美国经济曾经提供给高中毕业生的就业保障，在很大程度上已经消失。</u>\n\n-**job security**：<u>工作稳定性、职业保障。</u>\n\n---\n\nMore education is the new principle.\n翻译: <u>更多教育成了新的原则。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe want more for our kids, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">rightfully so</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们希望孩子拥有更多，而且这是理所当然的。</u>\n\n-**rightfully so**：<u>理所当然地、合理地。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the <font color=\"#ffff00\">headlong</font> push into bachelor’s degrees <font color=\"#ffff00\">for all</font> – and the subtle <font color=\"#ffff00\">devaluing</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">anything less</font> – misses an important point: That’s not the only thing the American economy needs.\n翻译: <u>但是，一头扎进让所有人都获得学士学位的推动之中——并且微妙地贬低任何低于学士学位的东西——忽略了一个重要观点：那并不是美国经济唯一需要的东西。</u>\n\n-**headlong**：<u>仓促的、鲁莽向前的、不顾后果的。</u>\n-**for all**：<u>给所有人。</u>\n-**devaluing**：<u>贬低、降低价值。</u>\n-**anything less**：<u>任何低于本科学位的教育或资格，比如职业证书、技术培训、副学士等。</u>\n\n---\n\nYes, a bachelor’s degree opens more doors.\n翻译: <u>是的，学士学位会打开更多扇门。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">even now</font>, 54 percent of the jobs in the country are middle-skill jobs, such as construction and <font color=\"#ffff00\">high-skill manufacturing</font>.\n翻译: <u>但即使到现在，这个国家54%的工作岗位仍是中等技能岗位，例如建筑业和高技能制造业。</u>\n\n-**even now**：<u>即使在今天。</u>\n-**high-skill manufacturing**：<u>高技能制造业。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut only 44 percent of workers are adequately trained.\n翻译: <u>但只有44%的工人接受了足够的培训。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn other words, at a time when the working class has <font color=\"#ffff00\">turned the country on its political head</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">frustrated</font> that the opportunity that once defined America is vanishing, one obvious solution is <font color=\"#ffff00\">staring us in the face</font>.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，在这样一个时刻：工人阶级因曾经定义美国的机会正在消失而感到沮丧，并已使这个国家的政治格局发生了彻底翻转；一个显而易见的解决办法正摆在我们眼前。</u>\n\n-**turn the country on its political head**：<u>让国家政治天翻地覆。</u>\n-**frustrated**：<u>沮丧的、受挫的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThere is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">gap</font> in working-class jobs, but the workers who need those jobs most <font color=\"#ffff00\">aren’t equipped to do</font> them.\n翻译: <u>工人阶级岗位存在缺口，但最需要这些工作的工人却没有能力胜任它们。</u>\n\n-**gap**：<u>缺口、差距。</u>\n-**be equipped to do**：<u>具备做某事的能力、技能或准备。</u>\n\n---\n\nKoziatek’s Manchester School of Technology High School is trying to fill that gap.\n翻译: <u>Koziatek 的 Manchester School of Technology High School 正在努力填补这一缺口。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nKoziatek’s school is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">wake-up call</font>.\n翻译: <u>Koziatek 的学校是一记警钟。</u>\n\n-**wake-up call**：<u>警钟、提醒人醒悟的信号。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhen education becomes <font color=\"#ffff00\">one-size-fits-all</font>, it risks <font color=\"#ffff00\">overlooking</font> a nation’s diversity of <font color=\"#ffff00\">gifts</font>.\n翻译: <u>当教育变成一刀切时，它就有可能忽视一个国家多样化的才能。</u>\n\n-**one-size-fits-all**：<u>一刀切的、统一规格适用于所有人的</u>\n-**overlook**：<u>忽视、忽略。</u>\n-**gifts**：<u>天赋、才能。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">While</font> fossil fuels – coal, oil, gas – still generate roughly 85 percent of the world’s energy supply, it’s clearer than ever that the future belongs to renewable sources such as wind and solar.\n翻译: <u>尽管化石燃料——煤、石油、天然气——仍然产生着全球大约85%的能源供应，但比以往任何时候都更清楚的是，未来属于风能和太阳能等可再生能源。</u>\n\n-**while**：<u>在这里不是“当……时候”，而是“尽管”。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The move to renewables</font> is <font color=\"#ffff00\">picking up momentum</font> around the world: They now <font color=\"#ffff00\">account for</font> more than half of new power sources <font color=\"#ffff00\">going on line</font>.\n翻译: <u>向可再生能源转型的趋势正在全球范围内加速：它们如今占新投运电力来源的一半以上。</u>\n\n-**the move to renewables**：<u>向可再生能源的转变。</u>\n-**pick up momentum**：<u>积聚势头、加速发展。</u>\n-**account for**：<u>占据、占……比例。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome growth stems from a <font color=\"#ffff00\">commitment</font> by governments and <font color=\"#ffff00\">farsighted</font> businesses to <font color=\"#ffff00\">fund</font> cleaner energy sources.\n翻译: <u>部分增长源于各国政府和有远见的企业为更清洁能源来源提供资金的承诺。</u>\n\n-**commitment**：<u>承诺、投入。</u>\n-**farsighted**：<u>有远见的。</u>\n-**fund**：<u>资助、投入资金。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">increasingly</font> the story is about the <font color=\"#ffff00\">plummeting prices</font> of renewables, especially wind and solar.\n翻译: <u>但越来越多地，这一情况关乎可再生能源价格的暴跌，尤其是风能和太阳能。</u>\n\n-**increasingly**：<u>越来越。</u>\n-**plummeting prices**：<u>急剧下降的价格。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe cost of solar panels has dropped by 80 percent and the cost of <font color=\"#ffff00\">wind turbines</font> by <font color=\"#ffff00\">close to one-third</font> in the past eight years.\n翻译: <u>在过去八年里，太阳能电池板的成本下降了80%，风力涡轮机的成本下降了近三分之一。</u>\n\n-**wind turbines**：<u>风力涡轮机。</u>\n-**close to one-third**：<u>接近三分之一。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn many parts of the world renewable energy is already a <font color=\"#ffff00\">principal</font> energy source.\n翻译: <u>在世界许多地区，可再生能源已经是一种主要能源来源。</u>\n\n-**principal**：<u>主要的、重要的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn Scotland, for example, wind turbines provide enough electricity to power 95 percent of homes.\n翻译: <u>例如在苏格兰，风力涡轮机提供的电力足以供应95%的家庭用电。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the rest of the world takes the lead, notably China and Europe, the United States is also <font color=\"#ffff00\">seeing a remarkable shift</font>.\n翻译: <u>在世界其他地区，尤其是中国和欧洲，走在前列的同时，美国也正在经历一场显著转变。</u>\n\n-**see a shift**：<u>经历变化、出现转变。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn March, for the first time, wind and solar power accounted for more than 10 percent of the power generated in the US, reported the US Energy Information Administration.\n翻译: <u>美国能源信息署报道，3月份，风能和太阳能发电首次占美国发电量的10%以上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPresident Trump has <font color=\"#ffff00\">underlined</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">fossil fuels</font> – especially coal – as the path to economic growth.\n翻译: <u>特朗普总统强调，化石燃料——尤其是煤炭——是通往经济增长的道路。</u>\n\n-**underline**：<u>强调、突出。</u>\n-**fossil fuels**：<u>化石燃料。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a recent speech in Iowa, he <font color=\"#ffff00\">dismissed</font> wind power <font color=\"#ffff00\">as</font> an unreliable energy source.\n翻译: <u>在最近于艾奥瓦州的一次演讲中，他把风能斥为一种不可靠的能源来源。</u>\n\n-**dismiss A as B**：<u>把 A 轻描淡写地否定为 B / 不屑地称 A 为 B。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut that message <font color=\"#ffff00\">did not play well</font> with many in Iowa, where wind turbines dot the fields and provide 36 percent of the state’s electricity generation – and where tech giants like Microsoft are being attracted by the availability of clean energy to power their data centers.\n翻译: <u>但这一信息并未得到艾奥瓦州许多人的认同；在那里，风力涡轮机遍布田野，提供该州36%的发电量；而且微软等科技巨头正因可用于为其数据中心供电的清洁能源而被吸引到那里。</u>\n\n-**did not play well**：<u>反响不好。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe question “what happens when the wind doesn’t blow or the sun doesn’t shine?” has provided a quick <font color=\"#ffff00\">put-down</font> for <font color=\"#ffff00\">skeptics</font>.\n翻译: <u>“当风不吹、太阳不照时会发生什么？”这个问题为怀疑者提供了一句快速的贬低之词。</u>\n\n-**put-down**：<u>贬低的话、挖苦、反驳。</u>\n-**skeptics**：<u>怀疑者。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut a boost in the storage capacity of batteries is making their ability to keep power flowing <font color=\"#ffff00\">around the clock</font> more likely.\n翻译: <u>但是，电池储能能力的提升正在使它们维持全天候电力持续供应的能力变得更有可能。</u>\n\n-**around the clock**：<u>全天候、昼夜不停。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The advance</font> is driven <font color=\"#ffff00\">in part</font> by vehicle manufacturers, who are <font color=\"#ffff00\">placing big bets</font> on battery-powered electric vehicles.\n翻译: <u>这一进步在一定程度上是由汽车制造商推动的，他们正在大举押注由电池驱动的电动汽车。</u>\n\n-**The advance**：<u>指电池储能能力的提升</u>\n-**in part**：<u>部分地。</u>\n\n---\n\nAlthough electric cars are still a <font color=\"#ffff00\">rarity</font> on roads now, this massive investment could change the picture rapidly in coming years.\n翻译: <u>尽管电动汽车现在在道路上仍然很少见，但这项巨额投资可能在未来几年迅速改变局面。</u>\n\n-**rarity**：<u>罕见之物。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile there’s a long way to go, the trend lines for renewables are <font color=\"#ffff00\">spiking</font>.\n翻译: <u>尽管还有很长的路要走，可再生能源的趋势线正在急剧上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe pace of change in energy sources appears to be speeding up – perhaps <font color=\"#ffff00\">just in time</font> to <font color=\"#ffff00\">have a meaningful effect</font> in slowing climate change.\n翻译: <u>能源来源变化的速度似乎正在加快——也许正好来得及对减缓气候变化产生有意义的影响。</u>\n\n-**just in time**：<u>刚好及时。</u>\n-**have a meaningful effect**：<u>产生有意义的影响。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat Washington does – or doesn’t do – to promote alternative energy may mean less and less at a time of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">global shift in thought</font>.\n翻译: <u>在全球思想转变的时期，华盛顿为促进替代能源所做或不做的事情，可能会变得越来越不重要。</u>\n\n-**global shift in thought**：<u>全球思想/观念转变。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nThe power and ambition of the giants of the digital economy is <font color=\"#ffff00\">astonishing</font>-\n翻译: <u>数字经济巨头的力量和野心令人震惊——</u>\n\n-**astonishing**：<u>令人惊讶的、惊人的。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmazon has just announced the <font color=\"#ffff00\">purchase</font> of the <font color=\"#ffff00\">upmarket</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">grocery chain</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">Whole Foods</font> for ＄ 13.5bn, but two years ago Facebook paid even more than that to <font color=\"#ffff00\">acquire</font> the WhatsApp messaging service, which doesn’t have any physical product at all.\n翻译: <u>亚马逊刚刚宣布以135亿美元收购高端食品杂货连锁店 Whole Foods，但两年前，Facebook 为收购 WhatsApp 这一并没有任何实体产品的消息服务所支付的金额甚至超过了这个数。</u>\n\n-**purchase**：<u>购买、收购。</u>\n-**upmarket**：<u>高端的、面向较富裕消费者的。</u>\n-**grocery chain**：<u>食品杂货连锁店。</u>\n-**Whole Foods**：<u>全食超市。</u>\n-**acquire**：<u>收购。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat WhatsApp offered Facebook was an <font color=\"#ffff00\">intricate</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">finely detailed</font> web of its users’ friendships and social lives.\n翻译: <u>WhatsApp 向 Facebook 提供的，是一个由其用户的友谊和社交生活构成的复杂而极其详尽的网络。</u>\n\n-**intricate**：<u>复杂精细的。</u>\n-**finely detailed**：<u>细节非常丰富的。</u>\n\n---\n\nFacebook promised the European commission <font color=\"#ffff00\">then</font> that it would not link phone numbers to <font color=\"#ffff00\">Facebook identities</font>, but it broke the promise almost as soon as <font color=\"#ffff00\">the deal went through</font>.\n翻译: <u>Facebook 当时向欧盟委员会承诺，它不会把电话号码与 Facebook 身份关联起来，但交易一完成，它几乎立刻就违背了这一承诺。</u>\n\n-**then**：<u>当时，指收购 WhatsApp 的时候。</u>\n-**Facebook identities**：<u>Facebook 身份/账号身份。</u>\n-**the deal went through**：<u>交易完成、交易获批并生效。</u>\n\n---\n\nEven without knowing what was in the messages, <font color=\"#ffff00\">the knowledge of</font> who sent them and to whom was <font color=\"#ffff00\">enormously</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">revealing</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">still could be</font>.\n翻译: <u>即使不知道消息内容是什么，知道是谁发送了它们以及发送给谁，也极具揭示性，而且仍然可能如此。</u>\n\n-**the knowledge of…**：<u>关于……的信息。</u>\n-**enormously**：<u>极其、非常。</u>\n-**revealing**：<u>揭示性的、透露大量信息的。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhat political journalist, <font color=\"#ffff00\">what party whip</font>, would not want to know the makeup of the WhatsApp groups in which Theresa May’s enemies are currently plotting?\n翻译: <u>哪位政治记者、哪位政党督导员，会不想知道特蕾莎·梅的敌人目前正在其中密谋的 WhatsApp 群组的构成呢？</u>\n\n-**what party whip**：<u>哪个党鞭/政党督导员。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It may be that</font> the value of Whole Foods to Amazon is not so much the 460 shops it owns, but the records of which customers have purchased what.\n翻译: <u>Whole Foods 对亚马逊的价值或许不在于它拥有的460家门店，而更多在于记录了哪些顾客购买了什么的资料。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Competition law</font> appears to be the only way to address these imbalances of power.\n翻译: <u>竞争法似乎是解决这些权力失衡的唯一方式。</u>\n\n-**competition law**：<u>竞争法、反垄断法。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut it is <font color=\"#ffff00\">clumsy</font>.\n翻译: <u>但它很笨拙。</u>\n\n-**clumsy**：<u>笨拙的、不灵活的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">For one thing</font>, it is very slow compared to the pace of change within the digital economy.\n翻译: <u>一方面，与数字经济内部的变化速度相比，它非常缓慢。</u>\n\n-**for one thing**：<u>首先、一方面。</u>\n\n---\n\nBy the time a problem has been addressed and remedied it may have vanished in the marketplace, to be replaced by <font color=\"#ffff00\">new abuses of power</font>.\n翻译: <u>等到一个问题得到处理和补救时，它可能已经在市场中消失，并被新的权力滥用所取代。</u>\n\n-**new abuses of power**：<u>新的权力滥用。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut there is a deeper conceptual problem, too.\n翻译: <u>但还有一个更深层的概念问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCompetition law <font color=\"#ffff00\">as presently interpreted</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">deals with</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">financial disadvantage</font> to consumers and this is not obvious when the users of these services don’t pay for them.\n翻译: <u>按照目前的解释，竞争法处理的是消费者在经济上的不利处境；而当这些服务的用户并不为其付费时，这一点并不明显。</u>\n\n-**as presently interpreted**：<u>按照目前的解释方式。</u>\n-**financial disadvantage**：<u>金钱上的不利、经济损害。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe users of their services are not their customers.\n翻译: <u>这些服务的用户并不是它们的客户。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat would be the people who buy advertising\n翻译: <u>客户应当是那些购买广告的人</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nfrom them – and Facebook and Google, the two virtual giants, dominate digital\n翻译: <u>从它们那里购买广告的人——而 Facebook 和 Google 这两大虚拟巨头，主导着数字</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nadvertising to the disadvantage of all other media and entertainment companies.\n翻译: <u>广告，从而使所有其他媒体和娱乐公司处于不利地位。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe product they’re selling is data, and we, the users, convert our lives to data <font color=\"#ffff00\">for the benefit of the digital giants</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们出售的产品是数据，而我们这些用户，则为了数字巨头的利益把自己的生活转化为数据。</u>\n\n-**for the benefit of…**：<u>为了……的利益。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Just as</font> some ants <font color=\"#ffff00\">farm</font> the bugs called aphids for the honeydew they produce when they <font color=\"#ffff00\">feed</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">so</font> Google farms us for the data that our digital lives yield.\n翻译: <u>正如有些蚂蚁饲养一种叫蚜虫的小虫，以获取它们进食时产生的蜜露一样，Google 也在“饲养”我们，以获取我们的数字生活所产生的数据。</u>\n\n-**Just as…so…**：<u>正如……一样，……也……。</u>\n-**farm**：<u>在这里作动词，意思是“饲养、养殖”。</u>\n-**feed**：<u>进食。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnts keep <font color=\"#ffff00\">predatory insects</font> away from where their aphids feed; Gmail keeps the <font color=\"#ffff00\">spammers</font> out of our inboxes.\n翻译: <u>蚂蚁会把捕食性昆虫赶离蚜虫进食的地方；Gmail 会把垃圾邮件挡在我们的收件箱之外。</u>\n\n-**predatory insects**：<u>捕食性昆虫。</u>\n-**spammers**：<u>垃圾邮件发送者。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt doesn’t feel like a <font color=\"#ffff00\">human</font> or democratic relationship, even if <font color=\"#ffff00\">both sides</font> benefit.\n翻译: <u>这并不像一种人性化或民主的关系，即便双方都从中受益。</u>\n\n-**human relationship**：<u>人性化关系。</u>\n-**both sides**：<u>双方，即平台和用户。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nTo combat the trap of putting a premium on being busy, Cal Newport, author of Deep Work: Rules for Focused Success in a Distracted World, recommends building a habit of “deep work” – the ability to focus without distraction.\n翻译: <u>为了对抗把忙碌视为高价值的陷阱，《深度工作：在分心世界中专注成功的法则》一书作者 Cal Newport 建议养成“深度工作”的习惯——即不受干扰地专注的能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere are a number of approaches to mastering the art of deep work – be it lengthy retreats dedicated to a specific task; developing a daily ritual; or taking a “journalistic” approach to seizing moments of deep work when you can throughout the day.\n翻译: <u>掌握深度工作艺术的方法有很多——无论是为某项特定任务而进行的长时间闭关；培养一种日常仪式；还是采取一种“新闻记者式”的方法，在一天中尽可能抓住深度工作的时刻。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhichever approach, the key is to determine your length of focus time and stick to it.\n翻译: <u>无论采用哪种方法，关键都是确定你的专注时间长度，并坚持下去。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNewport also recommends “deep scheduling” to combat constant interruptions and get more done in less time.\n翻译: <u>Newport 还建议采用“深度排程”，以对抗持续不断的打扰，并在更少时间内完成更多事情。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“At any given point, I should have deep work scheduled for roughly the next month.\n翻译: <u>他写道：“在任何给定时刻，我都应该已经为接下来大约一个月安排好深度工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOnce on the calendar, I protect this time like I would a doctor’s appointment or important meeting”, he writes.\n翻译: <u>一旦写进日程表，我就会像对待医生预约或重要会议一样保护这段时间。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnother approach to getting more done in less time is to rethink how you prioritise your day – in particular how we craft our to-do lists.\n翻译: <u>在更少时间内完成更多事情的另一种方法，是重新思考你如何安排一天的优先事项——尤其是我们如何制定待办事项清单。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTim Harford, author of Messy: The Power of Disorder to Transform Our Lives, points to a study in the early 1980s that divided undergraduates into two groups: some were advised to set out monthly goals and study activities; others were told to plan activities and goals in much more detail, day by day.\n翻译: <u>《混乱：无序改变我们生活的力量》一书作者 Tim Harford 提到20世纪80年代早期的一项研究，该研究把本科生分成两组：一些人被建议列出每月目标和学习活动；另一些人则被要求按天更详细地规划活动和目标。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the researchers assumed that the well-structured daily plans would be most effective when it came to the execution of tasks, they were wrong: the detailed daily plans demotivated students.\n翻译: <u>虽然研究人员原以为，在执行任务时，结构良好的每日计划会最有效，但他们错了：详细的每日计划削弱了学生的积极性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHarford argues that inevitable distractions often render the daily to-do list ineffective, while leaving room for improvisation in such a list can reap the best results.\n翻译: <u>Harford 认为，不可避免的干扰常常使每日待办事项清单失效，而在这样的清单中为即兴调整留出空间，则能够取得最佳结果。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn order to make the most of our focus and energy, we also need to embrace downtime, or as Newport suggests, “be lazy”.\n翻译: <u>为了最大限度地利用我们的专注力和精力，我们还需要接受停工休息，或者正如 Newport 所建议的那样，“懒惰”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Idleness is not just a vacation, an indulgence or a vice; it is as indispensable to the brain as vitamin D is to the body…[idleness] is, paradoxically, necessary to getting any work done,” he argues.\n翻译: <u>他认为：“无所事事不只是假期、放纵或恶习；它对大脑来说就像维生素D对身体一样不可或缺……[无所事事] 反而是完成任何工作所必需的。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSrini Pillay, an assistant professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School, believes this counterintuitive link between downtime and productivity may be due to the way our brains operate.\n翻译: <u>哈佛医学院精神病学助理教授 Srini Pillay 认为，停工休息与生产力之间这种违反直觉的联系，可能源于我们大脑的运作方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen our brains switch between being focused and unfocused on a task, they tend to be more efficient.\n翻译: <u>当我们的大脑在专注于某项任务和不专注于该任务之间切换时，它们往往会更有效率。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“What people don’t realise is that in order to complete these tasks they need to use both the focus and unfocus circuits in their brain,” says Pillay.\n翻译: <u>Pillay 说：“人们没有意识到的是，为了完成这些任务，他们需要同时使用大脑中的专注回路和非专注回路。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2019","year":"2019","title":"2019 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2019 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2019 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nUnlike <font color=\"#ffff00\">so-called</font> basic emotions such as sadness, fear, and anger, guilt emerges a little later, <font color=\"#ffff00\">in conjunction with</font> a child’s growing <font color=\"#ffff00\">grasp</font> of <font color=\"#ffff00\">social and moral norms</font>.\n翻译: <u>与悲伤、恐惧和愤怒等所谓基本情绪不同，内疚出现得稍晚一些，它伴随着儿童对社会和道德规范日益增长的理解而产生。</u>\n\n-**so-called**：<u>所谓的。这里不一定表示质疑，也可能只是引用学术分类名称。</u>\n-**in conjunction with**：<u>与……同时、伴随着……。</u>\n-**grasp**：<u>在这里是“理解、掌握”，不是“抓住”。</u>\n-**social and moral norms**：<u>社会规范和道德准则。</u>\n\n---\n\nChildren aren’t born knowing how to say “I’m sorry”; <font color=\"#ffff00\">rather</font>, they learn over time that such statements appease parents and friends – and their own consciences.\n翻译: <u>孩子并不是天生就知道如何说“对不起”；相反，他们随着时间推移才学会，这类话语可以安抚父母和朋友——也可以安抚他们自己的良心。</u>\n\n-**rather**：<u>常用于；不是 A，而是 B</u>\n\n---\n\nThis is why researchers generally regard so-called <font color=\"#ffff00\">moral guilt</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the right amount</font>, to be a good thing.\n翻译: <u>这就是为什么研究人员通常认为，适量的所谓道德内疚是一件好事。</u>\n\n-**regard A to be B**：<u>认为 A 是 B。</u>\n-**moral guilt**：<u>道德性内疚，即因违反道德标准或伤害别人而产生的愧疚。</u>\n-**in the right amount**：<u>程度恰当、适量。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the popular imagination, of course, guilt still gets a bad <font color=\"#ffff00\">rap</font>.\n翻译: <u>当然，在大众想象中，内疚仍然名声不佳。</u>\n\n-**rap**：<u>在这里不是“说唱”，而是“评价、名声”。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt is deeply uncomfortable – it’s the emotional equivalent of wearing a jacket <font color=\"#ffff00\">weighted with</font> stones.\n翻译: <u>它令人非常不舒服——它在情感上相当于穿着一件装满石头的夹克。</u>\n\n-**weighted with…**：<u>装有……而变沉的。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet this understanding is outdated.\n翻译: <u>然而，这种理解已经过时了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“There has been a kind of <font color=\"#ffff00\">revival</font> or a rethinking about what guilt is and what role guilt can serve,” says Amrisha Vaish, a psychology researcher at the University of Virginia, adding that this revival is part of <font color=\"#ffff00\">a larger recognition</font> that emotions aren’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">binary</font> – feelings that may be <font color=\"#ffff00\">advantageous</font> in one context may be harmful in another.\n翻译: <u>弗吉尼亚大学心理学研究者 Amrisha Vaish 说：“关于内疚是什么以及内疚能够发挥什么作用，已经出现了一种复兴或重新思考。”她补充说，这种复兴是人们更广泛地认识到情绪并非二元对立的一部分——在一种情境中可能有利的感受，在另一种情境中可能有害。</u>\n\n-**revival**：<u>重新受到重视、观念复兴。</u>\n-**a larger recognition**：<u>一种更广泛的认识。</u>\n-**binary**：<u>二元的、非此即彼的。</u>\n-**advantageous**：<u>有利的。</u>\n\n---\n\nJealousy and anger, for example, may have <font color=\"#ffff00\">evolved</font> to alert us to important inequalities.\n翻译: <u>例如，嫉妒和愤怒可能是进化而来，用以提醒我们注意重要的不平等。</u>\n\n-**evolve**：<u>进化、逐渐形成。</u>\n\n---\n\nToo much happiness can be destructive.\n翻译: <u>过多的幸福可能具有破坏性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd guilt, by prompting us to think more deeply about <font color=\"#ffff00\">our goodness</font>, can encourage humans to make up for errors and fix relationships.\n翻译: <u>而内疚感通过促使我们更深入地思考自己的善良，可以鼓励人类弥补错误并修复关系。</u>\n\n-**our goodness**：<u>我们的善良、自己的道德品质。</u>\n\n---\n\nGuilt, in other words, can help hold a cooperative species together.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，内疚感有助于把一个合作性物种凝聚在一起。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is a kind of social glue.\n翻译: <u>它是一种社会黏合剂。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nViewed <font color=\"#ffff00\">in this light</font>, guilt is an opportunity.\n翻译: <u>从这个角度看，内疚感是一种机会。</u>\n\n-**in this light**：<u>从这个角度、按照这种理解。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Work</font> by Tina Malti, a psychology professor at the University of Toronto, suggests that guilt may compensate for an <font color=\"#ffff00\">emotional deficiency</font>.\n翻译: <u>多伦多大学心理学教授蒂娜·马尔蒂的研究表明，内疚感可能会弥补一种情感缺陷。</u>\n\n-**work**：<u>在这里不是“工作”，而是“研究成果、研究工作”。</u>\n-**emotional deficiency**：<u>情感缺陷、某种情感能力不足。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a number of studies, Malti and others have shown that guilt and sympathy may represent different pathways to cooperation and sharing.\n翻译: <u>在多项研究中，马尔蒂和其他研究者已经表明，内疚感和同情心可能代表通向合作与分享的不同路径。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome kids who are low in sympathy may <font color=\"#ffff00\">make up for</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">that shortfall</font> by experiencing more guilt, which can rein in their <font color=\"#ffff00\">nastier impulses</font>.\n翻译: <u>一些同情心水平较低的孩子，可能会通过体验更多内疚感来弥补这一不足，而这种内疚感能够约束他们较为恶劣的冲动。</u>\n\n-**make up for**：<u>弥补。</u>\n-**that shortfall**：<u>那种不足，指同情心不足。</u>\n-**nastier impulses**：<u>更恶劣、不友善的冲动。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd <font color=\"#ffff00\">vice versa</font>: High sympathy can substitute for low guilt.\n翻译: <u>反之亦然：高同情心可以替代低内疚感。</u>\n\n-**vice versa**：<u>反之亦然。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a 2014 study, for example, Malti <font color=\"#ffff00\">looked at</font> 244 children.\n翻译: <u>例如，在2014年的一项研究中，马尔蒂考察了244名儿童。</u>\n\n-**look at**：<u>在研究语境中是“考察、研究”，不是简单“看”。</u>\n\n---\n\nUsing caregiver assessments and the children’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-observations</font>, she <font color=\"#ffff00\">rated</font> each child’s overall sympathy level and his or her tendency to feel negative emotions after <font color=\"#ffff00\">moral transgressions</font>.\n翻译: <u>她利用照护者的评估和儿童的自我观察，评定了每个孩子的总体同情心水平，以及他或她在道德违规后感到负面情绪的倾向。</u>\n\n-**self-observations**：<u>自我观察、自我报告。</u>\n-**rate**：<u>评定、测量、打分。</u>\n-**moral transgressions**：<u>违反道德规范的行为、道德过失。</u>\n\n---\n\nThen the kids were handed chocolate coins, and given a chance to share them with an anonymous child.\n翻译: <u>随后，孩子们得到了巧克力金币，并被给予一个机会，可以把它们分享给一个匿名儿童。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFor the low-sympathy kids, how much they shared appeared to <font color=\"#ffff00\">turn on</font> how inclined they were to feel guilty.\n翻译: <u>对于同情心水平较低的孩子来说，他们分享多少似乎取决于他们有多倾向于感到内疚。</u>\n\n-**turn on**：<u>在这里不是“打开”，而是“取决于”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe guilt-prone ones shared more, even though they hadn’t <font color=\"#ffff00\">magically</font> become more sympathetic to the other child’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">deprivation</font>.\n翻译: <u>那些容易内疚的孩子分享得更多，尽管他们并没有神奇地变得更同情另一个孩子的匮乏处境。</u>\n\n-**magically**：<u>神奇地、突然地。这里带有轻微幽默。</u>\n-**deprivation**：<u>缺乏、匮乏、被剥夺。</u>\n\n---\n\n“That’s good news, ” Malti says.\n翻译: <u>“这是个好消息，”马尔蒂说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We can be <font color=\"#ffff00\">prosocial</font> because we <font color=\"#ffff00\">caused harm</font> and we feel regret.”\n翻译: <u>“我们可能因为自己造成了伤害并感到后悔，而表现出亲社会行为。”</u>\n\n-**prosocial**：<u>亲社会的，有利于他人或社会合作的。</u>\n-**cause harm**：<u>造成伤害。</u>\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nForests give us shade, quiet and one of the harder challenges in the fight against climate change.\n翻译: <u>森林给我们提供树荫、宁静，也给我们带来应对气候变化斗争中较为艰难的挑战之一。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Even as</font> we humans count on forests to soak up a good share of the carbon dioxide we produce, we are threatening their ability to do so.\n翻译: <u>尽管我们人类指望森林吸收我们所产生的相当一部分二氧化碳，但我们正在威胁它们这样做的能力。</u>\n\n-**even as**：<u>在这里有“尽管与此同时”的意思；正当</u>\n\n---\n\nThe climate change we are <font color=\"#ffff00\">hastening</font> could one day leave us with forests that emit more carbon than they absorb.\n翻译: <u>我们正在加速的气候变化，有朝一日可能会让我们面对释放的碳多于吸收的碳的森林。</u>\n\n-**hasten**：<u>加速、促使更快发生。</u>\n\n---\n\nThankfully, there is a way out of this trap – but it involves striking a subtle balance.\n翻译: <u>值得庆幸的是，有一条摆脱这一困境的出路——但它涉及达成一种微妙的平衡。</u>\n\n-**strike a balance**：<u>取得平衡。</u>\n\n---\n\nHelping forests flourish as valuable “carbon sinks” long into the future may require reducing their capacity to absorb carbon now.\n翻译: <u>要帮助森林作为宝贵的“碳汇”在未来长期繁荣，可能需要现在降低它们吸收碳的能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCalifornia is <font color=\"#ffff00\">leading the way</font>, as it does on so many climate efforts, in figuring out <font color=\"#ffff00\">the details</font>.\n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚州正在摸索细节方面走在前列，正如它在许多气候行动中所做的那样。</u>\n\n-**lead the way**：<u>带头、领先、作示范。</u>\n-**the details**：<u>具体细节、实施方案。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe state’s proposed Forest Carbon Plan aims to double efforts to <font color=\"#ffff00\">thin out</font> young trees and clear brush in parts of the forest.\n翻译: <u>该州拟议的《森林碳计划》旨在加倍努力，对部分森林中的幼树进行间伐并清理灌木丛。</u>\n\n-**thin out**：<u>疏伐、减少密度。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis temporarily lowers carbon-carrying capacity.\n翻译: <u>这会暂时降低碳承载能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the remaining trees <font color=\"#ffff00\">draw</font> a greater share of the available moisture, so they grow and thrive, restoring the forest’s capacity to pull carbon from the air.\n翻译: <u>但剩余的树木会吸收更大份额的可用水分，因此它们能够生长并繁盛，从而恢复森林从空气中吸收碳的能力。</u>\n\n-**draw**：<u>吸收、获取。</u>\n\n---\n\nHealthy trees are also better able to fend off insects.\n翻译: <u>健康的树木也更能够抵御昆虫。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe landscape is rendered less easily burnable.\n翻译: <u>这片景观会变得不那么容易燃烧。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven <font color=\"#ffff00\">in the event of</font> a fire, fewer trees are consumed.\n翻译: <u>即使发生火灾，被烧毁的树木也会更少。</u>\n\n-**in the event of…**：<u>如果发生……、在……发生的情况下。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe need for such planning is increasingly urgent.\n翻译: <u>对此类规划的需求正变得日益迫切。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Already</font>, since 2010, drought and insects have killed over 100 million trees in California, most of them in 2016 alone, and wildfires have burned hundreds of thousands of acres.\n翻译: <u>自2010年以来，干旱和昆虫已经在加利福尼亚州造成超过1亿棵树死亡，其中大多数仅发生在2016年，而野火已经烧毁了数十万英亩土地。</u>\n\n-**already**：<u>已经、事实上已经。</u>\n\n---\n\nCalifornia plans to treat 35, 000 acres of forest a year by 2020, and 60,000 by 2030 – financed from the <font color=\"#ffff00\">proceeds</font> of the state’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">emissions-permit auctions</font>.\n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚州计划到2020年每年治理3.5万英亩森林，到2030年每年治理6万英亩——资金来自该州排放许可拍卖的收益。</u>\n\n-**treat forest**：<u>治理、处理森林。</u>\n-**proceeds**：<u>所得款项、收益。</u>\n-**emissions-permit auctions**：<u>排放许可拍卖。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat’s only a small share of the total <font color=\"#ffff00\">acreage</font> that could benefit, about half a million acres in all, so it will be vital to prioritize areas at greatest risk of fire or drought.\n翻译: <u>这只是在所有可能受益的总面积中占很小一部分，总计约有50万英亩，因此优先处理火灾或干旱风险最高的地区将至关重要。</u>\n\n-**acreage**：<u>土地面积、英亩数。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe strategy also aims to ensure that carbon in woody material removed from the forests is locked away in the form of solid lumber or burned as biofuel in vehicles that would otherwise run on fossil fuels.\n翻译: <u>该策略还旨在确保从森林中移除的木质材料中的碳，以实木木材的形式被封存起来，或作为生物燃料在原本会使用化石燃料的车辆中燃烧。</u>\n\n-**lock away carbon**：<u>把碳固定、封存起来。</u>\n\n---\n\nNew research on <font color=\"#ffff00\">transportation biofuels</font> is already under way.\n翻译: <u>关于交通运输生物燃料的新研究已经在进行中。</u>\n\n-**transportation biofuels**：<u>用于交通运输的生物燃料。</u>\n\n---\n\nState governments are <font color=\"#ffff00\">well accustomed</font> to managing forests, but traditionally they’ve focused on wildlife, <font color=\"#ffff00\">watersheds</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">opportunities for recreation</font>.\n翻译: <u>州政府非常习惯于管理森林，但传统上它们关注的是野生动物、流域和休闲机会。</u>\n\n-**be accustomed to**：<u>习惯于。</u>\n-**well accustomed**：<u>非常熟悉、很习惯。</u>\n-**watersheds**：<u>流域、集水区。</u>\n-**opportunities for recreation**：<u>休闲娱乐机会，如徒步、露营等。</u>\n\n---\n\nOnly recently have they <font color=\"#ffff00\">come to see</font> the vital part forests will have to play in storing carbon.\n翻译: <u>直到最近，它们才开始认识到森林在储存碳方面将不得不发挥的关键作用。</u>\n\n-**come to see**：<u>逐渐认识到、开始明白。</u>\n\n---\n\nCalifornia’s plan, which is expected to <font color=\"#ffff00\">be finalized</font> by the governor next year, should serve as a model.\n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚州的计划预计将于明年由州长最终确定，它应当成为一个范例。</u>\n\n-**be finalized**：<u>被最终确定、完成定稿。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nAmerican farmers have been complaining of labor shortages for several years.\n翻译: <u>美国农民多年来一直在抱怨劳动力短缺。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe complaints are unlikely to stop without an overhaul of immigration rules for farm workers.\n翻译: <u>如果不对农场工人的移民规则进行全面改革，这些抱怨不太可能停止。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCongress has <font color=\"#ffff00\">obstructed</font> efforts to create a more <font color=\"#ffff00\">straightforward</font> visa for agricultural workers that would let foreign workers stay longer in the U.S. and <font color=\"#ffff00\">change jobs within the industry</font>.\n翻译: <u>国会阻碍了为农业工人制定一种更直接的签证的努力，这种签证将允许外国工人在美国停留更久，并在该行业内部更换工作。</u>\n\n-**obstruct**：<u>阻碍、妨碍。</u>\n-**straightforward**：<u>简单明了的、不复杂的。</u>\n-**change jobs within the industry**：<u>在该行业内部更换工作。</u>\n\n---\n\nIf this doesn’t change, American businesses, communities, and consumers will be <font color=\"#ffff00\">the losers</font>.\n翻译: <u>如果这种情况不改变，美国企业、社区和消费者都将成为输家。</u>\n\n-**the losers**：<u>不是“失败者”这么简单，而是“利益受损的一方”。</u>\n\n---\n\nPerhaps half of U.S. farm laborers are undocumented immigrants.\n翻译: <u>美国农场劳工中也许有一半是无证移民。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs fewer such workers enter the country, the characteristics of the agricultural workforce are changing.\n翻译: <u>随着进入美国的此类工人减少，农业劳动力的特征正在发生变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nToday’s farm laborers, while still <font color=\"#ffff00\">predominantly</font> born in Mexico, are more likely to be settled rather than migrating and more likely to be married than single.\n翻译: <u>如今的农场劳工虽然仍然主要出生在墨西哥，但他们更可能已经定居而不是迁移流动，也更可能已婚而不是单身。</u>\n\n-**predominantly**：<u>主要地、绝大多数。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey’re also aging.\n翻译: <u>他们也在老龄化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt the start of this century, about one-third of <font color=\"#ffff00\">crop workers</font> were over the age of 35.\n翻译: <u>本世纪初，大约三分之一的农作物工人年龄超过35岁。</u>\n\n-**crop workers**：<u>种植业工人、田间作物工人。</u>\n\n---\n\nNow more than half are.\n翻译: <u>现在超过一半的人都是如此。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd picking crops is hard on older bodies.\n翻译: <u>而采摘农作物对年长者的身体来说很吃力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOne <font color=\"#ffff00\">oft-debated</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">cure for</font> this labor shortage remains as <font color=\"#ffff00\">implausible</font> as it’s been <font color=\"#ffff00\">all along</font>: Native U.S. workers won’t be returning to the farm.\n翻译: <u>对于这种劳动力短缺，一个经常被讨论的解决办法仍然像一直以来那样不现实：美国本土工人不会回到农场。</u>\n\n-**oft-debated**：<u>经常被讨论的。</u>\n-**cure for…**：<u>解决……的方法，字面是“治疗办法”。</u>\n-**implausible**：<u>不可信的、不太可能实现的。</u>\n-**all along**：<u>一直以来、从一开始到现在。</u>\n\n---\n\nMechanization isn’t the answer, <font color=\"#ffff00\">either</font> – <font color=\"#ffff00\">not yet, at least</font>.\n翻译: <u>机械化也不是答案——至少目前还不是。</u>\n\n-**either**：<u>也不；至少目前还不是</u>\n\n---\n\nProduction of corn, cotton, rice, soybeans, and wheat has been largely mechanized, but many high-value, labor-intensive crops, such as strawberries, need labor.\n翻译: <u>玉米、棉花、水稻、大豆和小麦的生产已经基本实现机械化，但许多高价值、劳动密集型作物，如草莓，仍然需要劳动力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven dairy farms, where robots do a small share of milking, have a long way to go before they’re automated.\n翻译: <u>即使是在机器人承担少部分挤奶工作的奶牛场，它们距离自动化也还有很长的路要走。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs a result, farms have grown increasingly reliant on temporary guest workers using the H-2A visa to fill the gaps in the workforce.\n翻译: <u>因此，农场越来越依赖使用H-2A签证的临时客工来填补劳动力缺口。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nStarting around 2012, requests for the visas rose sharply; from 2011 to 2016 the number of visas issued more than doubled.\n翻译: <u>大约从2012年开始，对这类签证的申请急剧增加；从2011年到2016年，签发的签证数量增加了一倍多。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe H-2A visa has no <font color=\"#ffff00\">numerical cap</font>, unlike the H-2B visa for nonagricultural work, which is limited to 66,000 a year.\n翻译: <u>与非农业工作的H-2B签证不同，H-2A签证没有数量上限；H-2B签证每年限额为6.6万份。</u>\n\n-**numerical cap**：<u>数量上限、名额上限。</u>\n\n---\n\nEven so, employers complain they aren’t given all the workers they need.\n翻译: <u>即便如此，雇主仍抱怨他们没有得到所需的全部工人。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe process is <font color=\"#ffff00\">cumbersome</font>, expensive, and unreliable.\n翻译: <u>这一流程繁琐、昂贵且不可靠。</u>\n\n-**cumbersome**：<u>繁琐笨重的、手续复杂的。</u>\n\n---\n\nOne survey found that <font color=\"#ffff00\">bureaucratic</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">delays</font> led the average H-2A worker to arrive on the job 22 days late.\n翻译: <u>一项调查发现，官僚程序造成的延误使普通H-2A工人到岗平均晚了22天。</u>\n\n-**bureaucratic**：<u>官僚机构的、行政手续造成的。</u>\n-**delays**：<u>延误。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe shortage is <font color=\"#ffff00\">compounded</font> by <font color=\"#ffff00\">federal immigration raids</font>, which remove some workers and drive others underground.\n翻译: <u>联邦移民执法部门的突击搜查/抓捕行动使劳动力短缺进一步加剧，这些行动驱逐了一些工人，并迫使另一些工人转入地下。</u>\n\n-**compound 作动词**：<u>使恶化、使问题更加严重。</u>\n-**federal immigration raids**：<u>联邦移民执法部门的突击搜查/抓捕行动。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a 2012 survey, 71 percent of tree-fruit growers and almost 80 percent of raisin and <font color=\"#ffff00\">berry growers</font> said they were short of labor.\n翻译: <u>在2012年的一项调查中，71%的树果种植者以及近80%的葡萄干和浆果种植者表示他们缺少劳动力。</u>\n\n-**raisin growers**：<u>葡萄干原料葡萄的种植者。</u>\n-**berry growers**：<u>浆果种植者。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome western farmers have <font color=\"#ffff00\">responded</font> by moving operations to Mexico.\n翻译: <u>一些西部农民的应对方式是把经营活动转移到墨西哥。</u>\n\n-**respond**：<u>应对、采取反应。</u>\n-**move operations to…**：<u>把业务搬到……。</u>\n\n---\n\nFrom 1998 to 2000, 14.5 percent of the fruit Americans consumed was imported.\n翻译: <u>从1998年到2000年，美国人消费的水果中有14.5%是进口的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Little more than</font> a decade later, the share of imports was 25.8 percent.\n翻译: <u>仅仅十多年后，进口所占比例为25.8%。</u>\n\n-**little more than…**：<u>仅仅略多于……。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">In effect</font>, the U.S. can import food or it can import the workers who pick it.\n翻译: <u>实际上，美国可以进口食物，也可以进口采摘这些食物的工人。</u>\n\n-**in effect**：<u>实际上、事实上、从结果来看。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nArnold Schwarzenegger, Dia Mirza and Adrian Grenier have a message for you: It’s easy to beat plastic.\n翻译: <u>阿诺德·施瓦辛格、迪娅·米尔扎和阿德里安·格雷尼尔有一条信息要告诉你：战胜塑料很容易。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey’re part of a bunch of celebrities starring in a new video for World Environment Day – encouraging you, the consumer, to swap out your single-use plastic staples like straws and cutlery to combat the plastics crisis.\n翻译: <u>他们是一群名人中的一员，这些名人出演了为世界环境日制作的一段新视频，鼓励你作为消费者，将吸管和餐具等一次性塑料日用品替换掉，以应对塑料危机。</u>\n\n-**swap out A**：<u>更换、替换 A。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe key messages that <font color=\"#ffff00\">have been put together</font> for World Environment Day do include a call for governments to enact legislation to curb single-use plastics.\n翻译: <u>为世界环境日整合出的关键信息确实包括呼吁各国政府制定法律，以限制一次性塑料。</u>\n\n-**have been put together**：<u>被组织、整理、汇总起来。</u>\n-**do**：<u>加入 do 后强调；的确、确实包括</u>\n\n---\n\nBut the <font color=\"#ffff00\">overarching</font> message is directed at individuals.\n翻译: <u>但其总体信息是面向个人的。</u>\n\n-**overarching**：<u>总括性的、最主要的、统领全局的；这里指整个宣传活动最突出的主旨</u>\n-**direct a message at sb.**：<u>把信息传达给某人、以某人为对象。</u>\n\n---\n\nMy concern with leaving it up to the individual, however, is our <font color=\"#ffff00\">limited sense of</font> what needs to be achieved.\n翻译: <u>然而，我对把这件事交给个人来处理的担忧在于，我们对需要实现什么的认识是有限的。</u>\n\n-**limited sense of…**：<u>对……有限的认识、理解不足。</u>\n\n---\n\nOn their own, taking our own bags to the grocery store or quitting plastic straws, for example, will accomplish little and require very little of us.\n翻译: <u>单独来看，例如，带上我们自己的袋子去杂货店购物，或是不再使用塑料吸管，所能成就的事情很少，而且对我们的要求也很低。</u>\n\n-**on one’s own**：<u>单独地、独立地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey could even be detrimental, satisfying a need to have “done our bit” without ever <font color=\"#ffff00\">progressing onto</font> bigger, bolder, more effective actions – a kind of “moral licensing” that allays our concerns and stops us doing more and asking more of <font color=\"#ffff00\">those in charge</font>.\n翻译: <u>它们甚至可能是有害的，因为它们满足了我们已经“尽了自己一份力”的需要，却从未推进到更大、更大胆、更有效的行动上去；这是一种“道德许可”，它缓解了我们的担忧，并阻止我们做得更多，也阻止我们向掌权者要求更多。</u>\n\n-**progress onto…**：<u>进一步发展到……。</u>\n-**those in charge**：<u>掌权者、负责决策的人，如政府官员和企业负责人。</u>\n\n---\n\nWhile the conversation around our environment and our responsibility toward it <font color=\"#ffff00\">remains centered on</font> shopping bags and straws, we’re ignoring the balance of power that implies that as “consumers” we must shop sustainably, rather than as “citizens” hold our governments and industries to account to push for real systemic change.\n翻译: <u>当围绕环境以及我们对环境责任的讨论仍然集中在购物袋和吸管上时，我们正在忽视一种权力平衡：这种平衡暗示，作为“消费者”，我们必须以可持续的方式购物，而不是作为“公民”去追究政府和行业的责任，推动真正的系统性变革。</u>\n\n-**remain centered on…**：<u>仍然以……为中心。</u>\n-**hold sb. to account**：<u>要求某人负责、追究某人的责任。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s important to acknowledge that the environment isn’t everyone’s priority – <font color=\"#ffff00\">or even most people’s</font>.\n翻译: <u>重要的是要承认，环境并不是每个人的优先事项，甚至也不是大多数人的优先事项。</u>\n\n-**or even most people’s priority**：<u>甚至也不是大多数人的优先事项。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe shouldn’t expect it to be.\n翻译: <u>我们不应该期待它会是。</u>\n\n-**collectively change**：<u>从集体层面改变。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn her latest book, Why Good People Do Bad Environmental Things, Wellesley College professor Elizabeth R.\n翻译: <u>在她的最新著作《为什么好人会做对环境有害的事》中，韦尔斯利学院教授 Elizabeth R.</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDeSombre argues that the best way to collectively change the behavior of large numbers of people is for the change to be structural.\n翻译: <u>DeSombre 认为，集体改变大量人群行为的最佳方式，是让这种改变成为结构性的改变。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis might mean implementing policy such as a plastic tax that adds a cost to environmentally problematic action, or banning single-use plastics <font color=\"#ffff00\">altogether</font>.\n翻译: <u>这可能意味着实施某种政策，例如征收塑料税，使对环境有问题的行为增加成本，或者完全禁止一次性塑料制品。</u>\n\n-**altogether**：<u>完全地、彻底地。</u>\n\n---\n\nIndia has just announced it will “eliminate all single-use plastic in the country by 2022.”\n翻译: <u>印度刚刚宣布，到2022年将“消除全国所有一次性塑料制品”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere are also <font color=\"#ffff00\">incentive-based</font> ways of making better environmental choices easier, such as ensuring recycling is at least as easy as trash disposal.\n翻译: <u>也有一些以激励为基础的方法，使更好的环境选择变得更容易，例如确保回收至少和垃圾处理一样方便。</u>\n\n-**incentive-based**：<u>以激励为基础的。</u>\n\n---\n\nDeSombre isn’t saying people should stop caring about the environment.\n翻译: <u>DeSombre 并不是说人们应该停止关心环境。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt’s just that individual actions are <font color=\"#ffff00\">too slow</font>, she says, <font color=\"#ffff00\">for that to be</font> the only, or even <font color=\"#ffff00\">primary</font>, approach to changing widespread behavior.\n翻译: <u>她说，只是个人行动太慢了，不能把它作为改变广泛行为的唯一方法，甚至主要方法。</u>\n\n-**too + 形容词 + for sb./sth. to do**：<u>表示“太……以至于某人/某物不能……”。</u>\n-**primary approach**：<u>主要方法。</u>\n\n---\n\nNone of this is about writing off the individual.\n翻译: <u>这一切都不是在否定个人。</u>\n\n-**write off**：<u>认为……没有价值、放弃、不再考虑。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s just about putting things into perspective.\n翻译: <u>这只是为了把事情放到恰当的视角中来看。</u>\n\n-**put something into perspective**：<u>客观、全面、按适当比例看待某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe don’t have time to wait.\n翻译: <u>我们没有时间等待。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe need progressive policies that shape collective action (and rein in polluting businesses), alongside engaged citizens pushing for change.\n翻译: <u>我们需要能够塑造集体行动（并约束污染企业）的进步政策，同时也需要积极参与的公民推动变革。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2020","year":"2020","title":"2020 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2020 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2020 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nRats and other animals need to be highly attuned to social signals from others so they can <font color=\"#ffff00\">identify</font> friends to cooperate with and enemies to avoid.\n翻译: <u>老鼠和其他动物需要高度敏锐地感知来自其他个体的社会信号，以便识别可以合作的朋友和需要避开的敌人。</u>\n\n-**be attuned to…**：<u>对……敏感，能够准确察觉……。</u>\n-**identify**：<u>识别、判断出。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo find out if this <font color=\"#ffff00\">extends to</font> non-living beings, Laleh Quinn at the University of California, San Diego, and her colleagues tested whether rats can detect social signals from robotic rats.\n翻译: <u>为了弄清这种能力是否延伸到非生命体身上，加利福尼亚大学圣迭戈分校的 Laleh Quinn 及其同事测试了老鼠是否能够探测到来自机器老鼠的社会信号。</u>\n\n-**extend to…**：<u>延伸到……、适用于……。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey housed eight adult rats with two types of robotic rat—one social and one asocial—for four days.\n翻译: <u>他们把八只成年老鼠与两种机器老鼠共同饲养了四天，一种具有社交性，另一种不具有社交性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe robot rats were quite <font color=\"#ffff00\">minimalist</font>, resembling <font color=\"#ffff00\">a chunkier version of</font> a computer mouse with wheels to move around and colourful markings.\n翻译: <u>这些机器老鼠相当简约，看起来像一个更笨重版本的电脑鼠标，带有用于四处移动的轮子和彩色标记。</u>\n\n-**minimalist**：<u>极简的、设计很简单的。</u>\n-**resemble**：<u>像、与……相似。</u>\n-**a chunkier version of…**：<u>更粗大、更厚实的……版本。</u>\n\n---\n\nDuring the experiment, the social robot rat followed the living rats around, played with the same toys, and opened cage doors to let trapped rats escape.\n翻译: <u>在实验期间，具有社交性的机器老鼠会跟着活老鼠四处移动，玩同样的玩具，并打开笼门让被困的老鼠逃出来。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, the asocial robot simply moved forwards and backwards and side to side.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，不具有社交性的机器老鼠只是前后移动以及左右移动。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNext, the researchers trapped the robots in cages and gave the rats the opportunity to release them by pressing a lever.\n翻译: <u>接下来，研究人员把这些机器人困在笼子里，并给老鼠机会通过按压杠杆来释放它们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAcross 18 trials each, the living rats were 52 per cent more likely on average to set the social robot free than the asocial one.\n翻译: <u>在每只老鼠各进行的18次试验中，活老鼠释放具有社交性的机器老鼠的平均可能性比释放不具有社交性的机器老鼠高52%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis suggests that the rats perceived the social robot as a genuine social being, says Quinn.\n翻译: <u>Quinn 说，这表明老鼠把具有社交性的机器老鼠感知为一个真正的社会性存在。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe rats may have bonded more with the social robot because it displayed behaviors like <font color=\"#ffff00\">communal</font> exploring and playing.\n翻译: <u>老鼠可能与具有社交性的机器老鼠建立了更强的联系，因为它表现出了共同探索和玩耍等行为。</u>\n\n-**communal**：<u>共同进行的、群体性的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThis could lead to the rats better remembering having freed it earlier, and wanting the robot to <font color=\"#ffff00\">return the favour</font> when they get trapped, she says .\n翻译: <u>她说，这可能使老鼠更好地记住自己此前曾释放过它，并希望当自己被困时，机器人能回报这一帮助。</u>\n\n-**return the favour**：<u>回报帮助、投桃报李。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Rats have been shown to engage in multiple forms of reciprocal help and cooperation, including what is referred to as <font color=\"#ffff00\">direct reciprocity</font> where a rat will help another rat that has previously helped them,” says Quinn.\n翻译: <u>Quinn 说：“已有研究表明，老鼠会参与多种形式的互惠帮助与合作，包括所谓的直接互惠，即一只老鼠会帮助另一只此前帮助过它的老鼠。”</u>\n\n-**direct reciprocity**：<u>直接互惠，即“你帮助过我，我之后也帮助你”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe readiness of the rats to <font color=\"#ffff00\">befriend</font> the social robot was surprising <font color=\"#ffff00\">given its minimal design</font>.\n翻译: <u>鉴于这种社交机器人的设计十分简约，老鼠愿意与它建立友好关系这一点令人惊讶。</u>\n\n-**readiness to do**：<u>愿意做某事、准备好做某事。</u>\n-**befriend**：<u>与……交朋友、对……表示友好。</u>\n-**given + 名词短语**：<u>考虑到、鉴于。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe robot was the same size as a regular rat but resembled a simple plastic box on wheels.\n翻译: <u>这个机器人和普通老鼠大小相同，但看起来像一个装在轮子上的简单塑料盒。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“<font color=\"#ffff00\">We’d</font> assumed <font color=\"#ffff00\">we’d</font> have to give it a moving head and tail, facial features, and put a scent on it to make it smell like a real rat, but that wasn’t necessary,”says Janet Wiles at the University of Queensland in Australia, who helped with the research.\n翻译: <u>澳大利亚昆士兰大学的 Janet Wiles 参与了这项研究，她说：“我们原本以为，必须给它装上会动的头和尾巴、面部特征，并给它加上气味，让它闻起来像一只真正的老鼠，但这些都不是必要的。”</u>\n\n-**We’d**：<u>第一个 We’d = We had。</u>\n-**we’d**：<u>第二个 we’d = we would。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe finding shows how sensitive rats are to social cues, even when they come from <font color=\"#ffff00\">basic robots</font>. says Wiles.\n翻译: <u>Wiles 说，这一发现显示出老鼠对社会线索有多么敏感，即使这些线索来自基本的机器人。</u>\n\n-**basic robots**：<u>结构简单的机器人。</u>\n\n---\n\nSimilarly, children tend to treat robots as if they are fellow beings, even when they display only simple social signals.\n翻译: <u>类似地，儿童往往会把机器人当作同类来对待，即使它们只表现出简单的社会信号。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We humans seem to be fascinated by robots, and it turns out other animals are too,” says Wiles.\n翻译: <u>Wiles 说：“我们人类似乎对机器人着迷，事实证明，其他动物也是如此。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nIt is true that <font color=\"#ffff00\">CEO pay</font> has gone up—top ones may make 300 times the pay of typical workers on average, and since the mid-1970s, CEO pay for large <font color=\"#ffff00\">publicly traded</font> American corporations has, by <font color=\"#ffff00\">varying estimates</font>, gone up by about 500%.\n翻译: <u>首席执行官的薪酬确实已经上涨了：顶级首席执行官的薪酬平均可能达到普通员工的300倍；而且自20世纪70年代中期以来，据不同估算，美国大型上市公司的首席执行官薪酬已经上涨了约500%。</u>\n\n-**CEO pay**：<u>首席执行官的薪酬。</u>\n-**publicly traded**：<u>公开上市交易的。</u>\n-**varying estimates**：<u>不同的估算结果。</u>\n-**go up by 500%**：<u>上涨 500%。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe typical CEO of a top American corporation now makes about $18.9 million a year.\n翻译: <u>如今，美国顶级公司中典型首席执行官的年收入约为1890万美元。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe best <font color=\"#ffff00\">model</font> for understanding the growth of CEO pay is that of limited CEO talent in a world where business opportunities for the top firms are growing rapidly.\n翻译: <u>理解首席执行官薪酬增长的最佳模型是：在一个顶级公司商业机会迅速增长的世界中，首席执行官人才是有限的。</u>\n\n-**model**：<u>解释模型、理解框架。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe efforts of America’ s highest-earning 1% have been one of the more dynamic elements of the global economy.\n翻译: <u>美国收入最高的1%人群的努力，一直是全球经济中较有活力的因素之一。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt’s not <font color=\"#ffff00\">popular</font> to say. but one reason their pay has gone up so much is that CEOs really have upped their game relative to many other workers in the U.S. economy.\n翻译: <u>这样说并不受欢迎，但他们薪酬上涨如此之多的一个原因是，相对于美国经济中的许多其他劳动者，首席执行官确实提升了自己的能力水平。</u>\n\n-**popular**：<u>在这里是“受欢迎、容易被人接受”。</u>\n-**up one’s game**：<u>提高竞争水平、改善表现、增强能力。</u>\n\n---\n\nToday’ s CEO, at least for major American firms, must have many more skills than simply being able to “run the company.”\n翻译: <u>如今的首席执行官，至少对美国大公司而言，必须具备的技能远不止能够“经营公司”这么简单。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCEOs must <font color=\"#ffff00\">have a good sense of</font> financial markets and maybe even how the company should <font color=\"#ffff00\">trade in them</font> .\n翻译: <u>首席执行官必须对金融市场有良好的判断，甚至可能还要了解公司应如何在这些市场中进行交易。</u>\n\n-**have a good sense of…**：<u>对……有良好的感觉、判断力或理解。</u>\n-**trade in them**：<u>在这些金融市场中进行交易。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey also need better public relations skills than their predecessors, as the costs of even a minor slipup can be significant.\n翻译: <u>他们还需要比前任更好的公共关系技能，因为即使是一个小失误，其代价也可能十分重大。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Then</font> there’s the fact that large American companies are much more globalized than ever before, with supply chains spread across a larger number of countries.\n翻译: <u>此外，还有这样一个事实：美国大公司比以往任何时候都更加全球化，其供应链分布在更多国家。</u>\n\n-**Then**：<u>在这里表示继续列举：“再者、此外”。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo lead in that system requires knowledge that is <font color=\"#ffff00\">fairly</font> mind-boggling.\n翻译: <u>要在那样的体系中发挥领导作用，需要掌握相当令人难以置信的知识。</u>\n\n-**fairly**：<u>相当、颇为。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Plus</font>, virtually all major American companies are becoming tech companies, <font color=\"#ffff00\">one way or another</font>.\n翻译: <u>另外，几乎所有美国大公司都正以这样或那样的方式变成科技公司。</u>\n\n-**Plus**：<u>在这里比较口语化，相当于 Moreover / In addition。</u>\n-**one way or another**：<u>以某种方式、这样或那样。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Beyond this</font>, major CEOs still have to do all the <font color=\"#ffff00\">day-to-day work</font> they have always done.\n翻译: <u>除此之外，大公司的首席执行官仍然必须完成他们一直以来都要做的所有日常工作。</u>\n\n-**day-to-day work**：<u>日常工作、日常管理事务。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The common idea</font> that high CEO pay is mainly about ripping people off doesn’t explain history very well.\n翻译: <u>认为高额首席执行官薪酬主要是通过剥削他人获利的普遍看法，并不能很好地解释历史。</u>\n\n-**rip someone off**：<u>宰某人、欺骗某人、从某人那里不公平地获取钱财。</u>\n\n---\n\nBy <font color=\"#ffff00\">most measures</font>, corporate governance has become a lot tighter and more <font color=\"#ffff00\">rigorous</font> since the 1970s.\n翻译: <u>按大多数衡量标准来看，自20世纪70年代以来，公司治理已经变得严格和严谨得多。</u>\n\n-**most measures**：<u>大多数指标、判断标准。</u>\n-**rigorous**：<u>严谨的、严格的。</u>\n\n---\n\nYet it is principally during this period of stronger governance that CEO pay has been high and rising.\n翻译: <u>然而，主要正是在这一治理更强的时期，首席执行官薪酬一直很高并且还在上升。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat suggests it is in the broader corporate interest to recruit top candidates for increasingly tough jobs.\n翻译: <u>这表明，招聘顶尖候选人来担任日益艰难的职位，符合更广泛的公司利益。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFurthermore, the highest CEO salaries are paid to outside candidates, not to the cozy insider picks, another sign that high CEO pay is not some kind of depredation at the expense of <font color=\"#ffff00\">the rest of the company</font>.\n翻译: <u>此外，最高的首席执行官薪水支付给的是外部候选人，而不是那些关系密切的内部人选；这也是一个迹象，说明高额首席执行官薪酬并不是某种以公司其他人为代价的掠夺。</u>\n\n-**the rest of the company**：<u>公司的其他成员或公司整体。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd the stock market reacts positively when companies tie CEO pay to, <font color=\"#ffff00\">say</font>, stock prices, a sign that <font color=\"#ffff00\">those practices</font> build up corporate value <font color=\"#ffff00\">not just for the CEO</font>.\n翻译: <u>而且，当公司把首席执行官薪酬与例如股价挂钩时，股票市场会作出积极反应，这表明这些做法不仅为首席执行官，也为公司积累价值。</u>\n\n-**say**：<u>在这里不是谓语“说”，而是 for example，即“比如”。</u>\n-**those practices**：<u>把 CEO 薪酬与股价等业绩指标挂钩的做法。</u>\n-**not just for the CEO**：<u>并非只让 CEO 受益。</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nMadrid was hailed as a public health beacon last November when it <font color=\"#ffff00\">rolled out</font> ambitious restrictions on the most polluting cars.\n翻译: <u>去年11月，马德里推出了针对污染最严重车辆的雄心勃勃的限制措施，因此被誉为公共健康的灯塔。</u>\n\n-**hail A as B**：<u>称赞 A 是 B、将 A 誉为 B。</u>\n-**roll out**：<u>正式推出、实施某项计划或政策。</u>\n\n---\n\nSeven months and <font color=\"#ffff00\">one election day later</font>, a new <font color=\"#ffff00\">conservative</font> city council suspended <font color=\"#ffff00\">enforcement</font> of the clean air zone, a first step toward its possible <font color=\"#ffff00\">demise</font>.\n翻译: <u>七个月后，在一次选举日之后，一个新的保守派市议会暂停了清洁空气区的执法，这是该区域可能走向终结的第一步。</u>\n\n-**one election day later**：<u>强调一次选举改变了政治局面。</u>\n-**conservative**：<u>保守派的。</u>\n-**enforcement**：<u>执行、执法。</u>\n-**demise**：<u>终结、消亡。</u>\n\n---\n\nMayor José Luis Martinez-Almeida made <font color=\"#ffff00\">opposition to</font> the zone a <font color=\"#ffff00\">centrepiece</font> of his election campaign, despite its success in improving air quality.\n翻译: <u>尽管该区域在改善空气质量方面取得了成功，市长 José Luis Martinez-Almeida 仍把反对该区域作为其竞选活动的核心内容。</u>\n\n-**opposition to…**：<u>对……的反对。</u>\n-**centrepiece**：<u>核心、中心议题、最重要的组成部分。</u>\n-**make A B**：<u>把 A 变成/作为 B；宾语 + 宾语补足语结构。</u>\n\n---\n\nA judge has now <font color=\"#ffff00\">overruled</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">the city’s decision</font> to stop <font color=\"#ffff00\">levying fines</font>, ordering <font color=\"#ffff00\">them</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">reinstated</font>.\n翻译: <u>一名法官现在已经推翻了该市停止征收罚款的决定，命令恢复罚款。</u>\n\n-**overrule**：<u>推翻、否决，常用于法院推翻某个决定。</u>\n-**the city’s decision**：<u>市政府作出的决定。</u>\n-**levy fines**：<u>征收罚款、处以罚款。</u>\n-**them**：<u>指 fines。</u>\n-**reinstate**：<u>them 指 fines。reinstate：恢复、重新实施。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">with legal battles ahead</font>, the zone’s future looks uncertain <font color=\"#ffff00\">at best</font>.\n翻译: <u>但由于未来还会有法律斗争，该区域的前景充其量也显得不确定。</u>\n\n-**ahead**：<u>在前方、接下来。</u>\n-**with legal battles ahead**：<u>可以理解为；由于接下来还会有法律争斗</u>\n-**at best**：<u>充其量、往最好处说；它暗示现实情况可能比“uncertain”更糟，甚至可能被彻底取消</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Among other</font> weaknesses, the measures cities must employ when left to tackle dirty air on their own are politically contentious, and therefore <font color=\"#ffff00\">vulnerable</font>.\n翻译: <u>在其他弱点之外，当城市被迫独自应对污浊空气时，它们必须采用的措施在政治上具有争议性，因此也很脆弱。</u>\n\n-**among other…**：<u>除了其他……之外、其中一个……。</u>\n-**leave someone to do…**：<u>让某人独自做……。</u>\n-**vulnerable**：<u>脆弱的、容易受到攻击或破坏的。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat’s because they inevitably put the costs of cleaning the air on to individual drivers—who must pay fees or buy better vehicles—rather than on to the car manufacturers <font color=\"#ffff00\">whose cheating</font> is the real cause of our toxic pollution.\n翻译: <u>这是因为，这些措施不可避免地把清洁空气的成本转嫁给个体司机，也就是那些必须支付费用或购买更好车辆的人，而不是转嫁给汽车制造商；这些制造商的作弊行为才是我们有毒污染的真正原因。</u>\n\n-**whose cheating**：<u>这些制造商的欺骗行为。</u>\n\n---\n\nIt’s not hard to imagine a similar <font color=\"#ffff00\">reversal</font> happening in London.\n翻译: <u>不难想象类似的逆转会发生在伦敦。</u>\n\n-**reversal**：<u>逆转、政策转向。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe new ultra-low emission zone (Ulez) is likely to be <font color=\"#ffff00\">a big issue</font> in next year's <font color=\"#ffff00\">mayoral election</font>.\n翻译: <u>新的超低排放区（Ulez）很可能会成为明年市长选举中的一个重大议题。</u>\n\n-**a big issue**：<u>重要议题、争议焦点。</u>\n-**mayoral election**：<u>市长选举。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd if Sadiq Khan wins and extends it to the North and South Circular roads in 2021 as he intends, it is sure to spark <font color=\"#ffff00\">intense opposition</font> from the far larger number of <font color=\"#ffff00\">motorists</font> who will then be affected.\n翻译: <u>而且，如果 Sadiq Khan 获胜，并按其计划在2021年把该区域扩展到北环路和南环路，那么它必定会引发更多届时将受到影响的驾车者的强烈反对。</u>\n\n-**intense opposition**：<u>强烈反对。</u>\n-**motorists**：<u>司机、驾车者。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">It's not that</font> measures such as London’s Ulez are useless.\n翻译: <u>这并不是说像伦敦超低排放区这样的措施毫无用处。</u>\n\n-**It’s not that A**：<u>并不是说 A。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Far from it</font>.\n翻译: <u>远非如此。</u>\n\n-**Far from it**：<u>远非如此，恰恰相反。</u>\n\n---\n\nLocal officials are using the <font color=\"#ffff00\">levers</font> that are available to them to safeguard residents’ health in the face of a serious threat.\n翻译: <u>面对严重威胁，地方官员正在利用他们可以使用的手段来保护居民健康。</u>\n\n-**levers**：<u>本义是“杠杆”，这里比喻“可运用的政策手段或权力工具”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe zones do deliver some improvements to air quality, and the science tells us that means real health benefits—fewer heart attacks, strokes and premature births, less cancer, dementia and asthma.\n翻译: <u>这些区域确实能在一定程度上改善空气质量，而科学告诉我们，这意味着真实的健康益处：心脏病发作、中风和早产减少，癌症、痴呆症和哮喘减少。</u>\n\n-**deliver improvements**：<u>带来改善。</u>\n\n---\n\nFewer <font color=\"#ffff00\">untimely deaths</font>.\n翻译: <u>过早死亡也会减少。</u>\n\n-**untimely deaths**：<u>过早死亡、非正常提前死亡。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut mayors and councilors <font color=\"#ffff00\">can only do so much</font> about a problem that is far bigger than any one city or town.\n翻译: <u>但是，对于一个远远大于任何单个城市或城镇的问题，市长和议员们能做的只有这么多。</u>\n\n-**can only do so much**：<u>是固定表达；能做的只有这么多；能力有限</u>\n\n---\n\nThey are acting because national governments—Britain’s and others across Europe—have failed to do so.\n翻译: <u>他们之所以采取行动，是因为国家政府，包括英国政府以及欧洲其他国家的政府，未能这样做。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRestrictions that keep highly polluting cars out of certain areas—city centres, “school streets”, <font color=\"#ffff00\">even individual roads</font>—are a response to the absence of a larger effort to properly enforce existing regulations and require auto companies to bring their vehicles into compliance.\n翻译: <u>将高污染车辆挡在某些区域之外的限制措施，例如市中心、“学校街道”，甚至单条道路，是对缺乏更大力度行动的一种回应；这种更大力度的行动本应恰当地执行现有法规，并要求汽车公司使其车辆符合规定。</u>\n\n-**even individual roads**：<u>甚至单独某一条路。</u>\n-**bring A into compliance**：<u>使 A 符合规定。</u>\n\n---\n\nWales has <font color=\"#ffff00\">introduced</font> special low speed limits to minimise pollution.\n翻译: <u>威尔士已经引入了特殊的低速限速措施，以尽量减少污染。</u>\n\n-**introduce**：<u>推出、实施。</u>\n\n---\n\nWe’re <font color=\"#ffff00\">doing everything but insist</font> that manufacturers clean up their cars.\n翻译: <u>我们什么都在做，就是没有坚持要求制造商清理他们的汽车。</u>\n\n-**do everything but do something**：<u>什么都做了，唯独没有做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nNow that members of Generation Z are graduating college this spring—the most commonly-accepted definition says this generation was born after 1995, give or take a year—the attention has been rising steadily in recent weeks.\n翻译: <u>随着Z世代成员今年春天大学毕业——最普遍接受的定义认为这一代人出生于1995年之后，前后相差一年左右——最近几周，对他们的关注一直在稳步上升。</u>\n\n-**give or take + 数量**：<u>上下相差……、出入……左右。</u>\n\n---\n\nGen Zs are about to hit the streets looking for work in a labor market that’s tighter than it's been in decades.\n翻译: <u>Z世代即将走上街头，在一个几十年来最为紧俏的劳动力市场中寻找工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd employers are planning on hiring about 17 percent more new graduates for jobs in the U.S. this year than last, according to a survey conducted by the National Association of Colleges and Employers.\n翻译: <u>根据全国大学与雇主协会进行的一项调查，雇主计划今年在美国招聘的新毕业生人数比去年多约17%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEverybody wants to know how the people who will soon <font color=\"#ffff00\">inhabit</font> those empty office cubicles will differ from those who came before them.\n翻译: <u>每个人都想知道，那些很快将坐进空置办公室隔间的人，会与他们之前的人有何不同。</u>\n\n-**inhabit**：<u>原意是“居住于”，这里幽默地表示；坐进、占据办公隔间，在办公室工作</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">If</font> “<font color=\"#ffff00\">entitled</font>” is the most common adjective, fairly or not, applied to millennials (those born between 1981 and 1995), the <font color=\"#ffff00\">catchwords</font> for Generation Z are practical and cautious.\n翻译: <u>如果说“自以为应得的”是不管公平与否最常被用来形容千禧一代（1981年至1995年之间出生的人）的形容词，那么Z世代的关键词就是务实和谨慎。</u>\n\n-**if**：<u>这里的 if 接近；如果说……的话 / 要说……；而是引出对两个世代标签的比较</u>\n-**entitled**：<u>这里的 entitled 不是普通的“有权享有”，而是带贬义；觉得别人理所当然应该满足自己；自认为应该得到特殊待遇</u>\n-**apply a word/adjective to someone**：<u>用某个词形容某人。</u>\n-**catchwords**：<u>代表性词语、常用标签、关键词。</u>\n\n---\n\nAccording to the career counselors and experts who study them, Generation Zs are clear-eyed, <font color=\"#ffff00\">economic pragmatists</font>.\n翻译: <u>根据研究他们的职业顾问和专家的说法，Z世代是头脑清醒的经济务实主义者。</u>\n\n-**economic pragmatists**：<u>在经济问题上重视现实利益的人。</u>\n\n---\n\nDespite graduating into the best economy in the past 50 years, Gen Zs know what an economic train wreck looks like.\n翻译: <u>尽管毕业时面对的是过去50年来最好的经济环境，Z世代却知道经济灾难是什么样子。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey were <font color=\"#ffff00\">impressionable</font> kids during the crash of 2008, when many of their parents lost their jobs or their <font color=\"#ffff00\">life savings</font> or both.\n翻译: <u>2008年经济崩溃时，他们还是容易受影响的孩子，当时他们的许多父母失去了工作、毕生积蓄，或者两者都失去了。</u>\n\n-**impressionable**：<u>容易受到影响的、容易被经历塑造的。</u>\n-**life savings**：<u>毕生积蓄。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey aren't interested in taking any chances.\n翻译: <u>他们对冒任何风险都不感兴趣。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe booming economy seems to have done little to assuage this underlying generational sense of anxious urgency, especially for those who have college debt.\n翻译: <u>繁荣的经济似乎几乎没有缓解这一代人内在的焦虑紧迫感，尤其是对那些背负大学债务的人而言。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCollege loan balances in the U.S. now <font color=\"#ffff00\">stand at</font> a record $1.5 trillion, according to <font color=\"#ffff00\">the Federal Reserve</font>.\n翻译: <u>根据美联储的数据，美国的大学贷款余额目前已达到创纪录的1.5万亿美元。</u>\n\n-**stand at**：<u>达到、处于某一数字。</u>\n-**the Federal Reserve**：<u>美联储。</u>\n\n---\n\nOne survey from Accenture found that 88 percent of <font color=\"#ffff00\">graduating seniors</font> this year chose their major with a job in mind.\n翻译: <u>埃森哲的一项调查发现，今年88%的毕业班学生在选择专业时心里想着就业。</u>\n\n-**graduating seniors**：<u>即将毕业的大四学生。</u>\n-**with something in mind**：<u>心里考虑着某事、以某事为考虑目标。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a 2019 survey of University of Georgia students, meanwhile, the career office found the most desirable trait in a future employer was the ability to offer <font color=\"#ffff00\">secure employment</font> (<font color=\"#ffff00\">followed by</font> professional development and training, and then inspiring purpose).\n翻译: <u>与此同时，在2019年对佐治亚大学学生的一项调查中，职业办公室发现，未来雇主最令人向往的特质是能够提供稳定就业（其次是职业发展和培训，再然后是鼓舞人心的使命）。</u>\n\n-**secure employment**：<u>有保障的工作、稳定就业。</u>\n-**secure**：<u>这里的 secure 不是“安全防护”，而是“不容易失去的、稳定的”。</u>\n-**followed by…**：<u>接下来是……。</u>\n\n---\n\nJob security or stability was the second most important career goal(work-life balance was number one), followed by a sense of being dedicated to a cause or to feel good about serving <font color=\"#ffff00\">the greater good</font>.\n翻译: <u>工作保障或稳定性是第二重要的职业目标（工作与生活的平衡位居第一），其后是对某项事业有奉献感，或因服务更大的公共利益而感到良好。</u>\n\n-**be dedicated to a cause**：<u>致力于某项事业。</u>\n-**the greater good**：<u>整体社会利益、公共福祉。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat’s a big change from the previous generation.\n翻译: <u>这与上一代相比是一个很大的变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Millennials wanted more flexibility in their lives,” notes Tanya Michelsen, Associate Director of YouthSight, a UK-based brand manager that conducts regular 60-day surveys of British youth, in findings that <font color=\"#ffff00\">might just as well apply to</font> American youth.\n翻译: <u>“千禧一代希望生活中有更多灵活性，”YouthSight副主任Tanya Michelsen指出。YouthSight是一家总部位于英国的品牌管理机构，定期对英国青年进行为期60天的调查，而这些发现或许同样适用于美国青年。</u>\n\n-**might just as well apply to…**：<u>很可能同样适用于…… / 用在……身上也完全说得通。</u>\n\n---\n\n“Generation Zs are looking for more certainty and stability, because of the rise of the gig economy.\n翻译: <u>“由于零工经济的兴起，Z世代正在寻找更多确定性和稳定性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey have troubles seeing a financial future and they are quite risk averse.”\n翻译: <u>他们难以看清自己的财务未来，而且相当厌恶风险。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2021","year":"2021","title":"2021 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2021 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2021 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\n“Reskilling” is something that sounds like a buzzword but is actually a <font color=\"#ffff00\">requirement</font> if we plan to have a future where a lot of <font color=\"#ffff00\">would-be workers</font> do not get left behind.\n翻译: <u>“再培训”听起来像是一个流行语，但如果我们打算拥有一个许多潜在劳动者不会被落下的未来，它实际上就是一项要求。</u>\n\n-**requirement**：<u>必要条件、必需之事。</u>\n-**would-be workers**：<u>潜在劳动者、本来可以成为劳动者的人。</u>\n-**a would-be writer**：<u>想成为作家的人</u>\n-**a would-be buyer**：<u>潜在买家</u>\n\n---\n\nWe know we are moving into a period where the jobs in demand will <font color=\"#ffff00\">change rapidly</font>, as will the requirements of the jobs that <font color=\"#ffff00\">remain</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们知道，我们正在进入一个时期：需求中的工作将迅速变化，仍然存在的工作的要求也会迅速变化。</u>\n\n-**remain**：<u>继续存在、保留下来。</u>\n\n---\n\nResearch by the World Economic Forum finds that on average 42 per cent of the“core skills”within job roles will change by 2022.\n翻译: <u>世界经济论坛的研究发现，到2022年，工作岗位中平均42%的“核心技能”将发生变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat is a very short timeline.\n翻译: <u>这是一个非常短的时间表。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe question of who should pay for reskilling is a thorny one.\n翻译: <u>谁应该为再培训买单，是一个棘手的问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFor individual companies, the <font color=\"#ffff00\">temptation</font> is always to let go of workers whose skills are no longer in demand and replace them with those whose skills are.\n翻译: <u>对单个公司来说，诱惑总是解雇那些技能不再被需要的员工，并用技能被需要的人取而代之。</u>\n\n-**temptation**：<u>诱惑；很想采取却未必最合理的做法。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat does not always happen.\n翻译: <u>这种情况并不总是发生。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAT&T is often given as the gold standard of a company who decided to do a massive reskilling program rather than <font color=\"#ffff00\">go with</font> a fire-and-hire strategy.\n翻译: <u>AT&T常常被视为一家公司的黄金标准：它决定开展大规模再培训计划，而不是采取解雇再招聘的策略。</u>\n\n-**go with**：<u>选择、采用。</u>\n\n---\n\nOther companies including Amazon and Disney had also pledged to create their own plans.\n翻译: <u>包括亚马逊和迪士尼在内的其他公司也已承诺制定自己的计划。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhen the skills mismatch is in <font color=\"#ffff00\">the broader economy</font> though, the focus usually turns to government to handle.\n翻译: <u>不过，当技能错配存在于更广泛的经济中时，焦点通常会转向政府来处理。</u>\n\n-**the broader economy**：<u>更广泛的经济体系、整个社会经济。</u>\n\n---\n\nEfforts in Canada and elsewhere have been arguably <font color=\"#ffff00\">languid</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">at best</font>, and have <font color=\"#ffff00\">given us a situation</font> where we frequently hear of <font color=\"#ffff00\">employers begging for workers</font>, even at times and in regions <font color=\"#ffff00\">where</font> unemployment is high.\n翻译: <u>加拿大及其他地方的努力可以说充其量也只是进展迟缓，并使我们陷入这样一种局面：我们经常听到雇主苦苦寻找工人，即使在失业率很高的时期和地区也是如此。</u>\n\n-**languid**：<u>无力的、迟缓的、缺乏活力的。</u>\n-**at best**：<u>充其量、往最好处说；整个表达带有明显批评。</u>\n-**give us a situation**：<u>使我们面对一种局面。</u>\n-**employers begging for workers**：<u>雇主苦苦寻找员工、急切求人来工作。</u>\n-**beg for**：<u>字面是“乞求”，这里夸张地表示企业非常缺人。</u>\n-**where**：<u>引导定语从句，修饰 times and regions；在失业率很高的时期和地区。</u>\n\n---\n\nWith the pandemic, unemployment is very high indeed.\n翻译: <u>受疫情影响，失业率确实非常高。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn February,at 3.5 per cent and 5.5 per cent <font color=\"#ffff00\">respectively</font>, unemployment rates in Canada and the United States were at <font color=\"#ffff00\">generational lows</font> and worker shortages were everywhere.\n翻译: <u>2月份，加拿大和美国的失业率分别为3.5%和5.5%，处于一代人以来的低点，劳动力短缺随处可见。</u>\n\n-**respectively**：<u>分别地、依次对应地。</u>\n-**generational lows**：<u>一代人以来的最低水平、数十年来低点。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">As of</font> May, those rates had spiked up to 13.3 per cent and 13.7 per cent,and although many worker shortages had disappeared, not all had done so.\n翻译: <u>截至5月，这些比例已飙升至13.3%和13.7%；尽管许多劳动力短缺已经消失，但并非全部如此。</u>\n\n-**as of**：<u>截至……；从……时起。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the medical field, to take an obvious example, the pandemic meant that there were still clear shortages of doctors, nurses and other medical personnel.\n翻译: <u>以医疗领域这个显而易见的例子来说，疫情意味着医生、护士和其他医务人员仍然明显短缺。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOf course, <font color=\"#ffff00\">it is not like</font> you can take an unemployed waiter and train him to be a doctor in a few weeks, no matter who pays for it.\n翻译: <u>当然，这并不像你可以把一个失业的服务员在几周内培训成医生，不管由谁来出钱。</u>\n\n-**It is not like…**：<u>常用来否定一种不现实的理解；事情并不是你可以……；可不是说……就能……</u>\n\n---\n\nBut <font color=\"#ffff00\">even if</font> you cannot close that gap, maybe you can close <font color=\"#ffff00\">others</font>, and doing so would be to the benefit of <font color=\"#ffff00\">all concerned</font>.\n翻译: <u>但即使你无法弥合那一差距，也许你可以弥合其他差距，而这样做将有利于所有相关方。</u>\n\n-**even if**：<u>引导让步状语从句。</u>\n-**others**：<u>= other gaps。</u>\n-**all concerned**：<u>所有相关人员、所有有关方面。</u>\n-**concerned**：<u>这里 concerned 是后置形容词，意思是“相关的”，不是“担心的”。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat seems to be the case in Sweden: When forced to furlough 90 per cent of their <font color=\"#ffff00\">cabin staff</font>, Scandinavian Airlines decided to start up a short retraining program that reskilled the laid-off workers to support hospital staff.\n翻译: <u>瑞典的情况似乎就是如此：当被迫让90%的客舱员工休假时，斯堪的纳维亚航空公司决定启动一个短期再培训项目，使被裁员工获得新技能，以支持医院工作人员。</u>\n\n-**cabin staff**：<u>客舱乘务人员，包括空乘人员。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe effort was a collective one and involved other companies as well as a Swedish university.\n翻译: <u>这一努力是集体性的，还涉及其他公司以及一所瑞典大学。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nWith the global population predicted to hit close to 10 billion by 2050, and forecasts that agricultural production in some regions will need to nearly double to keep pace, food security is increasingly making headlines.\n翻译: <u>随着全球人口预计到2050年将接近100亿，并且有预测称一些地区的农业生产需要几乎翻倍才能跟上步伐，粮食安全正越来越多地成为新闻头条。</u>\n\n-**make headlines**：<u>成为新闻头条、成为广泛关注的话题。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn the UK, it has become a big talking point recently too, for a <font color=\"#ffff00\">rather</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">particular</font> reason: Brexit.\n翻译: <u>在英国，最近它也成了一个重要谈资，原因相当特殊：英国脱欧。</u>\n\n-**rather**：<u>相当、颇为。</u>\n-**particular**：<u>特殊的、特定的。</u>\n\n---\n\nBrexit is seen by some as an opportunity to reverse a recent trend towards the UK importing food.\n翻译: <u>一些人把英国脱欧视为扭转英国近年来趋向进口食品这一趋势的机会。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe country produces only about 60 per cent of the food it eats, <font color=\"#ffff00\">down from</font> almost <font color=\"#ffff00\">three-quarters</font> in the late 1980s.\n翻译: <u>英国生产的食物只占其消费食物的约60%，低于20世纪80年代末近四分之三的水平。</u>\n\n-**down from…**：<u>从……下降。</u>\n-**three-quarters**：<u>四分之三，即75%。</u>\n\n---\n\nA move back to self-sufficiency ， the argument goes, would boost the farming industry, political sovereignty and even the nation’s health.\n翻译: <u>这种观点认为，回归自给自足将促进农业产业、政治主权，甚至国民健康。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSounds great — but how feasible is this <font color=\"#ffff00\">vision</font>?\n翻译: <u>听起来很棒——但这一愿景有多可行呢？</u>\n\n-**vision**：<u>设想、愿景。</u>\n\n---\n\nAccording to a report on UK food production from the University of Leeds,UK,\n翻译: <u>根据英国利兹大学一份关于英国食品生产的报告，</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n85 per cent of the country’s total land area is associated with meat and dairy production.\n翻译: <u>英国总土地面积的85%与肉类和乳制品生产有关。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat supplies 80 per cent of what is consumed, so <font color=\"#ffff00\">even</font> covering the whole country in livestock farms wouldn’t allow us to cover all our meat and dairy needs.\n翻译: <u>这供应了所消费量的80%，因此即使把整个国家都变成畜牧农场，也无法满足我们所有的肉类和乳制品需求。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere are many caveats to those figures,but they are still <font color=\"#ffff00\">grave</font>.\n翻译: <u>这些数字有许多需要保留说明之处，但它们仍然很严峻。</u>\n\n-**grave**：<u>严重的、严峻的。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo become much more self-sufficient, the UK would need to drastically reduce its consumption of animal foods, and probably also farm more intensively — meaning fewer green fields and more factory-style production.\n翻译: <u>要实现大幅度更高的自给自足，英国将需要大幅减少动物性食品消费，而且很可能还要进行更集约化的农业生产——这意味着更少的绿色田野和更多工厂式生产。</u>\n\n-**farm intensively**：<u>进行集约化农业生产。</u>\n\n---\n\nBut switching to a mainly plant-based diet wouldn’t help.\n翻译: <u>但转向以植物为主的饮食也无济于事。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere is a good reason why the UK is dominated by animal husbandry: most of its terrain doesn’t have the right soil or climate to grow crops on a commercial basis.\n翻译: <u>英国以畜牧业为主导是有充分理由的：其大部分地形并不具备以商业规模种植作物所需的合适土壤或气候。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nJust 25 per cent of the country’s land is suitable for crop-growing, most of which is already occupied by arable fields.\n翻译: <u>英国只有25%的土地适合种植作物，其中大部分已经被耕地占用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven if we converted all the suitable land to fields of fruit and veg — which would involve taking out all the nature reserves and removing thousands of people from their homes — we would achieve only a 30 per cent boost in crop production.\n翻译: <u>即使我们把所有适合的土地都改造成水果和蔬菜田——这将涉及取消所有自然保护区，并让成千上万人离开他们的家园——我们也只能使作物产量提高30%。</u>\n\n-**take out**：<u>在这里不是“拿出去”，而是：取消、拆除、清除。</u>\n\n---\n\nJust 23 per cent of the fruit and vegetables consumed in the UK are currently <font color=\"#ffff00\">home-grown</font>, so even with the most extreme measures we could meet only 30 per cent of our <font color=\"#ffff00\">fresh produce</font> needs.\n翻译: <u>目前，英国消费的水果和蔬菜中只有23%是本土种植的，因此即使采取最极端的措施，我们也只能满足30%的新鲜农产品需求。</u>\n\n-**home-grown**：<u>本国种植的、本土生产的。</u>\n-**fresh produce**：<u>新鲜农产品，通常主要指水果和蔬菜。</u>\n\n---\n\nThat is <font color=\"#ffff00\">before</font> we look for the space to grow the grains, sugars, seeds and oils that provide us with the vast bulk of our current calorie intake.\n翻译: <u>这还没有考虑我们要寻找空间来种植为我们当前热量摄入提供绝大部分来源的谷物、糖类、种子和油料。</u>\n\n-**before**：<u>不是单纯时间上的“在……之前”，而是表示；上面的计算还没算上接下来这个问题；可以翻译为；更不用说……；而且这还没有考虑……</u>\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nWhen Microsoft bought task management app Wunderlist and mobile calendar Sunrise in 2015,it picked two <font color=\"#ffff00\">newcomers</font> that were attracting considerable <font color=\"#ffff00\">buzz</font> in Silicon Valley.\n翻译: <u>2015年，微软收购任务管理应用Wunderlist和移动日历应用Sunrise时，选择的是两家在硅谷引起相当多关注的新兴公司。</u>\n\n-**newcomers**：<u>新来者、新兴企业。</u>\n-**buzz**：<u>热议、关注度、轰动效应。</u>\n\n---\n\nMicrosoft’s own Office dominates the market for “productivity” software, but the start-ups represented a new wave of technology designed from the ground up for the smartphone world.\n翻译: <u>微软自己的Office主导着“生产力”软件市场，但这些初创公司代表了一股从一开始就为智能手机世界设计的新技术浪潮。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBoth apps, however, were later <font color=\"#ffff00\">scrapped</font>, after Microsoft said it had used their best features in its own products.\n翻译: <u>然而，后来这两款应用都被废弃了，此前微软表示，它已经把它们最好的功能用于自己的产品中。</u>\n\n-**scrap**：<u>废弃、取消、停止。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir teams of engineers stayed on,making them two of the many “ acqui-hires”that the biggest companies have used to <font color=\"#ffff00\">feed</font> their great <font color=\"#ffff00\">hunger</font> for tech talent.\n翻译: <u>它们的工程师团队留了下来，使它们成为最大型公司为满足其对科技人才的巨大渴求而使用的众多“收购式雇佣”中的两个例子。</u>\n\n-**feed one’s hunger for…**：<u>满足对……的强烈渴求。</u>\n-**hunger**：<u>饥饿；</u>\n-**feed**：<u>喂养、满足。</u>\n\n---\n\nTo Microsoft’s <font color=\"#ffff00\">critics</font>,the fates of Wunderlist and Sunrise are examples of a <font color=\"#ffff00\">remorseless</font> drive by Big Tech to chew up any innovative companies that lie in their path.\n翻译: <u>在微软的批评者看来，Wunderlist和Sunrise的命运，是大型科技公司无情吞噬任何挡在其道路上的创新公司的例子。</u>\n\n-**critics**：<u>批评者、反对者。</u>\n-**remorseless**：<u>无情的、毫无悔意的、冷酷的。</u>\n\n---\n\n“They bought the seedlings and closed them down,” complained Paul Arnold, a partner at San Francisco-based Switch Ventures, putting an end to businesses that might one day turn into competitors.\n翻译: <u>“他们买下幼苗，然后把它们关停，”总部位于旧金山的Switch Ventures合伙人Paul Arnold抱怨道，称这终结了有朝一日可能变成竞争对手的企业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMicrosoft declined to comment.\n翻译: <u>微软拒绝置评。</u>\n\n-**decline to do**：<u>婉拒、拒绝做某事。</u>\n\n---\n\nLike other start-up investors, Mr. Arnold’s own business often depends on selling start-ups to larger tech companies, though he admits to mixed feelings about the result: “I think these things are good for me, if I put my selfish hat on.\n翻译: <u>和其他初创公司投资者一样，Arnold先生自己的业务往往依赖于把初创公司卖给更大的科技公司，尽管他承认自己对结果感受复杂：“如果我戴上自私的帽子，我认为这些事情对我有利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut are they good for the American economy?\n翻译: <u>但它们对美国经济有利吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nI don’t know.”\n翻译: <u>我不知道。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe US Federal Trade Commission says it wants to find the answer to that question.\n翻译: <u>美国联邦贸易委员会表示，它想找到这个问题的答案。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis week, it asked the five most valuable US tech companies for information about their many small acquisitions over the past decade.\n翻译: <u>本周，它要求美国五家市值最高的科技公司提供有关它们过去十年中许多小型收购的信息。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAlthough only a research project <font color=\"#ffff00\">at this stage</font>, the request has <font color=\"#ffff00\">raised the prospect of</font> regulators wading into early-stage tech markets that until now have been beyond their reach.\n翻译: <u>尽管现阶段这只是一个研究项目，但这一要求已使监管机构介入早期科技市场的可能性上升，而这些市场直到现在一直超出其触及范围。</u>\n\n-**at this stage**：<u>在现阶段。</u>\n-**raise the prospect of…**：<u>使……成为一种可能；让人开始预期……</u>\n\n---\n\nGiven their <font color=\"#ffff00\">combined market value</font> of more than $5.5 trillion, rifling through such small deals—many of them much less prominent than Wunderlist and Sunrise—might seem <font color=\"#ffff00\">beside the point</font>.\n翻译: <u>鉴于它们合计超过5.5万亿美元的市值，翻查这些小型交易——其中许多远不如Wunderlist和Sunrise知名——似乎可能偏离重点。</u>\n\n-**combined market value**：<u>合计市场价值、总市值。</u>\n-**rifle through…**：<u>快速翻查、仔细搜查。</u>\n-**beside the point**：<u>离题的、不重要的、没有触及核心问题的。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Between them</font>, the five biggest tech companies have spent an average of only $3.4 billion a year on <font color=\"#ffff00\">sub</font>- $ 1 billion acquisitions over the past five years—a drop in the ocean compared with their massive financial reserves, and the more than $130 billion of venture capital that was invested in the US last year.\n翻译: <u>在过去五年里，这五大科技公司合计平均每年只在低于10亿美元的收购上花费34亿美元；与它们庞大的财务储备，以及去年在美国投入的超过1300亿美元风险资本相比，这不过是沧海一粟。</u>\n\n-**between them**：<u>这里的 between them 不是“两者之间”，而是：由它们共同计算、合计起来。</u>\n-**sub-**：<u>低于、少于。</u>\n\n---\n\nHowever, critics say the big companies use <font color=\"#ffff00\">such deals</font> to buy their most threatening potential competitors before their businesses have a chance to gain momentum, in some cases as part of a“ buy and kill”tactic to <font color=\"#ffff00\">simply</font> close them down.\n翻译: <u>然而，批评者称，大公司利用这类交易，在那些对它们最具威胁的潜在竞争者的业务有机会发展壮大之前将其买下；在某些情况下，这只是“买下并扼杀”策略的一部分，目的就是将它们关闭。</u>\n\n-**such deals**：<u>这类小规模收购交易。</u>\n-**simply**：<u>直接地、干脆地；也有“唯一目的就是”的意味。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nWe’re fairly good at judging people based on first impressions, thin slices of experience ranging from a glimpse of a photo to five-minute interaction, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">deliberation</font> can be <font color=\"#ffff00\">not only</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">extraneous</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">but</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">intrusive</font>.\n翻译: <u>我们相当善于根据第一印象来判断他人；这些第一印象是很薄的经验片段，从匆匆看一眼照片到五分钟的互动不等，而深思熟虑不仅可能是多余的，还可能会造成干扰。</u>\n\n-**not only A but B**：<u>并列结构。</u>\n-**deliberation**：<u>深思熟虑、刻意分析。</u>\n-**extraneous**：<u>不必要的、与核心任务无关的。</u>\n-**intrusive**：<u>干扰性的、造成妨碍的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn one study of the ability she called“thin slicing,” the <font color=\"#ffff00\">late</font> psychologist Nalini Ambady asked participants to watch silent 10-second video clips of professors and to rate <font color=\"#ffff00\">the instructor’s overall effectiveness</font>.\n翻译: <u>在一项关于她称为“薄片判断”能力的研究中，已故心理学家Nalini Ambady要求参与者观看教授们10秒钟的无声视频片段，并评价这些教师的整体教学效果。</u>\n\n-**the late + 人**：<u>已故的某人。</u>\n-**late**：<u>这里的 late 不是“迟到的”，而是“已故的”。</u>\n-**the instructor’s overall effectiveness**：<u>教师总体上的教学效果。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir ratings correlated strongly with students’ end-of-semester ratings.\n翻译: <u>他们的评分与学生在学期末给出的评分高度相关。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnother set of participants had to <font color=\"#ffff00\">count backward</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">from 1,000 by nines</font> as they watched the clips, occupying their conscious working memory.\n翻译: <u>另一组参与者在观看这些片段时必须从1000开始每次减9倒数，以占用他们有意识的工作记忆。</u>\n\n-**count backward**：<u>倒着数。</u>\n-**from 1,000 by nines**：<u>从1000开始，每次递减9。</u>\n\n---\n\nTheir ratings were <font color=\"#ffff00\">just as accurate</font>, demonstrating the <font color=\"#ffff00\">intuitive nature</font> of the social processing.\n翻译: <u>他们的评分同样准确，这表明这种社会信息处理具有直觉性质。</u>\n\n-**just as accurate**：<u>同样准确、丝毫不差。</u>\n-**intuitive nature**：<u>直觉性、本质上依赖直觉的特征。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Critically</font>, another group was asked to spend a minute writing down reasons for their judgment, before giving the rating.\n翻译: <u>关键的是，另一组参与者被要求在给出评分之前花一分钟写下自己作出判断的理由。</u>\n\n-**critically**：<u>这里 critically 不是“批判性地”，而是：至关重要的是、关键的一点是。</u>\n\n---\n\nAccuracy dropped <font color=\"#ffff00\">dramatically</font>.\n翻译: <u>准确性急剧下降。</u>\n\n-**dramatically**：<u>显著地、急剧地。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmbady suspected that deliberation focused them on <font color=\"#ffff00\">vivid</font> but <font color=\"#ffff00\">misleading cues</font>, such as certain gestures or <font color=\"#ffff00\">utterances</font>, rather than letting <font color=\"#ffff00\">the complex interplay of</font> subtle signals form a holistic impression.\n翻译: <u>Ambady怀疑，深思熟虑使他们把注意力集中在鲜明但具有误导性的线索上，比如某些手势或话语，而不是让各种微妙信号的复杂互动形成一个整体印象。</u>\n\n-**vivid**：<u>鲜明的、容易被注意到的。</u>\n-**misleading cues**：<u>具有误导性的线索。</u>\n-**utterance**：<u>说出的话、言语表达。</u>\n-**the complex interplay of…**：<u>……之间复杂的相互作用。</u>\n\n---\n\nShe found similar interference when participants watched 15-second clips of <font color=\"#ffff00\">pairs of people</font> and judged whether they were strangers, friends, or dating partners.\n翻译: <u>当参与者观看一对对人15秒钟的视频片段，并判断他们是陌生人、朋友还是恋爱伴侣时，她发现了类似的干扰。</u>\n\n-**pairs of people**：<u>一对一对的人、两人组合。</u>\n\n---\n\nOther research shows we’re better at <font color=\"#ffff00\">detecting deception</font> from thin slices when we rely on intuition instead of reflection.\n翻译: <u>其他研究表明，当我们依靠直觉而不是反思时，我们更善于从薄片信息中识别欺骗。</u>\n\n-**detect deception**：<u>识别欺骗、发现别人是否在撒谎。</u>\n\n---\n\n“It’s as if you’re driving a stick shift,” says Judith Hall, a psychologist at Northeastern University, “and if you start thinking about it too much, you can’t remember what you’re doing.\n翻译: <u>“这就好像你在开手动挡汽车，”东北大学心理学家Judith Hall说，“如果你开始想得太多，就会记不起自己在做什么。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut if you go on automatic pilot,you’re fine.\n翻译: <u>但如果你进入自动驾驶状态，你就没问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMuch of our social life is like that.”\n翻译: <u>我们社会生活中的许多事情都是这样。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThinking too much can also harm our ability to form preferences.\n翻译: <u>想得太多也会损害我们形成偏好的能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCollege students’ ratings of strawberry jams and college courses aligned better with experts’ opinions when the students weren’t asked to analyze their <font color=\"#ffff00\">rationale</font>.\n翻译: <u>当大学生没有被要求分析自己的理由时，他们对草莓酱和大学课程的评分与专家意见更一致。</u>\n\n-**align with**：<u>与……一致、吻合。</u>\n-**rationale**：<u>理由、理论依据、判断背后的逻辑。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd people made car-buying decisions that were both objectively better and more personally satisfying when asked to focus on their feelings rather than on details, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">only if</font> the decision was complex—when they had a lot of information to process.\n翻译: <u>当人们被要求关注自己的感受而不是细节时，他们作出的购车决定在客观上更好，也更令个人满意；但这只在决策复杂时，即他们有大量信息需要处理时才成立。</u>\n\n-**only if**：<u>只有在……条件下才……</u>\n\n---\n\nIntuition’s special powers are <font color=\"#ffff00\">unleashed</font> only in certain circumstances.\n翻译: <u>直觉的特殊力量只会在某些情境下被释放出来。</u>\n\n-**unleash**：<u>释放，使……充分发挥。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn one study,participants completed a battery of eight tasks, including four that <font color=\"#ffff00\">tapped</font> reflective thinking (<font color=\"#ffff00\">discerning rules</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">comprehending vocabulary</font>) and four that tapped intuition and creativity (generating new products or <font color=\"#ffff00\">figures of speech</font>).\n翻译: <u>在一项研究中，参与者完成了一组共八项任务，其中四项考查反思性思维（辨别规则、理解词汇），另外四项考查直觉和创造力（生成新产品或修辞表达）。</u>\n\n-**a battery of tests/tasks**：<u>一整套测试或任务。</u>\n-**tap**：<u>在这里不是“轻敲”，而是：调动、利用、测量某种能力。</u>\n-**discern rules**：<u>辨别、发现规则。</u>\n-**comprehend vocabulary**：<u>理解词汇。</u>\n-**figures of speech**：<u>修辞表达，例如比喻、拟人等。</u>\n\n---\n\nThen they <font color=\"#ffff00\">rated the degree</font> to which they had used intuition (“gut feelings,” “ <font color=\"#ffff00\">hunches</font>,” “my heart”).\n翻译: <u>随后，他们评估自己使用直觉（“直觉感受”、“预感”、“我的内心”）的程度。</u>\n\n-**rate the degree**：<u>给程度评分、评估程度。</u>\n-**hunch**：<u>预感、直觉判断。</u>\n\n---\n\nUse of their gut hurt their performance on the first four tasks, as expected, and helped them on <font color=\"#ffff00\">the rest</font>.\n翻译: <u>正如预期，使用直觉损害了他们在前四项任务中的表现，却帮助了他们完成其余任务。</u>\n\n-**the rest**：<u>其余四项任务。</u>\n\n---\n\nSometimes the heart is smarter than the head.\n翻译: <u>有时候，心比脑更聪明。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2022","year":"2022","title":"2022 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2022 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2022 年英语二阅读.md + /Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/未命名 1/2022 年 英语 2.md","content":"第一篇\n\nOn a recent sunny day, 13,000 chickens <font color=\"#ffff00\">roam over</font> Larry Brown’s 40 windswept <font color=\"#ffff00\">acres</font> in Shiner, Texas.\n翻译: <u>在最近一个阳光明媚的日子里，13000只鸡在德克萨斯州Shiner的Larry Brown那片40英亩、风很大的土地上四处走动。</u>\n\n-**roam over**：<u>在……上四处走动、漫游。</u>\n-**40 acres**：<u>40 英亩土地。</u>\n\n---\n\nSome rest in the shade of a parked car.\n翻译: <u>有些鸡在一辆停着的汽车的阴影下休息。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOthers drink water with the cows.\n翻译: <u>另一些则和奶牛一起喝水。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThis all seems random, but it’s by design, part of what the $6.1 billion U.S. egg industry <font color=\"#ffff00\">bets</font> will be its next big thing: climate-friendly eggs.\n翻译: <u>这一切看似随意，但其实是有意设计的，是美国价值61亿美元的鸡蛋行业押注的下一个大趋势的一部分：气候友好型鸡蛋。</u>\n\n-**bets**：<u>押注、认为会成功。</u>\n\n---\n\nThese eggs, which are <font color=\"#ffff00\">making their debut</font> now on shelves for as much as $8 a dozen, are still labeled organic and animal-friendly, but they’re also from birds that live on farms using regenerative agriculture — special techniques to cultivate rich soils that can trap greenhouse gases.\n翻译: <u>这些鸡蛋如今正以每打高达8美元的价格首次出现在货架上，它们仍被标注为有机和动物友好型，但它们也来自生活在采用再生农业的农场里的鸡；再生农业指的是用于培育肥沃土壤、从而能够吸收温室气体的特殊技术。</u>\n\n-**make one’s debut**：<u>首次亮相、首次上市。</u>\n\n---\n\nSuch eggs could be marketed as helping to fight climate change.\n翻译: <u>这类鸡蛋可以被宣传为有助于应对气候变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I’m excited about our progress,” says Brown, who harvests eggs for Denver-based Nest Fresh Eggs and is adding more cover crops that draw worms and crickets for the chickens to eat.\n翻译: <u>“我对我们的进展感到兴奋，”Brown说。他为总部位于丹佛的Nest Fresh Eggs收集鸡蛋，并正在增加更多覆盖作物，以吸引蚯蚓和蟋蟀供鸡食用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe birds’ waste then fertilizes fields.\n翻译: <u>随后，这些鸡的排泄物又为田地施肥。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSuch improvements “allow our hens to forage for higher-quality natural feed that will be good for the land, the hens, and the eggs that we supply to our customers.”\n翻译: <u>这些改进“让我们的母鸡能够觅食到更高质量的天然饲料，这将有益于土地、母鸡以及我们供应给客户的鸡蛋。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe egg industry’s push is the first major test of whether animal products from regenerative farms can become the next premium offering.\n翻译: <u>鸡蛋行业的这一推动，是检验来自再生农场的动物产品能否成为下一个高端产品的首次重大考验。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn barely more than a decade, organic eggs went from being dismissed as a niche product in natural foods stores to being sold at Walmart.\n翻译: <u>在短短十多年里，有机鸡蛋从被视为天然食品商店里的小众产品，发展到在沃尔玛销售。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMore recently there were similar doubts about probiotics and plant-based meats, but both have exploded into major supermarket categories.\n翻译: <u>近来，人们对益生菌和植物基肉类也曾有类似怀疑，但两者都迅速发展成了大型超市品类。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIf the sustainable-egg rollout is successful, it could open the floodgates for regenerative beef, broccoli, and beyond.\n翻译: <u>如果可持续鸡蛋的推广获得成功，它可能会为再生牛肉、西兰花以及更多产品打开闸门。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRegenerative products could be a hard sell, because the concept is tough to define quickly, says Julie Stanton, associate professor of agricultural economics at Pennsylvania State University Brandywine.\n翻译: <u>宾夕法尼亚州立大学Brandywine校区农业经济学副教授Julie Stanton说，再生产品可能很难销售，因为这个概念很难迅速界定清楚。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSuch farming also brings minimal, if any, improvement to the food products, though some producers say their eggs have more protein.\n翻译: <u>这种耕作方式对食品本身也几乎没有带来改进，即便有，也很小（尽管一些生产者说他们的鸡蛋含有更多蛋白质）。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe industry is betting that the same consumers paying more for premium attributes such as free-range, non-GMO, and pasture-raised eggs will embrace sustainability.\n翻译: <u>该行业押注的是，那些愿意为散养、非转基因和牧场饲养鸡蛋等高端属性支付更高价格的消费者，也会接受可持续性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSurveys show that younger generations are more concerned about climate change, and some of the success of plant-based meat can be chalked up to shoppers wanting to signal their desire to protect the environment.\n翻译: <u>调查显示，年轻一代更关心气候变化，而植物基肉类的一部分成功，可以归因于购物者想要传达自己保护环境的愿望。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYoung adults “really care about the planet,” says John Brunnquell, president of Egg Innovations.\n翻译: <u>“年轻成年人真的很关心这个星球，”Egg Innovations总裁John Brunnquell说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“They are absolutely altering the food chain beyond what I think even they understand what they’re doing.”\n翻译: <u>“他们正在绝对地改变食物链，其程度甚至超出了我认为他们自己对所做之事的理解。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\n第二篇\n\n\n\n\nMore Americans are opting to <font color=\"#ffff00\">work well into retirement</font>, a growing trend that <font color=\"#ffff00\">threatens to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">upend</font> the old workforce model.\n翻译: <u>越来越多的美国人选择在退休后继续工作很长时间，这一日益增长的趋势可能会颠覆旧有的劳动力模式。</u>\n\n-**work well into retirement**：<u>在进入退休阶段后仍工作很长时间。</u>\n-**threaten to do**：<u>有可能做……，带有“可能造成重大影响”的意味。</u>  \n-**upend**：<u>颠覆、彻底改变。</u>\n\n---\n\nOne in three Americans <font color=\"#ffff00\">who are at least 40</font> have or plan to have a job in retirement to prepare for a longer life, according to a survey conducted by Harris Poll for TD Ameritrade.\n\n-who are at least 40 四十岁以上的\n-\n翻译: <u>根据Harris Poll为TD Ameritrade开展的一项调查，在至少40岁的美国人中，每三人就有一人已经或计划在退休后拥有一份工作，以应对更长寿的人生。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEven more surprising is that more than half of “unretirees” — those who plan to work in retirement or went back to work after retiring — said they would be employed in their later years even if they had enough money to settle down, the survey showed.\n翻译: <u>调查显示，更令人惊讶的是，在“未退休者”——即那些计划退休后工作或退休后又重返工作岗位的人——中，超过一半的人说，即使他们有足够的钱安顿下来，晚年也仍会工作。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFinancial needs aren’t the only <font color=\"#ffff00\">culprit</font> for the “unretirement” trend.\n翻译: <u>经济需求并不是“未退休”趋势的唯一原因。</u>\n\n-**culprit**：<u>罪魁祸首、主要原因。</u>\n\n---\n\nOther reasons, according to the study, include <font color=\"#ffff00\">personal fulfillment</font> such as staying mentally fit, preventing boredom or avoiding depression.\n\n-\n**personal fulfillment**：个人成就感、个人满足感。\n-\n翻译: <u>根据这项研究，其他原因包括个人满足感，例如保持心理健康、防止无聊或避免抑郁。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAbout 72% of “unretiree” respondents said that they would return to work once retired to keep mentally fit while 59% said it would<font color=\"#ffff00\"> be tied to</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">making ends meet</font>.\n翻译: <u>约72%的“未退休者”受访者表示，他们退休后会为了保持心理健康而重返工作岗位，而59%的人表示这会与维持生计有关。</u>\n\n-**be tied to…**：<u>与……有关。</u>  \n-**make ends meet**：<u>维持生计、收支相抵。</u>\n\n---\n\n“The concept of retirement is <font color=\"#ffff00\">evolving,</font>” said Christine Russell, senior manager of retirement at TD Ameritrade.\n翻译: <u>“退休的概念正在演变，”TD Ameritrade退休业务高级经理Christine Russell说。</u>\n\n-**is evolving**：<u>正在演变、发展。   变了下形式还有点看不出来了</u>\n\n---\n\n“It’s not just about finances.\n翻译: <u>“它不只是关乎财务。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe value of work is also driving folks to continue working past retirement.”\n翻译: <u>工作的价值也在推动人们过了退休年龄之后继续工作。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOne reason for the change in retirement patterns: Americans are living longer.\n翻译: <u>退休模式发生变化的一个原因是：美国人寿命更长了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">The share of the population</font> 65 and older was 16% in 2018, up 32% from the prior year, according to the U.S. Census Bureau.\n翻译: <u>根据美国</u>\n\n-**share of the population**：<u>人口比例。</u>\n\n---\n\nCensus Bureau.\n翻译: <u>人口普查局的数据，2018年65岁及以上人口占总人口的比例为16%，比前一年上升32%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat’s also up 302% since 2010.\n翻译: <u>这也比2010年以来上升了302%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOlder Americans are also the fastest-growing segment of the U.S. workforce, and boomers are expected to live longer than previous generations.\n翻译: <u>老年美国人也是美国劳动力中增长最快的群体，婴儿潮一代的预期寿命也将比前几代人更长。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe percentage of retirement-age people in the labor force has doubled over the past three decades.\n翻译: <u>在过去三十年里，劳动人口中达到退休年龄者的比例已经翻了一番。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAbout 20% of people 65 and older were in the workforce in February, <font color=\"#ffff00\">up from </font>an <font color=\"#ffff00\">all-time low</font> of 10% in January 1985, according to <font color=\"#ffff00\">money manager</font> United Income.\n翻译: <u>据资产管理公司United Income称，2月份，65岁及以上人群中约20%仍在劳动力队伍中，高于1985年1月10%的历史低点。</u>\n\n-**up from…**：<u>从……上升。</u>  \n-**all-time low**：<u>历史最低点。</u>  \n-**money manager**：<u>资产管理公司 / 投资管理机构。</u>\n\n---\n\nBecause of longer life spans, Americans are also boosting their savings to preserve their <font color=\"#ffff00\">nest eggs</font>, the TD Ameritrade study showed, which surveyed 2000 adults between 40 to 79.\n翻译: <u>TD Ameritrade这项对2000名40至79岁成年人进行的调查显示，由于寿命延长，美国人也在增加储蓄，以保住自己的养老积蓄。</u>\n\n-**nest egg**：<u>储备金、养老积蓄。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Six in 10 </font>“unretirees” are increasing their savings in anticipation of a longer life, according to the survey.\n翻译: <u>调查显示，十分之六的“未退休者”正在增加储蓄，以应对更长的寿命。</u>\n\n-**Six in 10**：<u>十个中有六个，也就是 60%。</u>\n\n---\n\nAmong the most popular ways they are doing this, the company said, is <font color=\"#ffff00\">by </font>reducing their overall expenses, <font color=\"#ffff00\">securing</font> life insurance or maximizing their <font color=\"#ffff00\">contributions</font> to retirement accounts.\n翻译: <u>该公司表示，他们这样做的最受欢迎方式包括减少总体开支、购买人寿保险，或尽可能提高对退休账户的缴款。</u>\n\n-**by  通过\n-**securing life insurance**：<u>取得/安排人寿保险。</u>  \n-**maximizing their contributions to retirement accounts**：<u>最大化向退休账户的缴款。</u>\n\n---\n\nUnfortunately, many people who are opting to work in retirement are preparing to do so because they are worried about making ends meet in their later years, said Brent Weiss, a co-founder at <font color=\"#ffff00\">Baltimore-based</font> financial-planning firm Facet Wealth.\n翻译: <u>位于巴尔的摩的理财规划公司Facet Wealth联合创始人Brent Weiss说，不幸的是，许多选择退休后工作的人之所以准备这样做，是因为他们担心晚年难以维持生计。</u>\n\n-**Baltimore-based**：<u>总部位于巴尔的摩的。</u>\n\n---\n\nHe suggested that preretirees should speak with a financial adviser to set long-term financial goals.\n翻译: <u>他建议，退休前人群应与理财顾问交谈，以设定长期财务目标。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“The most challenging moments in life are getting married, starting a family and ultimately retiring,” Weiss said.\n翻译: <u>“人生中最具挑战性的时刻是结婚、组建家庭，最终还有退休，”Weiss说。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It’s not just a financial decision, but an emotional one.\n翻译: <u>“这不仅是一个财务决定，也是一个情感决定。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMany people believe they can’t retire.”\n翻译: <u>许多人认为他们无法退休。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nWe have all encountered them, in both our personal and professional lives.\n翻译: <u>我们在个人生活和职业生活中都遇到过它们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThink about the times you felt tricked or frustrated by a membership or subscription that had a <font color=\"#ffff00\">seamless</font> sign-up process but was later difficult to cancel.\n翻译: <u>想想那些时候：你曾因某个会员或订阅服务而感到受骗或沮丧，它的注册流程很顺畅，但后来却很难取消。</u>\n\n-**seamless**：<u>本义是“没有接缝的”，引申为；流畅的、无障碍的、毫不费力的</u>\n\n---\n\nSomething that should be simple and transparent can be complicated, intentionally or unintentionally, in ways that impair consumer choice.\n翻译: <u>本应简单透明的事情，可能会以有意或无意的方式变得复杂，从而损害消费者的选择。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThese are examples of dark patterns.\n翻译: <u>这些都是黑暗模式的例子。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFirst coined in 2010 by user experience expert Harry Brignull, “ dark patterns” is a <font color=\"#ffff00\">catch-all term</font> for practices that manipulate user interfaces to influence the decision-making ability of users.\n翻译: <u>“黑暗模式”这一说法最早由用户体验专家哈里·布里格诺尔在2010年提出，它是一个统称，指那些通过操纵用户界面来影响用户决策能力的做法。</u>\n\n-**catch-all term**：<u>包罗性术语、统称。</u>\n\n---\n\nBrignull identifies 12 types of common dark patterns, ranging from misdirection and hidden costs to “<font color=\"#ffff00\">roach motel</font>,” where a user experience seems easy and <font color=\"#ffff00\">intuitive</font> at the start, but turns difficult when the user tries to get out.\n翻译: <u>布里格诺尔确定了12种常见的黑暗模式，范围从误导和隐藏费用到“蟑螂旅馆”不等；所谓“蟑螂旅馆”，是指一种用户体验起初看起来简单而直观，但当用户试图退出时却变得困难。</u>\n\n-**roach motel**：<u>蟑螂旅馆模式。</u>\n-**intuitive**：<u>直观易懂的、不用特别学习就知道如何操作的。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn a 2019 study of 53,000 product pages and 11,000 websites, researchers found that about <font color=\"#ffff00\">one in 10</font> employs <font color=\"#ffff00\">these design practices</font>.\n翻译: <u>在2019年一项针对53000个产品页面和11000个网站的研究中，研究人员发现，大约每10个网站中就有1个采用了这些设计做法。</u>\n\n-**one in 10**：<u>每十个中有一个，即约10%。</u>\n-**these design practices**：<u>这些设计手法，即暗黑模式。</u>\n\n---\n\nThough widely prevalent, the concept o f dark patterns is still not well understood.\n翻译: <u>尽管黑暗模式广泛存在，但这一概念仍未被充分理解。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBusiness and nonprofit leaders should be aware of dark patterns and try to avoid the gray areas they engender.\n翻译: <u>企业和非营利组织的领导者应当了解黑暗模式，并努力避免其所造成的灰色地带。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhere is the line between ethical, persuasive design and dark patterns?\n翻译: <u>合乎伦理的说服性设计与黑暗模式之间的界线在哪里？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBusinesses should engage in conversations with IT, compliance, risk, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">legal teams</font> to review their privacy policy, and include in the discussion the customer/user experience designers and coders responsible for the company’s user interface, as well as the marketers and advertisers responsible for <font color=\"#ffff00\">sign-ups</font>, <font color=\"#ffff00\">checkout baskets</font>, pricing, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">promotions</font>.\n翻译: <u>企业应当与信息技术、合规、风险和法律团队展开对话，以审查其隐私政策，并将负责公司用户界面的客户/用户体验设计师和程序员，以及负责注册、结账购物篮、定价和促销的营销人员和广告人员纳入讨论。</u>\n\n-**compliance teams**：<u>合规团队</u>\n-**sign-ups**：<u>用户注册、会员开通。</u>\n-**checkout baskets**：<u>结账购物车或购物篮流程。</u>\n-**promotions**：<u>促销活动。</u>\n-**IT teams**：<u>信息技术团队</u>\n-**risk teams**：<u>风险管理团队</u>\n-**legal teams**：<u>法务团队</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Any or all</font> these teams can play a role in creating or avoiding “digital deception.”\n翻译: <u>这些团队中的任何一个或全部，都可能在制造或避免“数字欺骗”方面发挥作用。</u>\n\n-**any or all**：<u>任何一个，或者全部。</u>\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Lawmakers</font> and regulators are slowly starting to address the <font color=\"#ffff00\">ambiguity</font> around dark patterns, most recently <font color=\"#ffff00\">at the state level</font>.\n翻译: <u>立法者和监管机构正开始缓慢处理围绕黑暗模式的不明确性，最近尤其是在州一级。</u>\n\n-**lawmakers**：<u>立法者、议员。</u>\n-**ambiguity**：<u>模糊性、不明确之处。</u>\n-**at the state level**：<u>在州政府层面。</u>\n\n---\n\nIn March, the California <font color=\"#ffff00\">Attorney General</font> announced the approval of <font color=\"#ffff00\">additional regulations</font> under the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) that “ensure that consumers will not be confused or misled when seeking to exercise their data privacy rights.”\n翻译: <u>3月，加利福尼亚州总检察长宣布批准《加利福尼亚消费者隐私法》（CCPA）下的附加规定，这些规定“确保消费者在试图行使其数据隐私权时不会感到困惑或受到误导”。</u>\n\n-**Attorney General**：<u>总检察长、司法部长。</u>\n-**additional regulations**：<u>补充法规、额外规定。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe regulations aim to ban dark patterns—this means prohibiting companies from using u confusing language or unnecessary steps such as forcing them to click through multiple screens or listen to reasons why they shouldn’t opt out.”\n翻译: <u>这些规定旨在禁止黑暗模式，这意味着禁止公司使用令人困惑的语言或不必要的步骤，例如迫使消费者点击多个页面，或听取他们不应选择退出的理由。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">As</font> more states consider promulgating additional regulations, there is a need for greater <font color=\"#ffff00\">accountability</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">from within</font> the business community.\n翻译: <u>随着更多州考虑颁布附加规定，商业界内部需要更大的问责。</u>\n\n-**as**：<u>在这里表示“随着”。</u>\n-**promulgate**：<u>正式颁布、发布法律或法规。</u>\n-**accountability**：<u>问责、责任承担。</u>\n-**from within**：<u>从内部产生。</u>\n\n---\n\nDark patterns also can be addressed <font color=\"#ffff00\">on a</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">self-regulatory</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">basis</font>, but <font color=\"#ffff00\">only if</font> organizations hold themselves accountable, not just to legal requirements but also to <font color=\"#ffff00\">industry best practices</font> and standards.\n翻译: <u>黑暗模式也可以通过自律方式加以处理，但前提是组织让自己承担责任，不仅对法律要求负责，也对行业最佳实践和标准负责。</u>\n\n-**on a…basis**：<u>以……为基础、通过……方式。</u>\n-**self-regulatory**：<u>自我监管的、行业自律的。</u>\n-**only if**：<u>只有在……条件下才……</u>\n-**hold someone accountable**：<u>要求某人对自己的行为负责。</u>\n-**industry best practices**：<u>行业最佳实践，指公认更合理、更负责任的做法。</u>\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nAlthough <font color=\"#ffff00\">ethics classes</font> are common around the world, scientists are unsure if their lessons can actually change behavior; <font color=\"#ffff00\">evidence either way</font> is weak, relying on <font color=\"#ffff00\">contrived</font> laboratory tests or sometimes unreliable self-reports.\n翻译: <u>尽管伦理课程在世界各地都很常见，但科学家并不确定这些课程的内容是否真的能改变行为；支持或反对这一点的证据都很薄弱，依赖的是人为设计的实验室测试，或有时并不可靠的自我报告。</u>\n\n-**ethics classes**：<u>伦理学课程、道德教育课程。</u>\n-**be unsure**：<u>不确定、没有把握。</u>\n-**either way**：<u>在这里指两种可能；1. 伦理课能够改变行为；2. 伦理课不能改变行为；支持任一结论的证据</u>\n-**contrived**：<u>刻意设计的、人为制造的、不够自然的；</u>\n\n---\n\nBut a new study published in Cognition found that, in at least one real-world situation, a single ethics lesson may have had lasting effects.\n翻译: <u>但一项发表在《Cognition》上的新研究发现，至少在一种现实情境中，一堂伦理课可能产生了持久影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe researchers investigated <font color=\"#ffff00\">one class session</font>’s impact on eating meat.\n翻译: <u>研究人员考察了一节课对吃肉这一行为的影响。</u>\n\n-**one class session**：<u>一节课、一次课堂活动。</u>\n\n---\n\nThey chose <font color=\"#ffff00\">this particular behavior</font> for three reasons, according to study co-author Eric Schwitzgebel, a philosopher at the University of California, Riverside: students’ attitudes on the topic are variable and <font color=\"#ffff00\">unstable</font>, behavior is easily measurable, and <font color=\"#ffff00\">ethics literature</font> largely agrees that eating less meat is good because it reduces environmental harm and animal suffering.\n翻译: <u>据该研究的共同作者、加利福尼亚大学河滨分校哲学家埃里克·施维茨格贝尔称，他们选择这一特定行为有三个原因：学生对这一话题的态度多变且不稳定，行为容易测量，而且伦理学文献在很大程度上一致认为，少吃肉是有益的，因为它能减少环境伤害和动物痛苦。</u>\n\n-**this particular behavior**：<u>吃肉这一特定行为。</u>\n-**unstable**：<u>不稳定的、容易改变的。</u>\n-**ethics literature**：<u>伦理学相关文献、伦理学研究成果。</u>\n\n---\n\nHalf of the students in four large philosophy classes read an article on the ethics of factory-farmed meat, <font color=\"#ffff00\">optionally</font> watched an 11-minute video on the topic and joined a 50-minute discussion.\n翻译: <u>四个大型哲学班中有一半学生阅读了一篇关于工厂化养殖肉类伦理问题的文章，可选择观看一段关于该话题的11分钟视频，并参加了一场50分钟的讨论。</u>\n\n-**optionally**：<u>可选择地、不是强制地。</u>\n\n---\n\nThe other half focused on <font color=\"#ffff00\">charitable giving</font> <font color=\"#ffff00\">instead</font>.\n翻译: <u>另一半学生则转而关注慈善捐赠。</u>\n\n-**charitable giving**：<u>慈善捐赠、向公益事业捐款；作为替代、而不是讨论吃肉伦理</u>\n\n---\n\nThen, <font color=\"#ffff00\">unknown to the students</font>, the researchers studied their anonymized meal-card purchases for that semester—nearly 14,000 <font color=\"#ffff00\">receipts</font> for almost 500 students.\n翻译: <u>随后，在学生不知情的情况下，研究人员研究了他们该学期经过匿名处理的餐卡购买记录，涉及近500名学生的将近14000张收据。</u>\n\n-**unknown to someone**：<u>不为某人所知。</u>\n-**without the students knowing it**：<u>在学生不知道这件事的情况下。</u>\n-**receipts**：<u>购物小票、交易记录。</u>\n\n---\n\nSchwitzgebel predicted the intervention would have no effect; he had previously found that ethics professors do not differ from other professors on a range of behaviors, including voting rates, blood donation and returning library books.\n翻译: <u>施维茨格贝尔原本预测这种干预不会产生效果；他此前发现，在包括投票率、献血和归还图书馆书籍在内的一系列行为上，伦理学教授与其他教授并无差异。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut among <font color=\"#ffff00\">student subjects</font> who discussed meat ethics, meal purchases containing meat decreased from 52 to 45 percent—and this effect held steady for the study’s duration of several weeks.\n翻译: <u>但在讨论过肉类伦理的学生受试者中，含肉餐食的购买比例从52%下降到45%，而且这一效果在研究持续的数周内保持稳定。</u>\n\n-**student subjects**：<u>作为研究对象的学生。</u>\n\n---\n\nPurchases from the other group remained at 52 percent.\n翻译: <u>另一组的购买比例则维持在52%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“That’s actually a pretty large effect for a pretty small intervention,” Schwitzgebel says.\n翻译: <u>施维茨格贝尔说：“对于一次相当小的干预来说，这实际上是一个相当大的效果。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPsychologist Nina Strohminger at the University of Pennsylvania, who was not involved in the study, says she wants the effect to be real but cannot <font color=\"#ffff00\">rule out</font> some unknown <font color=\"#ffff00\">confounding variable</font>.\n翻译: <u>宾夕法尼亚大学心理学家妮娜·斯特罗明格没有参与这项研究，她说自己希望这种效果是真实的，但不能排除某些未知混杂变量的影响。</u>\n\n-**want A to be B**：<u>希望A是B。</u>\n-**rule out**：<u>排除某种可能性。</u>\n-**confounding variable**：<u>混杂变量、干扰变量。</u>\n\n---\n\nAnd if real, she notes, it might be <font color=\"#ffff00\">reversible</font> by another <font color=\"#ffff00\">nudge</font>: “Easy come, easy go.”\n翻译: <u>她还指出，如果这种效果是真实的，它也可能被另一次推动逆转：“来得容易，去得也容易。”</u>\n\n-**reversible**：<u>可以逆转的、可以恢复原状的。</u>\n-**nudge**：<u>轻推、助推。</u>\n\n---\n\nSchwitzgebel suspects the greatest impact came from social influence- classmates or teaching assistants leading the discussions may have shared their own vegetarianism, showing it as <font color=\"#ffff00\">achievable</font> or <font color=\"#ffff00\">more common</font>.\n翻译: <u>施维茨格贝尔怀疑，最大的影响来自社会影响：主持讨论的同学或助教可能分享了他们自己吃素的经历，从而显示出这件事是可以做到的，或者比人们想象的更常见。</u>\n\n-**achievable**：<u>能够实现的、做得到的。</u>\n-**more common**：<u>更常见的。</u>\n\n---\n\nSecond, the video may have had an emotional impact.\n翻译: <u>其次，视频可能产生了情感影响。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n<font color=\"#ffff00\">Least rousing</font>, he thinks, was rational argument, although his co-authors say <font color=\"#ffff00\">reason</font> might play a bigger role.\n翻译: <u>他认为，最不令人振奋的是理性论证，尽管他的共同作者说，理性可能发挥更大的作用。</u>\n\n-**least rousing**：<u>最不容易打动人、最缺乏激发作用的；这里不是说理性论证完全没有作用，而是 Schwitzgebel 认为它在几个因素中作用最小</u>\n-**reason**：<u>理性、逻辑思考。</u>\n\n---\n\nNow the researchers are probing the specific effects of teaching style, <font color=\"#ffff00\">teaching assistants’ eating habits</font> and <font color=\"#ffff00\">students’ video exposure</font>.\n翻译: <u>目前，研究人员正在探究教学风格、助教的饮食习惯以及学生观看视频情况所产生的具体影响。</u>\n\n-**probe**：<u>深入调查、探究。</u>\n-**teaching assistants’ eating habits**：<u>助教本人的饮食习惯，例如是否吃素。</u>\n-**students’ video exposure**：<u>学生接触视频的程度，即是否观看、观看了多少。</u>\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, Schwitzgebel—who had predicted no effect—will be eating his words.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，曾预测不会有效果的施维茨格贝尔将不得不承认自己错了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2023","year":"2023","title":"2023 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2023 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2023 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIn the quest for the perfect lawn, homeowners across the country are taking a shortcut—and it is the environment that is paying the price.\n翻译: <u>在追求完美草坪的过程中，全国各地的房主正在走捷径，而为此付出代价的是环境。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAbout eight million square metres of plastic grass is sold each year but opposition has now spread to the highest gardening circles.\n翻译: <u>每年约有800万平方米的塑料草坪被售出，但反对声如今已经蔓延到园艺界最高层。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe Chelsea Flower Show has banned fake grass from this year’s event, declaring it to be not part of its ethos.\n翻译: <u>切尔西花展已禁止今年的活动使用假草，并称其不符合该展会的理念。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe Royal Horticultural Society (RHS), which runs the annual show in west London, says it has introduced the ban because of the damage plastic grass does to the environment and biodiversity.\n翻译: <u>负责在伦敦西部举办这一年度展会的英国皇家园艺学会（RHS）表示，之所以实施这一禁令，是因为塑料草坪对环境和生物多样性造成损害。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nEd Home, of the RHS, said: “We launched our sustainability strategy last year and fake grass is just not in line with our ethos and views on plastic.\n翻译: <u>英国皇家园艺学会的埃德·霍姆说：“我们去年启动了可持续发展战略，而假草根本不符合我们关于塑料的理念和看法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWe recommend using real grass because of its environmental benefits, which include supporting wildlife, alleviating flooding and cooling the environment.”\n翻译: <u>我们建议使用真草，因为它有环境效益，包括支持野生生物、缓解洪水以及为环境降温。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe RHS’s decision comes as campaigners try to raise awareness of the problems fake grass causes.\n翻译: <u>英国皇家园艺学会作出这一决定之际，活动人士正试图提高人们对假草所造成问题的认识。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA Twitter account, which claims to “cut through the greenwash” of artificial grass, already has more than 20,000 followers.\n翻译: <u>一个声称要“戳穿”人造草绿色漂洗的推特账号，已经拥有超过20000名关注者。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt is trying to encourage people to sign two petitions, one calling for a ban on the sale of plastic grass and another calling for an “ecological damage” tax on such lawns.\n翻译: <u>该账号正试图鼓励人们签署两份请愿书，一份呼吁禁止销售塑料草坪，另一份呼吁对此类草坪征收“生态损害”税。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey have gathered 7,276 and 11,282 signatures.\n翻译: <u>这两份请愿书已分别收集到7276个和11282个签名。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHowever, supporters of fake grass point out that there is also an environmental impact with natural lawns, which need mowing and therefore usually consume electricity or petrol.\n翻译: <u>然而，假草的支持者指出，天然草坪也会产生环境影响，因为天然草坪需要修剪，因此通常会消耗电力或汽油。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe industry also points out that real grass requires considerable amounts of water, weed killer or other treatments and that people who lay fake grass tend to use their garden more.\n翻译: <u>该行业还指出，真草需要大量的水、除草剂或其他处理，而且铺设假草的人往往会更频繁地使用自己的花园。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe industry also claims that people who lay fake grass spend an average of £500 on trees or shrubs for their garden, which provides habitat for insects.\n翻译: <u>该行业还声称，铺设假草的人平均会在花园里的树木或灌木上花费500英镑，而这些树木或灌木能为昆虫提供栖息地。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn response to another petition last year about banning fake lawns, which gathered 30,000 signatures, the government responded that it has “no plans to ban the use of artificial grass”.\n翻译: <u>去年，针对另一份要求禁止假草坪、并收集到30000个签名的请愿书，政府回应称，它“没有禁止使用人造草的计划”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt added: “We prefer to help people and organisations make the right choice rather than legislating on such matters.\n翻译: <u>政府还补充说：“我们更愿意帮助人们和组织作出正确选择，而不是就此类事项立法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHowever, the use of artificial grass must comply with the legal and policy safeguards in place to protect biodiversity and ensure sustainable drainage, while measures such as the strengthened biodiversity duty should serve to encourage public authorities to consider sustainable alternatives.”\n翻译: <u>然而，人造草的使用必须符合现有用于保护生物多样性并确保可持续排水的法律和政策保障，同时，加强后的生物多样性义务等措施应当有助于鼓励公共机构考虑可持续替代方案。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nIt’s easy to dismiss as absurd the federal government’s ideas for plugging the chronic funding gap of our national parks.\n翻译: <u>人们很容易把联邦政府关于填补我们国家公园长期资金缺口的想法斥为荒谬。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCan anyone really think ifs a good idea to allow Amazon deliveries to your tent in Yosemite or food trucks to line up under the redwood trees at Sequoia National Park?\n翻译: <u>真的会有人认为，允许亚马逊把包裹送到你在优胜美地的帐篷里，或者让餐车在红杉国家公园的红杉树下排队，是个好主意吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the government is right about one thing: U.S. national parks are in crisis.\n翻译: <u>但政府有一点是对的：美国国家公园正处于危机之中。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCollectively, they have a maintenance backlog of more than $ 12 billion.\n翻译: <u>总体而言，它们积压的维护项目超过120亿美元。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRoads, trails, restrooms, visitor centers and other infrastructure are crumbling.\n翻译: <u>道路、小径、洗手间、游客中心和其他基础设施正在破败。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut privatizing and commercializing the campgrounds would not be a cure-all.\n翻译: <u>但将露营地私有化和商业化并不会成为包治百病的办法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCampgrounds are a tiny portion of the overall infrastructure backlog, and businesses in the parks hand over, on average, only about 5% of their revenues to the National Park Service.\n翻译: <u>露营地只占整体基础设施积压项目的一小部分，而且公园内的企业平均只把其收入的大约5%上交给国家公园管理局。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMoreover, increased privatization would certainly undercut one of the major reasons why 300 million visitors come to the parks each year: to enjoy nature and get a break from the commercial drumbeat that overwhelms daily life.\n翻译: <u>此外，扩大私有化无疑会削弱每年3亿游客来到这些公园的一个主要原因：享受自然，并从压倒日常生活的商业鼓点中暂时解脱出来。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe real problem is that the parks have been chronically starved of funding.\n翻译: <u>真正的问题在于，这些公园长期资金不足。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAn economic survey of 700 U.S. taxpayers found that people would be willing to pay a significant amount of money to make sure the parks and their programs are kept intact.\n翻译: <u>一项针对700名美国纳税人的经济调查发现，人们愿意支付相当可观的金额，以确保这些公园及其项目保持完整。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome 81% of respondents said they would be willing to pay additional taxes for the next 10 years to avoid any cuts to the national parks.\n翻译: <u>约81%的受访者表示，他们愿意在未来10年缴纳额外税款，以避免国家公园遭到任何削减。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe national parks provide great value to U.S. residents both as places to escape and as symbols of nature.\n翻译: <u>国家公园作为逃离日常之处和自然象征，为美国居民提供了巨大价值。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOn top of this, they produce value from their extensive educational programs, their positive impact on the climate through carbon sequestration, their contribution to our cultural and artistic life, and of course through tourism.\n翻译: <u>除此之外，它们还通过广泛的教育项目、通过碳封存对气候产生的积极影响、对我们的文化和艺术生活的贡献，当然也通过旅游业，创造价值。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe parks also help keep America’s past alive, working with thousands of local jurisdictions around the country to protect historical sites and to bring the stories of these places to life.\n翻译: <u>这些公园还与全国数千个地方管辖机构合作，保护历史遗址，并让这些地方的故事鲜活起来，从而帮助美国的过去延续下去。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe parks do all this on a shoestring.\n翻译: <u>这些公园靠极少的经费做到了所有这些。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCongress allocates only $ 3 billion a year to the national park system—an amount that has been flat since 2001 (in inflation-adjusted dollars) with the exception of a onetime boost in 2009.\n翻译: <u>国会每年只向国家公园系统拨款30亿美元；除2009年一次性增加拨款外，这一金额自2001年以来一直持平（按通胀调整后的美元计算）。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMeanwhile, the number of annual visitors has increased by more than 50% since 1980, and now stands at 330 million visitors per year.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，自1980年以来，每年游客数量已增加逾50%，如今达到每年3.3亿人次。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nThe Internet may be changing merely what we remember, not our capacity to do so, suggests Columbia University psychology professor Betsy Sparrow.\n翻译: <u>哥伦比亚大学心理学教授贝齐·斯帕罗认为，互联网可能只是在改变我们记住什么，而不是改变我们记忆的能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn 2011, Sparrow led a study in which participants were asked to record 40 factoids in a computer (“an ostrich’s eye is bigger than its brain,” for example).\n翻译: <u>2011年，斯帕罗主持了一项研究，参与者被要求在电脑中记录40条小事实（例如，“鸵鸟的眼睛比它的大脑还大”）。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nHalf of the participants were told the information would be erased, while the other half were told it would be saved.\n翻译: <u>一半参与者被告知这些信息会被删除，而另一半则被告知这些信息会被保存。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nGuess what?\n翻译: <u>猜猜结果如何？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe latter group made no effort to recall the information when quizzed on it later, because they knew they could find it on their computers.\n翻译: <u>后一组在后来接受相关测验时并没有努力回忆这些信息，因为他们知道自己可以在电脑上找到它们。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn the same study, a group was asked to remember both the information and the folders it was stored in.\n翻译: <u>在同一项研究中，有一组参与者被要求同时记住信息以及存放这些信息的文件夹。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThey didn’t remember the information, but they remembered how to find the folders.\n翻译: <u>他们没有记住这些信息，但他们记住了如何找到这些文件夹。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn other words, human memory is not deteriorating but “adapting to new communications technology,” Sparrow says.\n翻译: <u>换句话说，Sparrow 说，人类记忆并不是在退化，而是在“适应新的通信技术”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn a very practical way, the Internet is becoming an external hard drive for our memories, a process known as “cognitive offloading.”\n翻译: <u>从非常实际的意义上说，互联网正在成为我们记忆的外部硬盘，这一过程被称为“认知卸载”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTraditionally, this role was fulfilled by data banks, libraries, and other humans.\n翻译: <u>传统上，这一角色由数据库、图书馆以及其他人来承担。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nYour father may never remember birthdays because your mother does, for instance.\n翻译: <u>例如，你父亲可能永远记不住生日，因为你母亲会记得。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSome worry that this is having a destructive effect on society, but Sparrow sees an upside.\n翻译: <u>有些人担心这正在对社会产生破坏性影响，但 Sparrow 看到了其中积极的一面。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPerhaps, she suggests, the trend will change our approach to learning from a focus on individual facts and memorization to an emphasis on more conceptual thinking—something that is not available on the Internet.\n翻译: <u>她提出，也许这一趋势会改变我们的学习方式，使其从关注个别事实和记忆，转向强调更具概念性的思考，而这种思考是互联网上无法获得的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“I personally have never seen all that much intellectual value in memorizing things,” Sparrow says, adding that we haven’t lost our ability to do it.\n翻译: <u>Sparrow 说：“就我个人而言，我从来没有在记忆事物这件事上看到太多智力价值。”她还补充说，我们并没有失去这样做的能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nStill other experts say ifs too soon to understand how the Internet affects our brains.\n翻译: <u>还有其他专家说，现在要理解互联网如何影响我们的大脑还为时过早。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere is no experimental evidence showing that it interferes with our ability to focus, for instance, wrote psychologists Christopher Chabris and Daniel J.\n翻译: <u>例如，心理学家 Christopher Chabris 和 Daniel J. 写道，没有实验证据表明它会干扰我们的专注能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSimons.\n翻译: <u>Simons。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAnd surfing the web exercised the brain more than reading did among computer-savvy older adults in a 2008 study involving 24 participants at the Semel Institute for Neuroscience and Human Behavior at the University of California, Los Angeles.\n翻译: <u>此外，2008 年加利福尼亚大学洛杉矶分校 Semel 神经科学与人类行为研究所一项涉及 24 名参与者的研究显示，在熟悉电脑的老年人中，网上浏览比阅读更能锻炼大脑。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“There may be costs associated with our increased reliance on the Internet, but I’d have to imagine that overall the benefits are going to outweigh those costs,” observes psychology professor Benjamin Storm.\n翻译: <u>心理学教授 Benjamin Storm 评论说：“我们对互联网日益增加的依赖可能会带来一些代价，但我不得不认为，总体而言，收益将会超过这些代价。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It seems pretty clear that memory is changing, but is it changing for the better?\n翻译: <u>“看起来很清楚的是，记忆正在发生变化，但它是在变得更好吗？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt this point, we don’t know.”\n翻译: <u>在这一点上，我们还不知道。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nTeenagers are paradoxical.\n翻译: <u>青少年是矛盾的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat’s a mild and detached way of saying something that parents often express with considerably stronger language.\n翻译: <u>这是一种温和而超然的说法，用来表达父母们常常会用强烈得多的语言来表达的事情。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the paradox is scientific as well as personal.\n翻译: <u>但这种矛盾既是个人层面的，也是科学层面的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn adolescence, helpless and dependent children who have relied on grown-ups for just about everything become independent people who can take care of themselves and help each other.\n翻译: <u>在青春期，那些几乎事事依赖成年人的无助而依赖性强的孩子，会变成能够照顾自己并互相帮助的独立个体。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAt the same time, once cheerful and compliant children become rebellious teenage risk-takers.\n翻译: <u>与此同时，曾经快乐而顺从的孩子会变成叛逆、爱冒险的青少年。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA new study published in the journal Child Development, by Eveline Crone of the University of Leiden and colleagues, suggests that the positive and negative sides of teenagers go hand in hand.\n翻译: <u>莱顿大学的 Eveline Crone 及其同事发表在《儿童发展》期刊上的一项新研究表明，青少年的积极面和消极面是相伴而生的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe study is part of a new wave of thinking about adolescence.\n翻译: <u>这项研究是关于青春期的一股新思潮的一部分。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFor a long time, scientists and policy makers concentrated on the idea that teenagers were a problem that needed to be solved.\n翻译: <u>长期以来，科学家和政策制定者一直集中关注这样一种观念：青少年是一个需要解决的问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe new work emphasizes that adolescence is a time of opportunity as well as risk.\n翻译: <u>新的研究强调，青春期既是充满机会的时期，也是充满风险的时期。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe researchers studied “prosocial” and rebellious traits in more than 200 children and young adults, ranging from 11 to 28 years old.\n翻译: <u>研究人员研究了 200 多名儿童和年轻成年人的“亲社会”特质和叛逆特质，他们的年龄从 11 岁到 28 岁不等。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe participants filled out questionnaires about how often they did things that were altruistic and positive, like sacrificing their own interests to help a friend, or rebellious and negative, like getting drunk or staying out late.\n翻译: <u>参与者填写了问卷，说明他们多久会做一些利他且积极的事情，比如牺牲自己的利益去帮助朋友，或者做一些叛逆且消极的事情，比如喝醉酒或很晚不回家。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOther studies have shown that rebellious behavior increases as you become a teenager and then fades away as you grow older.\n翻译: <u>其他研究已经表明，叛逆行为会随着你进入青少年时期而增加，然后随着年龄增长而逐渐消退。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut the new study shows that, interestingly, the same pattern holds for prosocial behavior.\n翻译: <u>但这项新研究有趣地表明，同样的模式也适用于亲社会行为。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTeenagers were more likely than younger children or adults to report that they did things like unselfishly helping a friend.\n翻译: <u>与年幼儿童或成年人相比，青少年更可能报告说他们做过无私帮助朋友之类的事情。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMost significantly, there was a positive correlation between prosociality and rebelliousness.\n翻译: <u>最重要的是，亲社会性与叛逆性之间存在正相关。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe teenagers who were more rebellious were also more likely to help others.\n翻译: <u>那些更叛逆的青少年也更有可能帮助他人。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe good and bad sides of adolescence seem to develop together.\n翻译: <u>青春期的好的一面和坏的一面似乎是一起发展的。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIs there some common factor that underlies these apparently contradictory developments?\n翻译: <u>是否存在某种共同因素，构成这些表面上相互矛盾的发展变化的基础？</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOne idea is that teenage behavior is related to what researchers call “reward sensitivity.”\n翻译: <u>一种观点是，青少年行为与研究人员所说的“奖赏敏感性”有关。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nDecision-making always involves balancing rewards and risks, benefits and costs.\n翻译: <u>决策总是涉及在奖赏与风险、收益与成本之间进行权衡。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Reward sensitivity” measures how much reward it takes to outweigh risk.\n翻译: <u>“奖赏敏感性”衡量的是需要多大的奖赏才足以压过风险。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTeenagers are particularly sensitive to social rewards—winning the game, impressing a new friend, getting that boy to notice you.\n翻译: <u>青少年对社会性奖赏尤其敏感，比如赢得比赛、给新朋友留下深刻印象、让那个男孩注意到你。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nReward sensitivity, like prosocial behavior and risk-taking, seems to go up in adolescence and then down again as we age.\n翻译: <u>奖赏敏感性就像亲社会行为和冒险行为一样，似乎会在青春期上升，然后随着我们年龄增长再次下降。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSomehow, when you hit 30, the chance that something exciting and new will happen at that party just doesn’t seem to outweigh the effort of getting up off the couch.\n翻译: <u>不知怎么地，当你到了 30 岁时，聚会上会发生某件令人兴奋而新鲜的事情的可能性，似乎就是不足以抵过从沙发上起身的那番力气。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"},{"courseId":"english2","courseTitle":"英语二","id":"english2-2024","year":"2024","title":"2024 年英语二阅读","fileName":"2024 年英语二阅读.md","sourcePath":"/Users/ruansheng/Library/Mobile Documents/iCloud~md~obsidian/Documents/仓库/英语/真题/训练日志/英语 2/英语 2 最终版/2024 年英语二阅读.md","content":"第一篇\n\nIn her new book Cogs and Monsters: What Economics Is, and What It Should Be, Diane Coyle, an economist at Cambridge University, argues that the digital economy requires new ways of thinking about progress.\n翻译: <u>剑桥大学经济学家 Diane Coyle 在她的新书《齿轮与怪物：经济学是什么，以及它应该是什么》中主张，数字经济需要新的方式来思考进步。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Whatever we mean by the economy growing, by things getting better, the gains will have to be more evenly shared than in the recent past,” she writes.\n翻译: <u>她写道：“无论我们所说的经济增长、事情变得更好是什么意思，其收益都必须比不久前更加公平地分享。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“An economy of tech millionaires or billionaires and gig workers, with middle-income jobs undercut by automation, will not be politically sustainable.”\n翻译: <u>“一个由科技百万富翁或亿万富翁与零工劳动者构成、而中等收入工作岗位又被自动化削弱的经济体，在政治上将是不可持续的。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nImproving living standards and increasing prosperity for more people will require greater use of digital technologies to boost productivity in various sectors, including health care and construction, says Coyle.\n翻译: <u>Coyle 说，要改善生活水平并提高更多人的繁荣程度，就需要更大程度地使用数字技术来提升包括医疗保健和建筑在内的各个行业的生产率。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut people can’t be expected to embrace the changes if they’re not seeing the benefits—if they’re just seeing good jobs being destroyed.\n翻译: <u>但是，如果人们看不到这些好处，如果他们只是看到好工作正在被摧毁，就不能指望他们会接受这些变化。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn a recent interview, Coyle said she fears that tech’s inequality problem could be a roadblock to deploying AI.\n翻译: <u>在最近的一次采访中，Coyle 说，她担心科技领域的不平等问题可能会成为部署人工智能的障碍。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We’re talking about disruption,” she says.\n翻译: <u>她说：“我们谈论的是颠覆。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“These are transformative technologies that change the ways we spend our time every day, that change business models that succeed.”\n翻译: <u>“这些是变革性技术，它们改变我们每天花费时间的方式，也改变能够取得成功的商业模式。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nTo make such “tremendous changes,” she adds, you need social buy-in.\n翻译: <u>她补充说，要实现这种“巨大的变化”，你需要社会认同。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nInstead, says Coyle, resentment is simmering among many as the benefits are perceived to go to elites in a handful of prosperous cities.\n翻译: <u>Coyle 说，相反，由于人们认为收益流向了少数繁荣城市中的精英，许多人心中的怨恨正在酝酿。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAccording to the Brookings Institution, a short list of eight American cities that included San Francisco, San Jose, Boston, and Seattle had roughly 38% of all tech jobs by 2019.\n翻译: <u>根据布鲁金斯学会的数据，到 2019 年，包括旧金山、圣何塞、波士顿和西雅图在内的八个美国城市，占据了大约 38% 的全部科技工作岗位。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNew AI technologies are particularly concentrated: Brookings’s Mark Muro and Sifan Liu estimate that just 15 cities account for two-thirds of the AI assets and capabilities in the United States.\n翻译: <u>新的人工智能技术尤其集中：布鲁金斯学会的 Mark Muro 和 Sifan Liu 估计，仅 15 个城市就占有美国三分之二的人工智能资产和能力。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe dominance of a few cities in the invention and commercialization of AI means that geographical disparities in wealth will continue to soar.\n翻译: <u>少数城市在人工智能发明和商业化方面的主导地位意味着，财富上的地域差距将继续急剧扩大。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nNot only will this foster political and social unrest, but it could, as Coyle suggests, hold back the sorts of AI technologies needed for regional economies to grow.\n翻译: <u>这不仅会助长政治和社会动荡，而且正如 Coyle 所指出的，它还可能阻碍区域经济增长所需要的那类人工智能技术。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPart of the solution could lie in somehow loosening the stranglehold that Big Tech has on defining the AI agenda.\n翻译: <u>解决方案的一部分可能在于以某种方式削弱大型科技公司在界定人工智能议程方面的控制。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThat will likely take increased federal funding for research independent of the tech giants.\n翻译: <u>这很可能需要增加联邦资金，用于独立于科技巨头的研究。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nA more immediate response is to broaden our digital imaginations to conceive of AI technologies that don’t simply replace jobs but expand opportunities in the sectors that different parts of the country care most about, like health care, education, and manufacturing.\n翻译: <u>更直接的回应是拓宽我们的数字想象力，去构想那些不是简单取代工作岗位，而是在全国不同地区最关心的行业中扩大机会的人工智能技术，比如医疗保健、教育和制造业。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第二篇\n\nThe UK is facing a future construction crisis because of a failure to plant trees to produce wood, Confor has warned.\n翻译: <u>Confor 警告称，由于未能种植树木来生产木材，英国正面临未来的建筑危机。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe forestry and wood trade body has called for urgent action to reduce the country’s reliance on timber imports and provide a stable supply of wood for future generations.\n翻译: <u>这个林业和木材贸易机构呼吁采取紧急行动，以减少该国对木材进口的依赖，并为后代提供稳定的木材供应。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCurrently only 20 per cent of the UK’s wood requirement is home-grown while it remains the second-largest net importer of timber in the world.\n翻译: <u>目前，英国木材需求中只有 20% 来自本国种植，同时英国仍是世界第二大木材净进口国。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nComing at a time of fresh incentives from the UK government for landowners to grow more trees, the trade body says these don’t go far enough and fail to promote the benefits of planting them to boost timber supplies.\n翻译: <u>在英国政府为土地所有者种植更多树木提供新激励措施之际，该贸易机构表示，这些措施还远远不够，并且未能宣传植树对增加木材供应的好处。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Not only are we facing a carbon crisis now, but we will also be facing a future construction crisis because of a failure to plant trees to produce wood,” said Stuart Goodall, chief executive of Confor.\n翻译: <u>Confor 首席执行官 Stuart Goodall 说：“我们现在不仅正面临碳危机，而且由于未能种植树木来生产木材，我们还将面临未来的建筑危机。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“For decades we have not taken responsibility for investing in our domestic wood supply, leaving us exposed to fluctuating prices and fighting for future supplies of wood as global demand rises and our own supplies fall.”\n翻译: <u>“几十年来，我们一直没有承担起投资国内木材供应的责任，这使我们在价格波动面前暴露无遗，并且随着全球需求上升而我们自身供应下降，我们不得不争夺未来的木材供应。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe UK has ideal conditions for growing wood to build low-carbon homes and is a global leader in certifying that its forests are sustainably managed, Confor says.\n翻译: <u>Confor 表示，英国拥有种植木材以建造低碳住宅的理想条件，并且在认证其森林得到可持续管理方面处于全球领先地位。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile around three quarters of Scottish homes are built from Scottish timber, the use of home-grown wood in England is only around 25 per cent.\n翻译: <u>虽然大约四分之三的苏格兰住宅是用苏格兰木材建造的，但英格兰本土种植木材的使用比例仅约为 25%。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe causes of the UK’s current position are complex and range from outdated perceptions of productive forestry to the decimation of trees by grey squirrels.\n翻译: <u>英国目前处境的原因很复杂，从对生产性林业的过时看法，到灰松鼠对树木的毁灭性破坏，范围很广。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIt also encompasses significant hesitation on behalf of farmers and other landowners to invest in longer-term planting projects.\n翻译: <u>这还包括农民和其他土地所有者在投资较长期植树项目方面存在明显犹豫。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile productive tree planting can deliver real financial benefits to rural economies and contribute to the UK’s net-zero strategy, the focus of government support continues to be on food production and the rewilding and planting of native woodland solely for biodiversity.\n翻译: <u>虽然生产性植树能够为农村经济带来真实的经济收益，并为英国的净零战略作出贡献，但政府支持的重点仍然放在粮食生产，以及仅仅为了生物多样性而进行的野化恢复和本土林地种植上。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nGoodall added: “While food production and biodiversity health are clearly of critical importance, we need our land to also provide secure supplies of wood for construction, manufacturing and contribute to net zero.”\n翻译: <u>Goodall 补充说：“虽然粮食生产和生物多样性健康显然至关重要，但我们也需要我们的土地为建筑、制造业提供可靠的木材供应，并为实现净零作出贡献。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“While the UK government has stated its ambition for more tree planting, there has been little action on the ground.\n翻译: <u>“虽然英国政府已经表明了增加植树的雄心，但实地行动却很少。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nConfor is now calling for much greater impetus behind those aspirations to ensure we have enough wood to meet increasing demand.”\n翻译: <u>Confor 现在呼吁为这些愿景注入更强大的推动力，以确保我们有足够的木材来满足不断增长的需求。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第三篇\n\nOne of the biggest challenges in keeping unsafe aging drivers off the road is convincing them that it’s time to turn over the keys.\n翻译: <u>让不安全的老年驾驶者远离道路的最大挑战之一，是说服他们：是时候交出车钥匙了。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“It’s a complete life-changer” when someone stops—or is forced to stop—driving, said former risk manager Anne M.\n翻译: <u>前风险经理 Anne M. 说，当一个人停止驾驶，或者被迫停止驾驶时，“这完全会改变生活”。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMenke.\n翻译: <u>Menke。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“The American Medical Association advises physicians that ‘in situations where clear evidence of substantial driving impairment implies a strong threat to patient and public safety, and where the physician’s advice to discontinue driving privileges is ignored, it is desirable and ethical to notify the Department of Motor Vehicles,’” Menke wrote.\n翻译: <u>Menke 写道：“美国医学会告知医生，‘在有明确证据表明严重驾驶能力受损意味着对患者和公众安全构成强烈威胁，并且医生关于停止驾驶权利的建议被忽视的情况下，通知机动车管理部门是可取的，也是合乎伦理的。’”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“Some states require physicians to report, others allow but do not mandate reports, while a few consider a report a breach of confidentiality.\n翻译: <u>她建议说：“一些州要求医生报告，另一些州允许但不强制报告，而少数州则认为报告是违反保密义务。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThere could be liability and penalties if a physician does not act in accordance with state laws on reporting and confidentiality,” she counseled.\n翻译: <u>如果医生没有按照州法律中关于报告和保密的规定行事，可能会产生责任和处罚。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPart of the problem in keeping older drivers safe is that the difficulties are addressed piecemeal by different professions with different focuses, including gerontologists, highway administration officials, automotive engineers and others, said gerontologist Elizabeth Dugan.\n翻译: <u>老年学家 Elizabeth Dugan 说，保障老年驾驶者安全的问题部分在于，这些困难是由关注点不同的不同职业群体零散处理的，包括老年学家、公路管理官员、汽车工程师以及其他人。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“There’s not a National Institute of Older Driver Studies,” she said.\n翻译: <u>她说：“并不存在一个全国老年驾驶者研究所。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“We need better evidence on what makes drivers unsafe” and what can help, said Dugan.\n翻译: <u>Dugan 说：“我们需要更好的证据来说明什么会使驾驶者变得不安全”，以及什么能够提供帮助。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nOne thing that does seem to work is requiring drivers to report in person for license renewal.\n翻译: <u>似乎确实有效的一件事，是要求驾驶者亲自到场办理驾照续期。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMandatory in-person renewal was associated with a 31 per cent reduction in fatal crashes involving drivers 85 or older, according to one study.\n翻译: <u>根据一项研究，强制亲自办理续期与涉及85岁或以上驾驶者的致命车祸减少31%有关。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPassing vision tests also produced a similar decline in fatal crashes for those drivers, although there appeared to be no benefit from combining the two.\n翻译: <u>通过视力测试也使这些驾驶者的致命车祸出现类似下降，尽管把这两项结合起来似乎没有额外益处。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nMany older drivers don’t see eye doctors or can’t afford to.\n翻译: <u>许多老年驾驶者不去看眼科医生，或者负担不起费用。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nPrimary care providers have their hands full and may not be able to follow through with patients who have trouble driving because they can’t turn their heads or remember where they are going—or have gotten shorter and haven’t changed their seat settings sufficiently to reach car pedals easily.\n翻译: <u>初级保健提供者已经忙得不可开交，可能无法继续跟进那些驾驶有困难的患者；这些困难可能是因为他们无法转头，或记不住自己要去哪里，或者他们身高变矮了，却没有充分调整座椅设置，以便轻松够到汽车踏板。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs long as there are other cars on the roads, self-driving cars won’t solve the problems of crashes, said Dugan.\n翻译: <u>Dugan 说，只要道路上还有其他汽车，自动驾驶汽车就无法解决车祸问题。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAvoiding dangers posed by all those human drivers would require too many algorithms, she said.\n翻译: <u>她说，要避开所有那些人类驾驶者造成的危险，将需要太多算法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nBut we need to do more to improve safety, said Dugan.\n翻译: <u>但 Dugan 说，我们需要做更多事情来提高安全性。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n“If we’re going to have 100-year lives, we need cars that a 90-year-old can drive comfortably.\n翻译: <u>“如果我们将拥有百岁人生，我们就需要90岁老人也能舒适驾驶的汽车。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\n第四篇\n\nIf you look at the apps on your phone, chances are you have at least one related to your health—and probably several.\n翻译: <u>如果你看看手机上的应用程序，很可能你至少有一个与你的健康有关，而且很可能有好几个。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhether it is a mental health app, a fitness tracker, a connected health device or something else, many of us are taking advantage of this technology to keep better track of our health in some shape or form.\n翻译: <u>无论是心理健康应用、健身追踪器、联网健康设备，还是其他东西，我们中的许多人都在利用这项技术，以某种形式更好地追踪自己的健康状况。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nRecent research from the Organization for the Review of Care and Health Applications found that 350,000 health apps were available on the market, 90,000 of which launched in 2020 alone.\n翻译: <u>来自护理与健康应用审查组织的最新研究发现，市场上有35万个健康应用程序，其中仅2020年就推出了9万个。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile these apps have a great deal to offer, it is not always clear how the personal information we input is collected, safeguarded and shared online.\n翻译: <u>尽管这些应用程序能提供很多东西，但我们输入的个人信息是如何被收集、保护并在网上共享的，并不总是清楚。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nExisting health privacy law, such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, is primarily focused on the way hospitals, doctors’ offices, clinics and insurance companies store health records online.\n翻译: <u>现有的健康隐私法律，例如《健康保险流通与责任法案》，主要关注医院、医生办公室、诊所和保险公司在线存储健康记录的方式。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe health information these apps and health data tracking wearables are collecting typically does not receive the same legal protections.\n翻译: <u>这些应用程序以及追踪健康数据的可穿戴设备所收集的健康信息，通常得不到同等的法律保护。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWithout additional protections in place, companies may share (and potentially monetize) personal health information in a way consumers may not have authorized or anticipated.\n翻译: <u>如果没有额外保护措施，公司可能会以消费者未曾授权或预料到的方式共享并可能从个人健康信息中获利。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nIn 2021, Flo Health faced a Federal Trade Commission (FTC) investigation.\n翻译: <u>2021年，Flo Health 面临联邦贸易委员会（FTC）的一项调查。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nThe FTC alleged in a complaint that “despite express privacy claims, the company took control of users’ sensitive fertility data and shared it with third parties.”\n翻译: <u>FTC 在一份投诉中称，“尽管作出了明确的隐私声明，该公司仍控制了用户敏感的生育数据，并将其分享给第三方。”</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nFlo Health and the FTC settled the matter with a Consent Order requiring the company to get app users’ express affirmative consent before sharing their health information as well as to instruct the third parties to delete the data they had obtained.\n翻译: <u>Flo Health 与 FTC 通过一项同意令解决了此事，该同意令要求该公司在分享用户健康信息之前获得应用用户明确的肯定同意，并指示第三方删除其已经获得的数据。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nSection 5 of the FTC Act empowers the FTC to initiate enforcement action against unfair or deceptive acts, meaning the FTC can only act after the fact if a company’s privacy practices are misleading or cause unjustified consumer harm.\n翻译: <u>《联邦贸易委员会法》第5条授权 FTC 对不公平或欺骗性行为发起执法行动，这意味着，如果一家公司的隐私做法具有误导性或造成不正当的消费者损害，FTC 只能在事后采取行动。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nWhile the FTC is doing what it can to ensure apps are keeping their promises to consumers around the handling of their sensitive health information, the rate at which these health apps are hitting the market demonstrates just how immense of a challenge this is.\n翻译: <u>尽管 FTC 正在尽其所能，确保应用程序在处理消费者敏感健康信息方面信守承诺，但这些健康应用进入市场的速度表明，这项挑战是多么巨大。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nAs to the prospects for federal legislation, commentators suggest that comprehensive federal privacy legislation seems unlikely in the short term.\n翻译: <u>至于联邦立法的前景，评论人士认为，全面的联邦隐私立法在短期内似乎不太可能实现。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nStates have begun implementing their own solutions to shore up protections for consumer-generated health data.\n翻译: <u>各州已经开始实施自己的解决方案，以加强对消费者生成的健康数据的保护。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nCalifornia has been at the forefront of state privacy efforts with the California Consumer Privacy Act of 2018.\n翻译: <u>加利福尼亚州一直处于州级隐私保护努力的前沿，推出了2018年的《加利福尼亚消费者隐私法》。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n\nVirginia, Colorado and Utah have also recently passed state consumer data privacy legislation.\n翻译: <u>弗吉尼亚州、科罗拉多州和犹他州最近也通过了州级消费者数据隐私立法。</u>\n\n()\n\n---\n"}]);
